<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three inmates, four guards injured in prison fire  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOMERS, Conn. (AP) -- Three inmates, including a man accused of
killing an East Hartford police officer, were injured Wednesday
night in a fire at the Northern Correctional Institution.
</P>
<P>
   The fire occurred at about 7:45 p.m. in a unit of the
maximum-security prison that houses about 50 inmates, including the
six on Connecticut's death row, said Christina Polce, a Correction
Department spokeswoman. No death row inmates were injured.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the fire had not been determined Wednesday, though
state police said it was reported as a mattress fire.
</P>
<P>
   The injured included Alex Sostre, who is awaiting trial on
capital felony charges in the Jan. 23, 1999 shooting of East
Hartford Police officer Brian Aselton. Sostre suffered smoke
inhalation, but was expected to be returned to the prison, said
Capt. Heather Ziemba, a spokeswoman for the Department of
Correction.
</P>
<P>
   Sostre's cellmate, identified as Pedro Poupart, suffered minor
burns and was expected to remain hospitalized overnight, Ziemba
said. A third inmate, identified as Julio Gomez, suffered minor
smoke inhalation as was being returned to Northern, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Johnson Memorial Hospital in Stafford said four
guards also were treated for smoke inhalation. But prison officials
said the guards were not injured, and went to the hospital only to
accompany the prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The housing unit, known as One East, is reserved for inmates
with behavioral problems. Inmates in the unit are locked in their
cells 23 hours a day, Ziemba said. The residents were evacuated to
another section of the prison after the fire, but were being
returned to their cells late Wednesday night, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''At no time was public safety, or the security of the facility
jeopardized,'' Polce said.
</P>
<P>
   The prison houses over 430 of Connecticut's worst offenders.
Polce said the facility's perimeter was ''secured and reinforced''
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The community was notified through a beeper system that
activates in times of emergency, Polce said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
