<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan OK With UN Decision on Israel  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Israel's inclusion in a U.N. regional
group will rectify a decades-old anomaly and give Israel ''equal
footing'' in the United Nations, Secretary-General Kofi Annan said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''This decision is particularly welcome at a time when all
people of goodwill are hoping for early and decisive progress in
the Middle East peace process,'' Annan said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, the U.N. regional group of European, North American
and other countries invited Israel to become a temporary member,
with some strings, ending nearly 50 years of Israeli isolation at
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Under U.N. rules, regional groups decide who fills the 10
rotating seats on the Security Council and other key U.N. committee
assignments. But Arab nations repeatedly blocked Israel's admission
to the regional group where it belonged geographically, making it
the lone country prevented from bidding for committee seats.
</P>
<P>
   The United States lobbied for years to get Israel accepted into
the Western European group, saying it was unfair that Israel had
been banned from participating fully in the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Annan said he was pleased that Israel had been
invited to join the European group.
</P>
<P>
   ''It should pave the way for Israel to participate on an equal
footing with other nations in the main organs of the United
Nations,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-01-00 0018 </TRAILER>
