<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramseys, Ex-Lead Detective Clash  </HEADLINE>
By P. SOLOMON BANDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- The parents of slain beauty queen JonBenet Ramsey
have offered to travel to Boulder along with their private
investigators to lay out their theory that a pedophile killed their
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   John and Patsy Ramsey made their offer on ''Larry King Live''
Wednesday during an argument that escalated to shouting and
finger-pointing with Steve Thomas, a former Boulder police
detective who helped lead the investigation into their daughter's
death.
</P>
<P>
   JonBenet, 6, was found beaten and strangled Dec. 26, 1996, in
the basement of the Ramseys' former home in Boulder.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here's what we've laid on the table,'' John Ramsey said. ''We
have told Chief (Mark) Beckner that we need them to help find this
killer. ... We've had investigators, seasoned investigators,
collectively with over 500 homicides under their belt, who have
been working on this case day in and day out. They have questions,
they have information.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckner sent the Ramseys a letter May 10 asking them to meet
with detectives to discuss new evidence. The couple told Beckner
they were not willing to submit to an ''interrogation.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckner could not be immediately reached by phone for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey lawyer L. Lin Wood said from his Atlanta-area home the
Ramseys' offer has not been formally submitted to Beckner.
</P>
<P>
   John Ramsey also said he plans to sue Thomas over his book,
''JonBenet: Inside the JonBenet Ramsey Murder Investigation,'' in
which Thomas theorizes that Patsy Ramsey killed her daughter. ''A
dead child, your child, was found in your basement and you could
not come up with a satisfactory explanation,'' Thomas told the
Ramseys while defending his book.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wish I had been (arrested) and we would have had a free and
fair trial,'' Patsy Ramsey said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, who now works as a carpenter, resigned in August 1998
and accused the Boulder district attorney of being compromised,
refusing to issue search warrants and refusing to cooperate with
police.
</P>
<P>
   Boulder authorities have said they Ramseys are under ''an
umbrella of suspicion.'' A 13-month grand jury investigation
convened in October without an indictment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
