<DOCNO> APW20000601.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prison Scraps Telemarketing Program  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT GEHRKE
<TEXT>
<P>
   MURRAY, Utah (AP) -- The Utah prison system is dropping its
inmate telemarketing center program after an inmate sent three
flirtatious letters, two of them to teen-age girls.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Corrections Executive Director Pete Haun said
Wednesday the prison can't provide enough supervision to guarantee
that inmates don't make inappropriate comments during the phone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe that no one's safety was compromised in these
matters, but we cannot tolerate situations where the community
feels at risk due to this kind of inappropriate conduct,'' Haun
said.
</P>
<P>
   Disbanding the call center will mean the loss of about 130
inmate jobs, Haun said.
</P>
<P>
   Utah Correctional Industries is a $14 million program designed
to teach inmates job skills by putting them to work doing tasks
such as building furniture, printing state documents and entering
data in computers.
</P>
<P>
   Haun said prison officials have been taking a careful look at
security at the call center for 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   The concerns were highlighted by three letters sent by inmate
David Hunsaker, one to a 15-year-old girl in Texas, one to a
14-year-old Logan girl, and one to a Logan woman. The letters
offered personal information, then tried to arrange a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The call center will remain open for 90 days so the prison
system can fulfill its contracts with the four entities it handles
calls for. The system has contracts with SandStar Family
Entertainment, Inmark and the Utah Travel Council and Utah
Department of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Inmates in the program get paid between $5.50 and $7 an hour for
the private contracts, but just 60 to 80 cents per hour on the
state programs.
</P>
<P>
   Prison systems in other states have had to end similar work
programs because of abuse, according to a report released last year
by the General Accounting Office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-01-00 0022 </TRAILER>
