<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No New Trial for Death-Row Inmate  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER HOLLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- A man spared from execution by the
last-minute confession of a traveling companion should not get a
new trial in the killing of a South Carolina Highway Patrol
trooper, a judge said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Charles Johnson, 37, of Morehead City, N.C., avoided
execution in October when his one-time traveling companion Connie
Sue Hess said she was the one who pulled the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe Connie Sue Hess will say almost anything, knowing it
to be untrue, for reasons satisfactory to her, but a mystery to the
rest of us,'' Circuit Judge William Keesley wrote. ''Her
understanding of the consequences of her lies is below being
described as childlike.''
</P>
<P>
   A week before Johnson was to die, Hess signed a sworn statement
confessing to the 1985 killing of Trooper Bruce K. Smalls.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court granted Johnson a stay of execution and
assigned Keesley to review the case and determine the credibility
of Hess, who suffers from a borderline personality disorder and
lives in a supervised apartment complex for the mentally ill in
Norfolk, Neb.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers will have a chance to respond to Keesley's
recommendation before the justices determine the next step.
Attorney General Charlie Condon said he would have to wait 15 days
before he could seek to have Johnson's execution rescheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ''Richard Charles Johnson has had every benefit of every
doubt,'' Condon said. ''It is now time for justice to be served.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's lawyer, John Blume, did not immediately return calls
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Hess' lawyer, Mark Johnson, said he did not anticipate any
criminal charges against his client.
</P>
<P>
   The trooper was shot after pulling over a motor home on I-95
near Hardeeville, near the Georgia line. The .38-caliber revolver
used to kill Smalls was found in a nearby ditch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-01-00 0023 </TRAILER>
