<DOCNO> APW20000601.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Helton Lifts Colo. Into Contention  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN MOSSMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Terrorizing opposing pitching with a .421 average,
Todd Helton has lifted the Colorado Rockies onto his muscular
shoulders, assuming a leadership role the club has been lacking.
</P>
<P>
   Since Larry Walker has been sidelined with an injured throwing
elbow, Helton has gone 25-for-51 (.490).
</P>
<P>
   In his last 19 games, he is 32-for-67 (.478) with seven doubles,
seven home runs and 19 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   His .421 average leads the majors by a wide margin, and he also
has 17 homers and 51 RBIs. His .825 slugging percentage trails only
Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday, Helton hit two homers and drove in four runs,
including a walkoff homer in the bottom of the ninth in a 7-6
victory over Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Houston pitchers ignored manager Larry Dierker's
instructions to pitch around Helton, and the first baseman hit two
homers, including the game-winner in the eighth inning in an 8-7
win.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, they listened -- but Helton still hurt them. With
the bases loaded in the eighth, Yorkis Perez pitched carefully to
Helton, walking him on a 3-2 pitch and forcing in the go-ahead run
in Colorado's 10-7 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Helton walked three times in the game, hitting a double and a
sacrifice fly in his other two at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd rather have walked him all five times,'' Dierker said. ''I
didn't want to walk him with the bases loaded, but one run is less
than we would have done if we threw him one down the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Helton walked three more times, going 1-for-2 in
Colorado's 8-6 win.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of respect usually is reserved for established stars
like Barry Bonds and Ken Griffey Jr., but Helton shrugs off any
comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sure they weren't pitching around me on that last
at-bat,'' Helton said Tuesday. ''He threw some pretty tough
pitches, but I've been seeing the ball good, and I was lucky enough
to lay off them.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite losing Walker -- the 1997 NL MVP and two-time defending
NL batting champion -- the Rockies have won 12 of their last 16 to
move within four games of NL West-leading Arizona, reviving hopes
that the Rockies might again be a playoff contender.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other player, Helton is responsible for that
surge.
</P>
<P>
   Helton, 26, doesn't like talking about himself, but others can't
say enough about him.
</P>
<P>
   ''This kid is the real deal,'' Rockies manager Buddy Bell said
Wednesday. ''He cares. He gets after it every day. I never doubted
his ability to lead. After meeting him in spring training, I was
impressed. He's a very important guy in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody always knew he could hit. He has the makeup and work
ethic to be a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies' first-round selection in the 1995 amateur draft,
Helton was projected to be a line-drive hitter who would ''wear out
the gaps in Coors Field,'' according to then-general manager Bob
Gebhard. He has far exceeded those expectations, especially in
terms of power.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a special person, a special athlete,'' Rockies hitting
coach Clint Hurdle said. ''And he's a quick learner.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first full season in the majors in 1998, he hit .315 with
25 homers and 97 RBIs. Last year he hit .320 with 35 homers and 113
RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, he is on pace to hit 56 homers.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Cubs manager Don Baylor managed the Rockies when Helton
broke into the majors in 1997 and when he finished runnerup in NL
Rookie of the Year voting in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''I envisioned him being a .300 hitter, but never one to hit
.400,'' Baylor said during a recent Cubs visit to Coors Field.
''Right now, he reminds me of Don Mattingly. He uses the whole
field.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we first got him, I advised our minor-league instructors
not to mess with his swing. I didn't want them to turn him into a
pull hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Helton, a former quarterback at the University of Tennessee,
doesn't go into prolonged slumps. He started the current homestand
0-for-13, then promptly went 13-for-17.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two years, the left-handed-hitting Helton has
proved he could hit left-handed pitching as well as hit on the
road. This season, he is hitting .392 against lefties. While
hitting .500 at home, he is hitting a respectable .333 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there were any holes in Helton's game, Dierker smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's not very fast,'' he said. ''He is a special hitter right
now. He may not hit as well all year, but the way he is hitting
right now, if you don't have a really sharp pitcher on the mound,
you are better off walking him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
