<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panel reviews EPA on PCB risk in Hudson  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL HILL
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) -- An independent panel of experts
agreed with federal researchers who warned of health risks from
eating upper Hudson River fish, according to the Environmental
Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The peer review concluded Wednesday was among the many steps the
federal EPA must take before deciding whether to order a dredging
of the upper Hudson. The agency is scheduled to make its proposal
in December.
</P>
<P>
   The six-member peer panel reviewed findings released by the EPA
last summer that claimed risks to people eating PCB-contaminated
fish from the upper Hudson River are many times higher than
acceptable levels.
</P>
<P>
   The panel unanimously agreed that cancer risks and non-cancer
health hazards from eating the contaminated fish in that area are
above ''levels of concern,'' said EPA Hudson River project manager
Alison Hess.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're very pleased with the outcome of the peer review,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Panel members said the EPA's data and conclusions appeared
sound, but called for some revisions. For instance, they suggested
the inclusion of guidelines for evaluating the effects of PCBs on
pregnant and lactating women. And panel members said more detailed
data needed to be provided on the range of risks to human health.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the six panel members called for major revisions.
</P>
<P>
   Hess said the recommended revisions would require additional
analysis of data the EPA already has. She said the EPA would
consider all the recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Hess did not expect the EPA's December proposal deadline to be
delayed.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for General Electric, which opposes dredging, said
the peer reviewers uncovered the same flaws in the EPA's health
analysis that GE had found earlier. Mark Behan said that without
''substantial changes'' in the report, the EPA's health risk
assessment would not be scientifically defensible.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are obliged to implement the recommendations,'' Behan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pollution from GE factories on the Hudson is largely blamed for
the PCB -- or polychlorinated biphenyl -- content in the river. The
substance, used as insulating material in transformers and other
electrical equipment, was banned by the federal government in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   If a dredging is ordered, General Electric could be forced to
spend billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The company released it own study last year showing the river is
cleaning up naturally. More recently it launched an advertising
campaign noting that more than 50 local governments have passed
resolutions opposing dredging and landfilling.
</P>
<P>
   EPA spokeswoman Ann Rychlenski said the panel's findings are
significant in light of GE's ''disinformation campaign.'' Behan
said the comment was ''outrageous'' and dismissive of public
opinion in the area.
</P>
<P>
   A final peer review panel looking over the EPA's ecological risk
assessment of the river is set to work today and Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-01-00 0055 </TRAILER>
