<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cornell astronomers say Eros is relic of solar system's birth  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) --An unexpected ''snapshot'' produced by a
powerful solar flare has given scientists evidence that the
asteroid Eros is a primitive relic from the dawn of the solar
system.
</P>
<P>
   The findings from NASA's NEAR Shoemaker spacecraft revealed to
scientists for the first time the chemical composition of an
asteroid, said Steven Squyres, a Cornell astronomy professor and
one of the scientists who analyzed the ''snapshot.''
</P>
<P>
   Orbiting 100 million miles from Earth, the 21-mile-long Eros
appears to have escaped heating and melting and remained largely
unchanged since the initial formation of the solar system from a
cloud of gas and dust, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''By looking at an asteroid like Eros, we are looking at one of
the solar system's basic building blocks,'' Squyres said.
</P>
<P>
   Squyres' team announced its discovery Tuesday at a meeting of
the American Geophysical Union in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The event that led to the surprise findings was a powerful solar
flare on May 4. For 30 minutes, X-rays produced by the solar
explosion washed over the asteroid, producing a ''glow'' called
X-ray fluorescence, Squyres said.
</P>
<P>
   That allowed scientists to record the different elements on the
asteroid's surface ''glowing'' at different wavelengths, he said.
The snapshot covered an area about 3.7 miles across. Scientists
found elements of magnesium, silicon and aluminum.
</P>
<P>
   ''In Eros, we are seeing the ratios of silicon, magnesium and
aluminum ... all basically preserved as they were in the solar
nebula, and nothing much has happened since ... so we are seeing
into the very distant past,'' Squyres said.
</P>
<P>
   Eros is classified as an S-type asteroid, the most common
classification. Squyres said the latest evidence provides ''a key
piece of information suggesting that many other S asteroids also
might show this primitive characteristic.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he cautioned, that the findings are just the first and
from only a small area of Eros and that asteroids remained
''puzzling and bizarre'' objects.
</P>
<P>
   Over the coming months, NEAR -- Near Earth Asteroid Rendezvous --
will provide scientists with X-ray readings from the entire body of
Eros as part of its exploration mission. Presently, NEAR is
orbiting about 31 miles above Eros. On July 7, the spacecraft will
begin a gradual descent to an orbit just 22 miles above the
asteroid's surface.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-01-00 0056 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000601.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oz museum quest a muddled mess  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CHITTENANGO, N.Y. (AP) -- The yellow brick road has turned into a
brick wall for a local group trying to build a museum to honor Oz
author and native son L. Frank Baum.
</P>
<P>
   The Chittenango Foundation has fallen at least six months behind
in its mortgage payment on a four-acre site where the Baum family
once lived. It is selling the land for half of what it paid for it
to help pay off debts. After two decades, the dream of a permanent
museum is fading.
</P>
<P>
   The local foundation has been plagued by other problems, too,
including a failure to file annual reports required by state and
federal laws.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't see anything that's happened that we should be ashamed
of,'' said Curt Tobin, who was the organization's president from
1992 until 1997. ''We're not as far along as we'd like, I
suppose.''
</P>
<P>
   For 21 years, the all-volunteer group has organized OzFest to
try to raise money for a museum. A 450-square-foot temporary museum
is set up in the rear of the local Masonic Temple.
</P>
<P>
   The festival, which started out as a ''birthday'' party at the
village library, now draws about 25,000 people -- about five times
the village's population. This year's OzFest runs from Thursday
through Sunday and includes food, music, a parade and visits by a
handful of the original ''munchkins'' from the classic 1939 movie
''The Wizard of Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   While attendance has grown, profits have not. Chittenango
Foundation officials said OzFest costs about $40,000 to stage and
the foundation barely brings in enough each year to meet expenses.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the foundation spent $74,000 for the Baum family site,
intending to erect a museum there. It borrowed $61,000 from two
local businessman, a loan it has yet to repay. The foundation has
spent more than $98,000 in down payments, principal, interest and
taxes on the land, said Foundation President Charles Goldsmith.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are doing poorly because we put so much money into the
land,'' Goldsmith said. ''The previous leadership bought the land
and we're stuck with it. We were foolish the way some of the money
was spent.''
</P>
<P>
   Making matters worse, there is some evidence that the Baum site
may actually have been on the other side of the road from the
foundation's property.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation's financial failings also have cost it in other
ways.
</P>
<P>
   State legislators set aside $25,000 for the museum in the past
three budgets but the foundation never submitted the proper
paperwork to collect the money. The money will soon be lost if the
foundation doesn't come forward, said Allen James, a spokesman for
the state Parks Department.
</P>
<P>
   Current foundation officials characterize their problems as the
legacy of the previous leadership. They said they are turning the
corner and are not quite ready to give up their dream of a
permanent museum. Last year, OzFest cleared about $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers also are working out details to donate the Masonic
Temple to the foundation as a permanent museum. If that fails,
foundation members said they will look for another site.
</P>
<P>
   Should it happen, the L. Frank Baum-Oz Museum would feature the
writings of Baum, who was born in Chittenango in 1856 and moved to
Syracuse when he was 4 years old.
</P>
<P>
   The first of Baum's 14 Oz books was published in 1900 and
quickly became a best seller. In 1939, Hollywood turned the first
book, ''The Wonderful Wizard of Oz,'' into one of the most popular
movies of all time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-01-00 0056 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
