<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Appellate Court reverses lower court decision, effectively ousting Essenberg </HEADLINE>
By LYNN BREZOSKY
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY -- The Independence Party State Committee was within its
power to oust party Chairman Jack Essenberg and five members of his
executive committee in February, an appellate court ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's decision, a reversal of an earlier decision by a
lower court, places Frank MacKay of Suffolk County in the
leadership position for Monday's state convention in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday the party is expected to nominate its choice for the
nationally watched U.S. Senate race pitting first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton against U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio. There is also a
possibility that Independence Party convention delegates could
authorize a Sept. 12 primary featuring both candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In April, State Supreme Court Justice Bernard Malone ruled that
since Essenberg did not set the agenda for the Feb. 4 meeting
resulting in his ouster, that removal was null and void.
</P>
<P>
   After Essenberg walked out of that meeting, committee members
voted to remove Essenberg and replace him with MacKay of North
Babylon, Long Island. Essenberg attorney Thomas Spargo appealed to
Malone, who stayed the action of the committee and ordered
Essenberg be restored as chair.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was fueled by a rivalry between factions of the
Independence Party, which is New York state's version of the
national Reform Party. One faction was led by Essenberg and the
other by leftist activist Lenora Fulani.
</P>
<P>
   Fulani's unconventional backing of conservative Pat Buchanan for
the party's presidential nomination brought her in opposition to
Essenberg, who at the time favored Donald Trump for the party's
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Laureen Oliver of Rochester, party secretary and founder, touted
the latest ruling, saying it would allow the party to remove
leaders who believe the party should be an ''appendix'' of larger
state parties.
</P>
<P>
   She said Essenberg ''wanted to be another Mike Long or another
Raymond Harding,'' referring respectively to leaders of the state
Conservative and Liberal parties. ''It won't work. We're too
demographically spread,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Essenberg, reached Wednesday night, said he was ''obviously
disappointed'' with the ruling and that he would bring the matter
to the state Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll deal with it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A Fulani spokeswoman could not be reached for comment Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The attraction of third-party nominations is strong in New York.
Unlike other states, New York allows major party candidates to also
run on third-party ballot lines and combine their vote totals.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Republican George Pataki beat Democratic incumbent
Mario Cuomo in the governor's race on the strength of the
Conservative Party vote.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the line brought more than 109,000 extra votes to
Democrat Charles Schumer as he beat Republican incumbent Alfonse
D'Amato in the U.S. Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Independence Party became New York's third
largest political party. As of March 1, it had more than 172,471
members. The Conservative Party fell into fourth place with 171,496
members. Both are dwarfed by the Democratic (4.96 million members)
and the Republican (3.09 million members) parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-01-00 0056 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000601.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers interested in Maine's approach to drug costs  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER JORDAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Pharmaceutical industry representatives
argued with state senators Wednesday who said people in New York
and other states pay unnecessarily high prices compared to those in
other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Marchi, a Staten Island Republican, has introduced a
bill requiring that drugs not be sold in New York priced higher
than in any other part of the world. He's also suggesting that New
York form a compact with other states setting price requirements at
the lowest prices available in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our interest goes far beyond senior citizens,'' Marchi said
during a public hearing Wednesday. ''This would affect every single
individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Marchi said prices in this country are more than 50 percent more
than in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Marjorie Powell, assistant general counsel for Pharmaceutical
Research and Manufacturers of America, and a colleague had a few
testy exchanges with Marchi's colleagues during the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ''Coverage rather than price controls,'' she said, adding that
insurers have ''frankly been quite successful'' in negotiating drug
prices for patients and that the system should continue without
state involvement.
</P>
<P>
   One of the industry's arguments is that research, development
and availability of new drugs could suffer if manufacturers are
forced to reduce prices.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. George Maziarz, R-Niagara Falls, called that
''disingenuous'' considering all the money drug makers spend on
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers were visibly more interested in remarks by a
legislator from Maine, which is the first state to agree to use its
bargaining power to negotiate prices of prescription medicine for
people without coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Maine's legislation had bipartisan support, Maine Sen. Chellie
Pingree said.
</P>
<P>
   While she said she would support federal price controls,
''Unfortunately they have yet to do that and we continue to pay the
bills.''
</P>
<P>
   Pingree, majority leader of the Maine state Senate, said the
industry's 17 percent profit margin is higher than any other
business and that drug makers spend $24 billion on research and
development while making $26 billion in profits annually.
</P>
<P>
   Pingree said she's been asked to testify in other states, an
indication of a national concern over drug prices.
</P>
<P>
   During the hearing, which only invited speakers attended, Alan
Sagar, a Boston University professor of health services, testified
that if prescriptions were more affordable, drug companies would
still make money because more drugs would be purchased.
</P>
<P>
   He said Marchi's bill would help more people get the drugs they
need.
</P>
<P>
   Sagar presented a study saying that, not including the U.S.
total, New York state is fifth in the world in health care spending
-- after Japan, Germany, California and France. It spends $553
million on drugs. An estimated 4.7 million residents -- 26 percent --
have no drug coverage through insurance, he said. If price controls
were used, people in the state would pay $4.9 billion, 35.8 percent
less than this year's estimated $7.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki's office said he would ''take a look'' at
Marchi's legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver has said prescription prices
need to be acted on before the legislative session ends in June,
but has not committed to support Marchi's bill.
</P>
<P>
   New York's Catholic Conference supports the bill as does New
York's AFL-CIO chapter. The Seniors Coalition and the Pharmacists
Society of the State of New York oppose it. The Health Care
Association of New York prefers imports of cheaper drugs from other
countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-01-00 0056 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000601.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giants 10, Phillies 4  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Barry Bonds hit his 465th career home run
and Ellis Burks homered in his 35th major league ballpark as the
San Francisco Giants completed a three-game sweep of the
Philadelphia Phillies with a 10-4 victory Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Martinez, filling in at shortstop for the injured Rich
Aurilia, homered and drove in three runs as the Giants won their
eighth straight against the Phillies dating to last year.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds' homer tied him with Dave Winfield for 20th on the career
list. Burks' first homer at Pac Bell Ballpark gave him home runs in
35 major league stadiums. Only Mark McGwire and Fred McGriff have
homered in more ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Gardner (4-2) allowed four runs and seven hits in six
innings. He struck out three and didn't walk a batter to win
consecutive starts for the first time since Aug. 14 and 19, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Byrd (1-5) gave up seven runs and 10 hits, walked one and
struck out three as he lost his third straight. It was also his
first career loss to the Giants in four decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Gant hit his second homer in as many days for the Phillies,
who have lost five of their last seven.
</P>
<P>
   Gant's eighth home run of the season on a 1-1 pitch from Gardner
gave the Phillies a 1-0 lead in the first.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds hit a 1-0 pitch from Byrd into the center-field bleachers
for his 20th of the season, and his first since May 25.
</P>
<P>
   Burks' homer, a two-run shot into the left-field bleachers, gave
the Giants a 3-1 lead in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's Kevin Jordan, playing in place of injured third
baseman Scott Rolen, hit his first homer of the season to cut the
Giants' lead to 5-4 in the sixth. Brian Hunter added an RBI single
in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's homer came off Byrd, who faced one more batter before
being replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Benard also drove in a run for the Giants in the fourth
and added a two-run single in the ninth off Jeff Brantley, who gave
up three runs in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Aurilia got the night off after straining his left
hamstring Tuesday. He's scheduled for further evaluation Thursday.
... Phillies LHP Scott Aldred will have his left shoulder examined
in Philadelphia on Thursday by team doctor Michael Ciccotti. He
missed his second game as a result of the injury suffered Monday.
... The Phillies have not won a series against the Giants in the
last 11. ... The Phillies were 11-7 in interleague play last year,
including a 2-1 record against the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
