<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss To Force Back Kosovo Refugees  </HEADLINE>
By CLARE NULLIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) -- The air at the Cafe Prishtina is thick with smoke
and anxiety as Kosovo Albanian refugees struggle with a harsh
choice: return home or be kicked out.
</P>
<P>
   With the deadline for departure having expired on Wednesday,
Swiss authorities are preparing in the coming months to deport
10,500 Kosovars -- 500 in June alone -- who have outstayed their
welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland took in tens of thousands of Kosovo war refugees
last year. And now it is in a hurry for them to leave, despite
warnings by U.N. officials that the shattered Yugoslav province
can't cope.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't go home as I haven't got a home,'' insists Bislim
Hojzeaj, nervously pulling at a cigarette as he seeks legal advice
at Geneva's Popular Albanian University, a cheerless factory-like
building opposite the city's soccer stadium. ''I don't know what
I'm going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hojzeaj says he arrived in Switzerland in 1979 and labored on
building sites until he suffered a leg injury in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   He was expelled in 1996 because he had no valid work permit, but
returned in 1998 because of ethnic tensions in Kosovo and
increasing pains in his right leg.
</P>
<P>
   Aged beyond his 47 years by work and worry, Hojzeaj hopes he
will be allowed to stay on medical grounds, arguing he and his wife
both need treatment they can't obtain in Kosovo. His children, aged
18, 14, 6 and 2, were all born in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   As rumors of police raids swirl through the university canteen --
named after Kosovo's regional capital -- the climate of suspicion is
such that Hojzeaj is one of the few willing to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   But he is wary as he writes the spelling of his name for a
reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ''This isn't a signature. I'm not signing to anything,'' he
repeats, reflecting widespread comments by ethnic Albanians that
the Swiss pressured them into signing their return forms.
</P>
<P>
   Since the middle of last year, more than 32,000 ethnic Albanians
have either returned home or registered to do so under a Swiss
government program that included cash handouts of up to $1,176 per
adult and building materials upon arrival in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The figures include people who fled both before and during the
fighting last year between Yugoslav forces and ethnic Albanian
rebels that led to NATO intervention and the deployment of
international peacekeepers in Kosovo, a province of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The top U.N. official in Kosovo, Bernard Kouchner, praised
Switzerland on Wednesday as one of the ''rare'' countries that
opened its doors wide. But he pleaded for extra time.
</P>
<P>
   ''I ask you please to be reasonable,'' Kouchner said during a
brief visit here. ''It's a real burden for Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Minister Ruth Metzler has refused to delay the
expulsions, under pressure from center-right parties and from the
widespread public perception of ethnic Albanians as petty criminals
and drug-traffickers. But she says the action will be gradual.
</P>
<P>
   ''There won't be police in front of the door of all Kosovars on
June 1,'' she said in a recent newspaper interview, stressing that
police will try to avoid using force.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, officials are vague on how they will persuade desperate
people to comply.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities estimate that of the 10,500 due to be deported,
about one half will ''disappear'' to other countries or go
underground in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Mejreme Priakaj said she wouldn't dare risk expulsion and that
it was impossible for her whole family to hide from authorities. So
the family reluctantly signed up to go back to Kosovo even though
their house in a village near Pec has been destroyed and her
husband -- a miner -- has no chance of work.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't want the children to be forced out of the house for a
second time,'' she said shuddering at the memories of the flight
last year. Her 16-year-old daughter Domika and 12-year-old son
Defrim still wake with nightmares, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the trauma, the children are flourishing. A report by
Domika's teacher describes the girl as ''a pupil who never ceases
to amaze us by her intelligence and maturity,'' and it pleads for
her to be allowed to continue her studies ''in the best possible
conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Priakaj family are considered lucky. Because their children
are all still at school, they can stay in Switzerland until
mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   Their attic apartment is cramped and stuffy, Priakaj said, but
it's better than the nuclear bunker that was ''home'' for their
first six months as Swiss authorities struggled to find shelter for
the new arrivals. And the family manages to survive on Swiss
monthly handouts of $882.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other Kosovo Albanians, the Priakaj family would like
to go back at some stage. But they believe the Swiss moves are
premature.
</P>
<P>
   ''I agree that our future is in Kosovo,'' Priakaj said. ''But
without a house or roof over our heads, it's difficult to see it
that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-01-00 0104 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
