<DOCNO> APW20000601.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Appeal for Rights Victims in China  </HEADLINE>
By ELAINE KURTENBACH
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- Chen Gang's death sentence was commuted to life
imprisonment. His offense? Setting furniture afire.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang Jie got 18 years for giving speeches and blocking traffic
during a protest.
</P>
<P>
   They are among 213 prisoners Amnesty International says remain
unjustly jailed in connection with the government's crackdown on
the Tiananmen Square pro-democracy demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven years after Chinese troops crushed the protests, killing
hundreds of unarmed demonstrators, human rights groups are still
campaigning for the crackdown's victims: people injured when
soldiers shot their way through Beijing, family members of those
killed, and prisoners it says were unfairly condemned to lengthy
jail terms.
</P>
<P>
   This year's anniversary of the June 4, 1989, crackdown comes
less than two weeks after the U.S. House of Representatives voted
to permanently grant China low-tariff trade rights, ending 20 years
of annual China trade debates that, especially since Tiananmen,
focused attention on Beijing's human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   Without the debates, U.S. officials and rights advocates are
pondering how to continue pushing Beijing to improve its rights
record.
</P>
<P>
   Among the cases cited by London-based Amnesty International in a
report released Wednesday was that of Peng Cheng, an engineer sent
to a labor camp in September for collecting signatures for a
petition demanding the government reassess its condemnation of the
1989 protests as ''counterrevolutionary rebellion.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen Gang, a manual worker, was sentenced to death for burning
furniture in the home of a security official at his factory in
Hunan province in 1989. His sentence was commuted to life
imprisonment, as was that of Wang Lianxi, after her defense argued
she was mentally retarded.
</P>
<P>
   They are among 65 people Amnesty says are known to be serving
life sentences in connection with the 1989 protests. Thousands more
were given lesser sentences.
</P>
<P>
   The report urged China to release all prisoners held for the
''peaceful exercise of fundamental human rights'' in the 1989
demonstrations and subsequent protests, to account for those killed
and injured, to compensate victims and to ''bring the perpetrators
to justice.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate appeal to China's top prosecutor's office, 108
injured survivors and victims' relatives demanded a response,
required by law, to a petition they submitted last year for an
investigation into the crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems like it might be even harder to get an answer this
year than last year. It gets harder and harder, but we will
continue to push for our demands,'' said signatory Ding Zilin, a
retired professor whose son was killed.
</P>
<P>
   The petition also demanded punishment of the leader considered
most closely associated with ordering soldiers to fire: former
Premier Li Peng. Li, the ruling Communist Party's second-most
powerful leader, now heads China's legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The government has never allowed an investigation into the
crackdown or a full accounting of those killed. Authorities have
detained dissidents demanding redress and harassed family members
of victims seeking compensation, seizing foreign donations sent to
ease their plight.
</P>
<P>
   Still, rights activists believe they have succeeded in drawing
attention to abuses that would go ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ''Somebody has to keep beating the drums,'' says John Kamm, a
businessman who has long lobbied Chinese officials on behalf of
political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Kamm, who runs a private foundation based in San Francisco, says
a new commission to monitor Beijing's labor and human rights
practices could help, but only if more money and personnel are
invested in it. The commission was part of the China trade bill
passed May 24 by the House and now headed for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Many concerned with Beijing's rights record, including
dissidents both inside and outside China, as well as U.S.
officials, believe the annual trade reviews had ceased to exert
much pressure on China. Annual attempts to censure China's record
at the United Nations Human Rights Commission have failed nine
years straight.
</P>
<P>
   ''To do nothing about human rights in China is not really
sustainable,'' says Andrew Nathan, a professor of political science
at Columbia University. ''But the government has not found
instruments to work on this area that seem effective.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-01-00 0105 </TRAILER>
