<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eminem Album Sells 1.7M First Week  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Call him Slim Shady, call him Eminem or even by
his real name, Marshall Mathers. He's probably too happy right now
to care.
</P>
<P>
   The foul-mouthed rapper sold 1.7 million copies of his new album
last week, zipping up the charts past the sunny teen pop stars he
ridicules.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Marshall Mathers LP'' is second only to 'N Sync's ''No
Strings Attached'' as the fastest-selling album in the nine years
the industry-tracking company Soundscan has been keeping accurate
count. No other rap album has sold so many copies in its first
week.
</P>
<P>
   MTV built anticipation for the album with heavy airtime, letting
Eminem serve as host of a two-hour ''EmTV'' special the weekend
before the May 23 release date. He was a guest on the network's
popular ''Total Request Live'' the first afternoon the album was on
sale.
</P>
<P>
   The profane rapper, who has been sued by his own mother for
defamation of character, appeals primarily to rap and rock fans but
has crossed over into MTV's larger pop audience, said Tom
Calderone, MTV senior vice president for music programming.
</P>
<P>
   ''As far as aggressive hip-hop or rock, there isn't anything new
out there,'' Calderone said. ''He's a welcome new sound that hit
the stores at a time people hadn't heard it for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Eminem pushes aside -- at least for a week -- the teen pop he has
mocked. He has rapped that the popular boy and girl groups ''make
me sick'' and joked in his music about Britney Spears and Christina
Aguilera performing a sex act on him.
</P>
<P>
   His album came a week after Britney Spears sold 1.3 million
copies of her new CD, which temporarily put her second to 'N Sync.
</P>
<P>
   It means the three fastest-selling albums have come in the last
two months. Soundscan has measured music sales since 1991; precise
sales figures from before that are considered unreliable.
</P>
<P>
   As a white artist in a field popularized by blacks, Eminem
benefited from a key endorsement from rapper Dr. Dre. Eminem grew
up near Detroit and has played up his ''trailer park'' upbringing.
</P>
<P>
   His new song ''Kill You'' talks about killing women -- including
Mom -- with the lyrics, ''I'm ready to play, I got the machete from
O.J.''
</P>
<P>
   At the song's end, he laughs and says: ''I'm just playin',
ladies. You know I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   He says half the things he puts on disc are done just to annoy
people, but not everyone thinks it's a joke. The Gay &AMP; Lesbian
Alliance Against Defamation criticized him Tuesday for anti-gay
lyrics, including the line: ''Hate fags? The answer's yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Eminem has told MTV that he doesn't hate gays. But GLAAD said it
is irresponsible for him and UNI/Interscope Records to promote such
material.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is especially negligent when considering the market for
this music has been shown to be adolescent males, the very group
that statistically commits the most hate crimes,'' GLAAD said.
</P>
<P>
   Even his grandmother has joined his mother in publicly
criticizing him.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's changed for the worse,'' Betty Kresin said in December.
''He talks filthy to me and is angry and disrespectful. I don't
know what's gotten into him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-01-00 0112 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000601.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Draw in Michael J. Fox Finale  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Television viewers -- 32 million of them -- showed
their fondness for Michael J. Fox by tuning in to his farewell
episode of ''Spin City'' last week.
</P>
<P>
   It was the highest rating ever for the 4-year-old ABC political
comedy, and the biggest audience for any comedy on the network
since the final ''Home Improvement'' last year, Nielsen Media
Research said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Spin City'' is continuing next season with Charlie Sheen,
despite Fox's departure because of his Parkinson's disease. Last
week's episode was heavily promoted as a farewell, though ABC has
said Fox will appear in a handful of episodes next season.
</P>
<P>
   ''Spin City'' eclipsed three installments of ''Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' in the ratings, enabling ABC to maintain its
dominance.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was a successful night for dramas: ABC's season finale
of ''NYPD Blue'' and CBS's competing ''Judging Amy'' both finished
in Nielsen's top 10.
</P>
<P>
   For the week, ABC averaged 13.6 million viewers (9.2 rating, 17
share). CBS was a distant second with 10.2 million viewers (7.4,
13), NBC had 9.5 million viewers (6.8, 12) and Fox had 6.7 million
viewers (4.5, 8)
</P>
<P>
   UPN had just under 4 million viewers (2.6 rating, 4 share), the
WB had 3.2 million viewers (2.3, 4), and Pax TV had 1.1 million
viewers (0.8, 1).
</P>
<P>
   NBC's ''Nightly News'' won the evening news ratings race with
9.4 million viewers (7.0 rating, 16 share). ABC's ''World News
Tonight'' had 8.7 million viewers (6.8, 15) and the ''CBS Evening
News'' had 7.1 million viewers (5.5, 12).
</P>
<P>
   NBC also won the May ratings sweeps in news, beating ABC in a
tight competition by 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A rating point represents 1,008,000 households, or 1 percent of
the nation's estimated 100.8 million TV homes. The share is the
percentage of in-use televisions tuned to a given show.
</P>
<P>
   For the week of May 22-28, the top 10 shows, their networks and
ratings were ''Spin City,'' ABC, 20.8; ''Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' (Thursday), ABC, 17.3; ''Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' (Wednesday), ABC, 15.9; ''Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' (Tuesday), ABC, 15.3; ''20/20'' (Wednesday), ABC,
13.6; ''Law and Order,'' NBC, 13.3; ''Everybody Loves Raymond,''
CBS, 12.4; ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' (Sunday), ABC, 11.9;
''NYPD Blue,'' ABC, 11.4; ''Judging Amy,'' CBS, 11.1.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.nielsenmedia.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
