<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Change Will Lower Phone Bills  </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Starting in July, all U.S. households should
see savings on their phone bills, with reductions as high as 50
percent for those who don't make any long-distance calls. Moderate
to heavy long-distance users can expect to see more modest
decreases.
</P>
<P>
   The reductions will result from a dramatic overhaul of the phone
subsidy system that was devised by the industry and adopted by the
Federal Communications Commission on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The commission cut by $3.2 billion the ''access fees'' that
local phone companies charge long-distance carriers to connect
calls -- costs that typically are paid by phone users. Long-distance
companies have pledged to pass on the savings, meaning their
customers should see lower rates.
</P>
<P>
   Low-volume callers would see the most immediate benefits, with
their bills dropping $3 to $4 a month. Those who make a moderate or
large amount of calls may only see small reductions in the
short-run, but stand to gain from falling long-distance rates or
price wars that the new plan could trigger, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to affect everyone differently, but overall,
everyone is going to benefit from this plan,'' FCC Chairman William
Kennard said.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers should begin seeing the changes in their July
statements.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses also would see some reductions in their monthly
charges, although it is unclear just how much they would save.
Typically, businesses, which make a large volume of long-distance
calls, have benefited from access charge reductions with lower
per-minute fees as well.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators have sliced access charges by several billion dollars
over the past few years to better reflect local phone companies'
connection costs. But Wednesday's reduction is the most dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC's action implements an industry proposal offered by
long-distance carriers AT&AMP;T and Sprint and major local phone
companies Bell Atlantic, BellSouth, GTE and SBC Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials said the plan is a major step in moving the
long-distance business toward the trend of flat-rate pricing for a
package of minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's probably the trend of the future,'' said John Nakahata,
spokesman for the industry coalition. ''This will allow those types
of plans to proliferate.''
</P>
<P>
   But consumer advocates warn that for Americans to realize the
full benefits of the FCC's action, long-distance companies must
drop their rates for middle-range callers, such as those who make
up to 60 minutes of calls a month.
</P>
<P>
   The plan's success depends on whether ''long-distance companies
deliver on their promise to pass through the savings with rate
reductions,'' said Gene Kimmelman of Consumers Union.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom, which did not sign onto the plan, said that based on
FCC data, it believes the plan ultimately will result in higher
rates for customers and additional revenue for the regional Bell
phone companies. U S West also did not join the industry coalition,
even though it must abide by the FCC's decision.
</P>
<P>
   As part of Wednesday's action, AT&AMP;T and Sprint pledged to
eliminate a minimum $3 monthly charge for residential customers on
their most basic calling plans, since some consumers make calls
totaling less than that amount.
</P>
<P>
   An AT&AMP;T basic rate customer who makes 10 minutes of
long-distance calls a month would pay $6.87 a month under the new
system, down from $9.39 a month the customer was paying before, for
a savings of $2.52 a month. A person who makes no calls would pay
$4.68, compared with $9.39 before, for a savings of $4.71 each
month, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
   The person who makes no long-distance calls benefits both from
the elimination of the minimum monthly charge and from no longer
being assessed the so-called universal service fee by the
long-distance carrier.
</P>
<P>
   More than 41 percent of long-distance users make 10 minutes or
less in calls each month.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also folds together and reduces two flat-rate charges
now on monthly bills. One, known as the subscriber line charge,
covers the cost of the phone line from the local phone company into
the home and is capped at $3.50 a month. A second pays for
long-distance companies' use of the local phone network. It now
averages about $1.50 per month.
</P>
<P>
   These two costs will be consolidated and reduced to $4.35. It
rises to $5 next July.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers, who have been indirectly paying to keep phone service
affordable for low-income people and those in high-cost areas, will
see these universal service charges spelled out separately in their
monthly bill. The fee, a percentage of their long-distance calls,
will go to a $650 million fund.
</P>
<P>
   A separate fee from their local phone company, averaging about
36 cents, will also be used to keep phone service affordable.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Federal Communications Commission site:
http://www.fcc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Industry site: http://www.phonepolicy.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-01-00 0134 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000601.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Newspapers Reveal Croatian's Talks  </HEADLINE>
By SNJEZANA VUKIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) -- Once private conversations of the late
president Franjo Tudjman are now filling the columns of Zagreb's
newspapers care of the man who succeeded him.
</P>
<P>
   Stipe Mesic, elected president in February two months after
Tudjman's death from cancer, found tapes that his predecessor had
made of his private conversations over the course of his nine-year
rule.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of keeping them confidential, Mesic delivered
transcripts to the press, saying he wanted the Croatian public ''to
see how decisions were made under Tudjman.''
</P>
<P>
   ''My goal is that those who violated the law end up behind
bars,'' Mesic told reporters recently.
</P>
<P>
   Conversations made public so far are from the final years of the
Tudjman era and do not include tapes from the 1991 war for
independence from Yugoslavia, nor from the period of the 1992-95
Bosnian conflict in which Croatia was deeply involved.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, there has been nothing published to confirm the
widely held view that Tudjman and Yugoslavia's current president,
Slobodan Milosevic, conspired in 1991 to carve up
Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
   But the transcripts show that even in 1999 -- four years after he
signed the Dayton peace agreement for Bosnia -- Tudjman still
dreamed of annexing part of that country.
</P>
<P>
   ''You should give no indication (to international officials)
that we wish ... the three-way division of Bosnia,'' the transcript
quotes Tudjman as telling a visiting Bosnian Croat leader in April,
1999.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, NATO was bombing Yugoslavia to force an end to
Milosevic's crackdown on Albanians in Kosovo. According to the
transcript, Tudjman reckoned that this could lead to the division
of Kosovo to Serb- and Albanian-controlled areas.
</P>
<P>
   Tudjman figured that such a division would set a precedent for
dividing Bosnia into Serb, Muslim and Croat sections, according to
the transcript.
</P>
<P>
   It also shows that Tudjman and his visitors discussed plans to
settle Croat refugees and build military barracks in parts of
Bosnia that they hoped to control under such a division.
</P>
<P>
   The transcripts also show that despite Croatia's war with Serbs,
relations between Tudjman and Milosevic were not altogether
strained. One transcript shows that Tudjman last year apologized to
Milosevic for a book written by his aide, Hrvoje Sarinic, that
blasted the Yugoslav president for supporting the Serb rebellion
against Croatia in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ''As far as I'm concerned, I was not in favor of him publishing
that book and particularly being so sharp about,'' Milosevic,
Tudjman asked a caller who had ties to Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   According to the transcripts, Milosevic and Tudjman stayed in
contact through a businessman living in Switzerland. On another
occasion, the businessman told Tudjman that Milosevic sent him
''warm regards and best wishes'' for his recovery from cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In another transcript, Tudjman and an aide allegedly plot to
secretly buy the largest Croatian newspaper, Vecernji list, for
their then ruling party while pretending it was bought by a foreign
media company.
</P>
<P>
   That transcript has prompted a police investigation into the
sale of the newspaper to an Austrian firm. The government has
suspended the sale pending the outcome of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The aide, Ivic Pasalic, claims the conversation was fabricated.
</P>
<P>
   Although the transcripts so far contain no ''smoking guns'' of
criminal activity, they provide an insight into the Tudjman regime.
Political analyst Jelena Lovric said they confirm a pattern of
''paranoia, conspiracy, plots and frauds, unscrupulous despotism
and decisions which outwitted people and laws.''
</P>
<P>
   For many Croats, the transcripts confirm what they always
suspected of their government.
</P>
<P>
   ''We did suspect all of what we're reading now,'' said Dora
Vlacic, 48, a painter. ''But it's still shocking because we now
know that everything we hoped was just mean gossip was actually
true.''
</P>
<P>
   Release of the tapes has also drawn mixed reactions about Mesic,
now dubbed ''Sherlock Mesic'' by the Zagreb press.
</P>
<P>
   Some see him as a fighter who only wants to reveal and punish
the wrongdoings of Tudjman and his clique. His opponents say the
transcripts seen so far offer little proof of actual crimes and
that it is up to police -- and not media -- to carry out
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Tudjman's party, now in the opposition, insisted the
conversations should be classified. The ruling parties rejected the
idea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-01-00 0134 </TRAILER>
