<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Comets 93, Fire 89, 2OT  </HEADLINE>
By LANDON HALL
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Sheryl Swoopes scored eight of her 29
points in the second overtime as the defending champion Houston
Comets held off the expansion Portland Fire 93-89 on Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes hit all four of Houston's baskets in the second overtime
and assisted on the other, feeding center Tiffani Johnson for an
easy layup that gave the Comets an 89-87 lead with 23.5 seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   On the next possession, Swoopes intercepted a pass from Portland
center Alisa Burras and ran downcourt for a layup and a 91-87 lead
with 12.6 seconds to go.
</P>
<P>
   The Fire's Stacey Thomas drove for a layup to cut the lead to
two, but Cynthia Cooper made both free throws with 3.4 seconds left
to seal it.
</P>
<P>
   Houston didn't exactly look like a three-time defending WNBA
champion most of the way against the inexperienced Fire. The Comets
were outshot 43 percent to 40 percent and outrebounded 49-36.
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes, who shot 12-for-27, also had six rebounds and five
assists. Cooper added 22 points but shot just 6-for-23. Janeth
Arcain had 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   Burras and Sophia Witherspoon, acquired in the expansion draft
from New York, led the Fire with 19 points each. Vanessa Nygaard
had 11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Fire blew a chance to win in the final seconds of
regulation, then needed a driving layup by Tully Bevilaqua with 2.1
seconds left to tie it at 73.
</P>
<P>
   Nygaard missed two free throws with 40.3 seconds left, but after
Thomas rebounded, Nygaard followed another miss with a rebound and
bank shot to tie it at 71. Nygaard was fouled but missed the free
throw.
</P>
<P>
   That set up a 17-foot jumper by Swoopes with 7.9 seconds left.
Portland then inbounded at halfcourt, and Bevilaqua drove the
baseline for the tying basket.
</P>
<P>
   In the first overtime, the Comets needed an easy layup by Cooper
off an inbounds pass from Thompson to tie it at 81 with 6.6 seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, coming off a season-opening 84-68 victory over the New
York Liberty on Monday, jumped to an early lead but struggled with
its outside shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets appeared to give themselves a cushion when Cooper's
hook shot capped a 15-3 run and opened up a 57-48 lead with 9:37 to
go.
</P>
<P>
   Portland fought back and tied it at 64 on a layup by Burras, and
the teams matched each other shot for shot until overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Burras, a husky 6-foot-3 reserve center who played for the
Cleveland Rockers last season and was third in the league in
field-goal percentage, made seven of her 12 shots and had eight
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, who has won the WNBA scoring title all three years and
shot a team-high 46.3 percent last season, has made just 11 of her
38 shots in the first two games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
