<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tentative agreement reached to end month long walkout  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WETHERSFIELD, Conn. (AP) -- The American Red Cross and its blood
collection workers in Connecticut have reached a tentative
three-year contract agreement that would end a monthlong walkout.
</P>
<P>
   The deal came Wednesday, the 31st day of a strike by 200 members
of the American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees
Local 3145. The workers were seeking better pay and less hectic
work schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side would release details of the deal, saying they
wanted workers to hear the proposal first.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an improvement over the previous last best offer of the
Red Cross that compelled the strike,'' said Jeffrey Jump, chief
negotiator for the union.
</P>
<P>
   A vote on the agreement was scheduled for Saturday. No date has
been set for employees to return to work.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're very pleased, looking forward to having our employees
back at their jobs,'' said Lynn Townshend, Red Cross spokeswoman.
''We're relieved.''
</P>
<P>
   Blood collections in Connecticut have dropped to about 100 pints
per day from the usual 600. The Red Cross has been holding only one
blood drive each day, instead of the six to 12 it held before the
strike. The agency hopes to have a full complement of blood drives
within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Jump predicted the members would ratify the deal. The union's
negotiating committee is unanimously recommending the agreement, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel good about it, to say the least,'' Jump said. ''Every
issue has been addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Jump thanked state and federal mediators for their help in
reaching an agreement, which came after a full day of negotiations
at the state Department of Labor in Wethersfield. He praised the
striking workers for maintaining solidarity throughout the strike.
</P>
<P>
   ''The membership has been remarkable,'' Jump said. ''They have
really stuck this out and persevered.''
</P>
<P>
   Jump attributed the settlement to both sides showing
flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   Although no hospital reported any problems with blood delivery
or service because of the strike, a controversy arose after the
Connecticut AFL-CIO urged the union's 265,000 members to boycott
blood drives until the contract dispute was resolved.
</P>
<P>
   The union had had also asked the American Red Cross ''to cease
the transfer to Connecticut of blood from national inventories or
other centers around the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut Hospital Association called that move
irresponsible, and a threat to the blood supply.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-01-00 0149 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000601.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three inmates, injured in prison fire  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOMERS, Conn. (AP) -- Three inmates, including a man accused of
killing an East Hartford police officer, were injured in a fire at
the Northern Correctional Institution.
</P>
<P>
   The fire occurred at about 7:45 p.m. Wednesday in a unit of the
maximum-security prison that houses about 50 inmates, including the
six on Connecticut's death row, said Christina Polce, a Correction
Department spokeswoman. No death row inmates were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters said that mattresses, books and paperwork were on
fire in a cell, but that the blaze did not spread beyond that cell.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was quite a bit of smoke,'' said Lt. Duane Drouin of the
Somers Volunteer Fire Department. ''The correction officers knocked
it down with fire extinguishers. But there was a small amount of
flame. It was still smoldering.''
</P>
<P>
   The injured included Alex Sostre, 25, who is awaiting trial on
capital felony and murder charges in the Jan. 23, 1999 shooting of
East Hartford Police officer Brian Aselton. Sostre suffered smoke
inhalation, but was expected to be treated and released from
Johnson Memorial Hospital, said Capt. Heather Ziemba, another
spokeswoman for the Department of Correction.
</P>
<P>
   Sostre's cellmate, identified as Pedro Poupart, suffered minor
burns and was expected to be transferred to the prison ward of the
John Dempsey Hospital in Farmington, Ziemba said. A third inmate,
identified as Julio Gomez, suffered minor smoke inhalation as was
being returned to Northern, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Poupart, 18, of New Haven, is serving 17 months for assault on a
police or fire officers. Gomez, 29, of Meriden, is serving three
years for violation of probation. His record includes burglary,
larceny and drug charges.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Johnson Memorial said four guards also were treated
for smoke inhalation. But prison officials said the guards were not
injured, and went to the hospital only to accompany the prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The housing unit, known as One East, is reserved for inmates
with behavioral problems. Inmates in the unit are locked in their
cells 23 hours a day, Ziemba said. The residents were evacuated to
another section of the prison after the fire, but were being
returned to their cells early this morning, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''At no time was public safety, or the security of the facility
jeopardized,'' Polce said.
</P>
<P>
   The prison houses over 430 of Connecticut's worst offenders.
Polce said the facility's perimeter was ''secured and reinforced''
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The community was notified through a beeper system that
activates in times of emergency, Polce said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-01-00 0149 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000601.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecution witness grilled by defense in Peeler trial  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- Josephine Lee, who has testified she
was the lookout when a gunman killed an 8-year-old witness and the
boy's mother, denied knowing anything about the killings in letters
she wrote to her former landlord.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, the state's star witness against Russell Peeler, originally
testified she overheard Peeler and his brother, Adrian, plan the
murders of Leroy ''B.J.'' Brown Jr. and his mother, Karen Clarke.
Lee also said she helped Adrian Peeler get into the Clarke house
and watched as he shot the mother and son on Jan. 7, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, Peeler's defense attorneys confronted her with
two letters she wrote to her former landlord, Norman Williams, in
which she said she lied.
</P>
<P>
   ''Norman you know that I lied on the Peelers. But I was scared
when the police came to the house to get me so I told them that I
had something to do with the murder. But I do not know anything,''
she wrote in a letter to Williams in May, just after she testified
against Russell Peeler.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who lived across the street from Clarke and her son in a
house owned by Williams, last year pleaded guilty to conspiracy to
commit murder. She agreed to testify against the Peeler brothers in
exchange for a maximum prison sentence of seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Peeler is accused of masterminding the murders to
prevent the boy from testifying against him in the 1998 slaying of
Clarke's boyfriend, Rudolph Snead Jr. His brother, Adrian, is
accused of being the actual triggerman who killed the mother and
son.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning from Peeler's attorneys Wednesday, Lee said
she lied in her letters to Williams because she was hoping to live
in his house again when she is released from prison. She later
contradicted herself, however, saying she did not want to go back
to Williams' house.
</P>
<P>
   She insisted that she was telling the truth when she said she
overheard Russell Peeler ask his brother, Adrian, to kill the
mother and son. She also repeated her original story that she got
Adrian inside the Clarke housing by knocking on the door and
identifying herself as the girl who lived across the street.
</P>
<P>
   ''This right here is a lie,'' she said, holding up one of the
letters she wrote to Williams. ''I'm telling the truth now,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Lee has changed her story.
</P>
<P>
   When Lee first testified as a prosecution witness, Peeler's
attorneys grilled her about a letter she wrote to her own attorney
in Dec. 1999 in which she denied knowing anything about the
killings. At the same time, she sent three separate letters to
Bridgeport police officers in which she said she asked forgiveness
for having a role in the killings.
</P>
<P>
   The defense also called Williams as a witness.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, a 75-year-old nicknamed ''Pops,'' said he did not see
Russell Peeler at his house the day before the murder,
contradicting Lee's earlier testimony that she overheard Russell
and Adrian planning the murders as they sat in Williams' house that
day.
</P>
<P>
   Williams also said he did not see Adrian Peeler at his house the
day of the murders. Lee testified earlier that Adrian Peeler walked
into Williams' house holding a gun and that she brought him across
the street to Clarke's house with him.
</P>
<P>
   ''Did you see Adrian with Josephine Lee with a gun in his
hand?'' Peeler's attorney, William Koch, asked Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ''No way,'' Williams replied.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination from Bridgeport State's Attorney
Jonathan Benedict, Williams acknowledged that he and others who
stayed in his house had smoked crack cocaine. Lee testified that
Russell Peeler used Williams' kitchen to cook the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Closing arguments in the case are scheduled for Friday. The jury
is expected to begin deliberations Monday after receiving
instruction on the law from the judge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
