<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smithsonian To Show Beltway Customs  </HEADLINE>
By CARL HARTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- This national capital consists of more than
bureaucrats and whistle-blowers. It's home to at least 560,000
people, many of whom came from other parts of the country and the
world.
</P>
<P>
   That may help explain the popularity of the Smithsonian's annual
folk-life festival, which, according to its executive director,
Diana Parker, may attract as many as 1 million visitors to the
National Mall beginning June 23.
</P>
<P>
   Colorful stands and pavilions will exhibit food, music, crafts
and pastimes, with large areas devoted to Tibetans and people who
live along the Rio Grande. There also will be exhibitions by a
basketball team of women over age 60.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has a large and growing Latino population.
Restaurants called French or Italian may be staffed largely by
people who come from El Salvador.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, a daily festival event called ''Washington, D.C.: It's Our
Home'' will have a distinctly Latin flavor. At a preview of the
festival Wednesday, Tony Gittens, executive director of the D.C.
Commission on Arts and Humanities, presented a band bravely named
Sin Miedo (Spanish for ''Without Fear''), playing with members of a
Brazilian group. The festival also will include demonstrations of
dress weaving for the quinceniera, the traditional coming-out
occasion for 15-year-old girls in the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Lessons will be available on how to make a pinata, the Mexican
package of paper or clay that spews candy when children hit it with
a stick.
</P>
<P>
   Gittens pointed out that many Washingtonians trace their origins
to the American rural South. Washington's highly urbanized 68
square miles include little farm land, but the festival will devote
an area on the Mall to gardening.
</P>
<P>
   A strong religious impulse will be represented by gospel blues
and blue grass, and by Jewish cantors, Yoruba ceremony from West
Africa, Koranic chants, Japanese and Cambodian melodies.
</P>
<P>
   Food will include Chesapeake Bay crab cakes and fried chicken as
well as a variety of ethnic foods: Panamanian snacks, Middle
Eastern bean pie, Senegalese cebujen -- fish and rice -- and Ghanaian
cooking. Pepper soup with goat meat over fufu is one local delicacy
promised.
</P>
<P>
   And somewhere, thought Michael McBride, the arts specialist
coordinating all the research, will be a demonstration of the
healing arts practiced by native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The festival, which will take place June 23-27 and June 30-July
4, will end with the traditional Independence Day fireworks display
at the Washington Monument.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.si.edu/folklife
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
