<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Castaway Leaves 'Survivor'  </HEADLINE>
By FRAZIER MOORE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Sonja, we hardly knew ye.
</P>
<P>
   Kindly Sonja -- a 60-ish musician who proved not quite as spry as
her fellow ''Survivor'' castaways -- was sent packing at the end of
the CBS reality series' premiere Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''Go get 'em, you guys,'' she said after being voted out,
gracious even in exile.
</P>
<P>
   That left 15 in this endurance contest, which was staged on a
primitive island off Borneo and is being aired by CBS in a survival
effort against ABC's smash quiz ''Who Wants to be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   By this summer's 13th installment, just one survivor will remain
and be $1 million richer. And maybe CBS will have itself a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Based on early returns, CBS probably has a hit on its hands. The
show drew an estimated audience of between 17 million and 18
million, with the best ratings for any regularly-scheduled CBS show
in its time slot in two years, according to Nielsen Media
Research's overnight measurement in 48 major markets.
</P>
<P>
   ''Survivor'' didn't quite beat ABC's ''Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire,'' but finished only 6 percent behind the game show
hit.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly for CBS, the show's audience grew as the hour
went on -- a strong sign that curious viewers weren't turning away,
said Marc Berman, a ratings analyst for Mediaweek.com.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think this is a tremendous start,'' Berman said, ''better
than anyone might have expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the first-night ''Survivor'' audience need not fret
over Sonja's banishment. Next week (which will cover another three
days in the 39-day ordeal taped earlier this year), viewers will
find the other characters marooned right where they left them.
</P>
<P>
   Among the carefully selected ''tribesmen,'' truck driver Susan
will likely still be squabbling with Richard, a corporate trainer.
And Rudy, a retired Navy SEAL, should still be bossing everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they listened to me,'' Rudy told the camera on the first
show, ''they'd all have haircuts. We'd be in formation in the
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, next week, the next person will be voted out at a
torch-lit tribal council. And then there will be 14.
</P>
<P>
   After months of buildup, ''Survivor'' may surprise viewers by
resisting the salacious or even sinister tone some were expecting.
With the motto ''Outwit, Outplay, Outlast,'' the show focuses on
roughing it in beautiful surroundings -- and on interpersonal
gamesmanship.
</P>
<P>
   The diverse group (which is split into two rival camps) harbors
distinct personalities that, if not always likable, are generally
involving. A few, like biochemist Ramona and Sean, the doctor with
a nipple ring, are also easy on the eyes.
</P>
<P>
   One contestant more interesting than the show's producers might
have preferred is Richard Hatch. Last month, he pleaded innocent to
allegations he abused his 9-year-old son. The boy said he was
forced to go running and his father wrapped his hands around his
neck to move him along when he tired.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm good to go, survival-wise,'' Hatch confidently told
Wednesday's ''Survivor'' audience. ''People-wise, it'll be a little
more challenging. But I've got the million-dollar check written
already.''
</P>
<P>
   The actual winner, whose identity CBS is jealously guarding, is
yet to be uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
http://entertainment.cbs.com/network/tvshows/mini/survivor/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
