<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 12:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Wants To Boost British Flights  </HEADLINE>
By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- U. S. and British negotiators are about to
resume talks on liberalizing air travel between the countries and
Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater is seeking a deal by the end
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Flights between the countries are limited by a 1977 treaty and
the governments have been at odds for years over how to ease those
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Thursday on a conference call from London, Slater said
formal negotiations are scheduled to resume June 12 and the United
States wants a ''comprehensive and liberalized aviation agreement
concluded by the end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Slater said he is seeking a ''more competitive and open
environment'' including increased access for U.S. carriers to
London's popular Heathrow Airport as well as increased flights
between the countries for both American and British carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Slater said the recently announced plan for United Airlines to
take over US Airways does not muddy the waters in these
discussions, although it is another item to be considered.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways has been one of the most vocal U.S. carriers in
seeking more trans-Atlantic flights.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're interested in hearing how that (the merger) might be
viewed here,'' Slater commented.
</P>
<P>
   As to the proposed merger itself, Slater said he met last week
with officials of both United and US Airways, as well as the new DC
Air, a proposed spinoff of US Airways that would fly from
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is just so much we can say about it while we look at it
and work with Justice'' in reviewing the proposed merger, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was clear they had anticipated some of the challenges they
will face,'' he added about the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to the British-U.S. talks, Slater noted an effort by
British Airways, which dominates flights into Heathrow, to protect
its markets.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, British Midland is seeking international service,
British Virgin wants to expand the flights it now has to the United
States and many U.S. airlines are interested in breaking into the
trans-Atlantic market.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we are trying to do is create, with the British, the most
comprehensive, forward and far-reaching agreement possible,''
Slater said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1977 Bermuda II treaty, U.S. and British carriers each
are limited to 21 daily flights between the countries. Negotiations
to expand the treaty broke down in January.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Department of Transportation: http://www.dot.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
