<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four hospitals to repay $11.3 million in Medicare case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- Four Connecticut hospitals will pay the
federal government $11.3 million in connection with overpayments
they received from an insurer linked to Medicare fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The payments meet the hospitals' financial responsibility in a
$74 million settlement the government reached in December 1999 with
Anthem Health Plans Inc., according to U.S. Attorney Stephen C.
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   The hospitals were overpaid when Anthem's predecessor company,
Blue Cross &AMP; Blue Shield of Connecticut, falsified cost reports to
conceal its failure to meet government standards under the Medicare
program, Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreements announced Wednesday do not constitute evidence of
any wrongdoing by the hospitals, Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials said the payments would have no effect on
patient care.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, the Hospital of St. Raphael in New Haven
agreed to pay $8.3 million, including $2.3 million in interest. The
hospital has already repaid $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said the investigation began when St. Raphael's
disclosed the fraud in 1998. The overpayments were discovered
during a corporate compliance program, according to Helayne
Lightstone, director of public relations for the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Other hospitals and their payments are: St. Vincent's Medical
Center in Bridgeport, $1.9 million; Bridgeport Hospital, $800,615;
and Griffin Hospital in Derby, $307,740.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation will continue, focusing on other hospitals
that might be linked to the fraudulent activity, said John B.
Hughes, chief of the civil division for the U.S. attorney's office
in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Spokespersons for the hospitals said hospital officials had been
unaware of the overpayments.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was no malfeasance,'' said Bruce Hutchison, a spokesman
for St Vincent's Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   The repayments come as the Department of Justice and state
hospitals continue to unravel $32 million worth of Medicare
overpayments. The DOJ has now accounted for $11 million of the $32
million that was overpaid, Hughes said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-01-00 1300 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000601.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Final answer: former game show contestant admits embezzling money  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM KATES
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) --This time, Paul Barbour made it to the hot
seat, where he got to give his final answer.
</P>
<P>
   Only this wasn't ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' and it
wasn't Regis Philbin listening to him.
</P>
<P>
   Barbour, a former ''Millionaire'' contestant who has written a
soon-to-be-released book on how to get on the game show, admitted
to U.S. District Judge Norman Mordue that he embezzled $213,800
from an insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   Barbour gained instant celebrity status after he and his two
brothers became the first three siblings in the country to make it
onto ABC-TV's popular game show. Although none made it to the final
''hot seat'' round, the brothers were the focus of a flurry of
media attention, including appearances on ''The Rosie O'Donnell
Show'' and ''Inside Edition.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbour, 38, of Baldwinsville, appeared in federal court
Wednesday with his accomplice, Kellie A. Moran, to plead guilty to
defrauding Nationwide Insurance Co. through the mail. Each faces
five years in prison, fines of up to $250,000 and an order to pay
more than $150,000 in restitution when they are sentenced Sept. 29
by Judge Norman A. Mordue.
</P>
<P>
   Barbour and Moran, 41, admitted inventing a scheme in 1998 to
defraud Nationwide, where Barbour worked as an in-house lawyer.
Between April and December 1998, Barbour authorized paying about
$213,800 of Nationwide's money to a phony medical services company
controlled by Moran, a registered nurse.
</P>
<P>
   The money was to pay for evaluations of Nationwide clients'
medical records. Moran's company got paid for reviewing more than
140 case files. Nationwide only received one written report from
her.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, the two spent $13,514 to pay off a
car loan and $3,254 as an investment with Dean Witter. The rest of
the money is unaccounted for, said Assistant U.S. Attorney Andrew
Baxter.
</P>
<P>
   Barbour did not return phone calls Thursday seeking comment.
Previously, he had declared himself innocent and said he would take
his case to trial.
</P>
<P>
   Barbour appeared on ''Millionaire's'' second show in August 1999
-- a month after he was indicted by a federal grand jury. His
brother Mark got on the show in March and their older brother Mike
made it on in May.
</P>
<P>
   Having successfully advised his brothers on how to get on the
show, Paul decided to write a book with tips on how to qualify as a
contestant, ''Who Wants to be a Contestant.'' The 200-page book is
being published by TV Books and is scheduled to be distributed by
HarperCollins.
</P>
<P>
   TV Books publisher Peter Kaufman did not return phone calls
seeking comment about whether Barbour's felony conviction will have
any impact on publication and distribution of the book.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
