<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Receive Unity Prize  </HEADLINE>
By TONY CZUCZKA
<TEXT>
<P>
   AACHEN, Germany (AP) -- When President Clinton visits this
historic town this week to receive a prestigious European unity
prize, he will mingle with people who have lived life without
borders for years.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's westernmost city on the Dutch and Belgian borders has
been a symbol of European integration since the 8th century, when
the Holy Roman emperor Charlemagne ruled a large swath of western
Europe from his palace in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Germans, Dutch and Belgians in the region have built a
small model of a united Europe. With border checks gone, many live
in one country and work in another. Three currencies jingle in
their pockets since storekeepers cater to cross-border shoppers. An
ambitious three-nation fund promotes economic projects for an area
of 4 million people.
</P>
<P>
   During his one-day visit Friday, Clinton will be presented with
the International Charlemagne Prize, awarded for 50 years by Aachen
city leaders to world leaders who have promoted European unity as a
safeguard against future world wars.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was chosen for his ''contributions to European
cooperation,'' including supporting former communist countries to
join the 15-nation European Union. The award also is a symbol of
thanks for American help in rebuilding postwar Germany.
</P>
<P>
   In Aachen, a city of 250,000 otherwise known for its crunchy
gingerbread and hot springs, Clinton's visit has set off an
unprecedented bustle.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who is to give a speech on U.S.-European relations,
will receive the prize at an open-air event on a cobblestone
courtyard between the 14th-century town hall and a cathedral begun
by Charlemagne around 800. Aachen residents are expected to jam
into the tree-lined square to greet Clinton on what is likely to be
his last official visit to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   He is the third American to win the prize after former
secretaries of state George Marshall and German-native Henry
Kissinger. Last year, it went to British Prime Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
   Other winners include Sir Winston Churchill, King Juan Carlos of
Spain, former Chancellor Helmut Kohl and Czech President Vaclav
Havel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
