<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N. Korea Wins Pledge of China Aid  </HEADLINE>
By CHARLES HUTZLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- On a secretive, first foray abroad in 17 years,
North Korean leader Kim Jong Il won fresh pledges of Chinese aid,
consulted China's leaders about his summit with South Korea and
saluted their capitalist reforms, the governments announced
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A legendary recluse, Kim was feted by Chinese leaders, toured a
respected computer maker synonymous with China's economic rise and,
donning sunglasses, stood atop the Gate of Heavenly Peace
overlooking Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   Announcement of Kim's Monday-to-Wednesday visit, hotly rumored
in Beijing and South Korea for two days, waited until the North
Korean leader, riding a special train, was safely home.
</P>
<P>
   Secrecy aside, the visit's timing and treatment underscored its
significance for long isolated, communist North Korea and the
region. In two weeks, Kim meets South Korean President Kim Dae-jung
for the rival Koreas' first summit. North Korea has recently set up
diplomatic ties with Australia and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ''This could be seen as further evidence that Kim's trying to
make some real significant reorientation in North Korean foreign
policy,'' said Marcus Noland of the Institute for International
Economics in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The summit was the first for China and North Korea since Kim's
father, Kim Il Sung, visited Beijing nine years ago. Ever since,
ties between the once-close communist allies have frayed as China
pursued free markets and South Korean investment while North Korea
sunk into economic torpor.
</P>
<P>
   Highlighting the visit's importance for China, Kim met Chinese
President Jiang Zemin and the six other members of the ruling
Communist Party's inner circle. Chinese state television showed
Jiang and Kim embracing.
</P>
<P>
   In a telling detail about the different paths their nations have
taken, Jiang wore a well-cut blue Western suit and tie. Kim had on
a high-collared gray Mao jacket, a badge with his father's bust on
his lapel.
</P>
<P>
   Kim made his last visit abroad in 1983, to China, and seldom
sees foreigners. Pressed for details about the North Korean leader
by foreign reporters, Chinese Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Zhang
Qiyue would only say that he ''looks to be in good health.''
</P>
<P>
   Both governments described the talks as friendly and important.
North Korea's news agency said China and North Korea cemented the
friendship ''sealed in blood,'' a reference to their common fight
in the 1950-53 Korean War. But few details were offered.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese President Jiang Zemin told Kim that China ''welcomes and
supports the North Korean and South Korean summit and hopes to see
positive progress,'' Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing wants to see tensions between the Koreas eased, partly
so it can concentrate on economic development, but also to prevent
the United States from deploying a regional anti-missile shield.
</P>
<P>
   For North Korea, the June 12-14 summit in the North Korean
capital of Pyongyang could deliver South Korean aid and a chance to
show a more confident leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Kim's ''position is strengthening, and the material gains that
he could expect to pick up in China and then in South Korea he
could further use to consolidate his power at home,'' said Noland,
the North Korea watcher.
</P>
<P>
   During the months that Beijing and Pyongyang negotiated Kim's
visit, North Korea was rumored to be seeking $800 million worth of
Chinese food, fuel and forgiveness of North Korean debts, Noland
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kim took home a Chinese promise for free food and other material
assistance, spokeswoman Zhang said. She refused to specify the
amount.
</P>
<P>
   Gripped by five years of food shortages and economic collapse,
North Korea has made tentative, piecemeal efforts to change its
collectivized agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   In meeting Jiang, Kim noted the ''great achievements'' China has
made and said North Korea ''supports the reform policy pursued by
the Chinese side,'' Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently defending his own policies, Kim added that North
Korea ''is building a Korean-style socialism according to its
specific national conditions,'' China's Xinhua News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the visit's more unexpected moments, Kim toured the
Legend Group, a Chinese computer maker in Beijing's high-tech
district of computer and Internet ventures.
</P>
<P>
   The stop showed that Kim ''is very interested in computer
technology,'' not that North Korea would follow Chinese reforms,
said Shinya Kato, a Japanese expert on North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if Kim's trip heralded a return to the heyday of
close ties, Zhang said: ''A philosopher once said, 'No man can step
into the same river twice' -- which means that things are always
changing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
