<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Up 128; Dow Up 83  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose sharply today as investors took
heart in the latest signs that rising interest rates are
successfully keeping inflation at bay. Buyers dipped into the
technology sector, snapping up shares of market leaders that have
been battered in the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 82.58 at 10,604.91.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was up 17.79 at 1,438.39, and the Nasdaq composite index
was up 128.31 at 3,529.22.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks led the market higher today. Qualcomm rose
$2.875 to $69.25 and PMC-Sierra rose $13.75 to $167.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard soared $10.875 to $131 following upbeat
projections made at the company's semiannual meeting this week.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft rose $1.688 to $64.25. The company has asked for extra
time to formulate a breakup plan should a federal judge order the
company to divest its Windows operating systems business.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. analyst Rick Sherlund said today the stock
may be able to recover some ''lost ground'' after the judge rules
and the lengthy appeal process gets underway.
</P>
<P>
   ''This 'quiet time' in which there is not much new news on the
lawsuit could enable sentiment to improve a bit,'' Sherlund told
clients. Sherlund, among Wall Street's most influential Microsoft
analysts, has triggered several shifts in the stock's performance
in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer rose 81.3 cents to $45.25. A study published in the New
England Journal of Medicine reported that Pfizer's impotence
treatment drug Viagra caused no harmful changes in the blood flow
of men with severe heart disease. Pfizer financed the study.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch added Pfizer to its ''Focus 1'' list of highly
recommended stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The market has gained strength in the past few sessions as a
string of economic reports have suggested that the runaway pace of
the nation's economic growth is slowing a bit. This morning, many
of the nation's retailers reported lackluster sales for May,
indicating that six interest-rate increases by the Federal Reserve
are beginning to quell consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the National Association of Purchasing Management issued
a report that growth in the industrial economy slowed during May.
The report also said inflationary pressures for industrial supplies
appear to have peaked in March.
</P>
<P>
   The report could convince the Fed to raise interest rates by a
slim quarter-percentage point -- or perhaps to hold them steady -- at
its next meeting on June 27-28, said Michael Moran, chief economist
at Daiwa Securities America.
</P>
<P>
   Still, analysts say the most crucial report will be the Labor
Department's May employment report, due out before the start of
trading Friday. Any signs of slower growth -- whether in a higher
unemployment rate or lower wage pressures -- should enable the
market to extend its efforts to rally.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has viewed the plummeting jobless rate as a sign that
companies would have to sharply raise wages and benefits to retain
workers. That could eventually force them to raise prices, setting
a stage for renewed inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 9-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 621.22 million
shares, slightly ahead of Wednesday afternoon's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 11.19 to
487.37.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. market drew strength from overseas markets, which were
almost uniformly higher. Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 2.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
