<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji's Ethnic Indians Live in Fear  </HEADLINE>
By ROHAN SULLIVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Ashok Chand and his wife, Mahoni Lata, have
had enough.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after Fiji's government crisis began, the ethnic
Indian couple are fleeing their home near the national parliament,
where rebels hold more than 30 people hostage.
</P>
<P>
   ''We fear for our lives,'' Chand said, clutching a cardboard box
of belongings as he packed to go stay with relatives. ''Yesterday I
was robbed. Today I just want to get out.'' Lata stood nearby,
holding the couple's pet cat.
</P>
<P>
   Chand and Lata, like other ethnic Indians, are living in terror
in this country 2,250 miles northeast of Sydney, Australia, where
ethnic unrest exploded two weeks ago and shows few signs of
abating.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis is rooted in simmering tensions between the country's
large ethnic Indian minority and the Fijian majority, many of whom
are angry that the Indians have gained power.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels led by businessman George Speight are Fijian, while
Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry and other hostages -- many of them
legislators -- are ethnic Indian. The rebels want Chaudhry, Fiji's
first prime minister from the minority, removed from power and
Fijians of Indian ancestry barred from leading the country again.
</P>
<P>
   Chand and Lata live less than a mile from the parliamentary
compound where Speight and hundreds of supporters have holed up
with their captives. Hooded, armed thugs have roamed the streets
around the compound, stoning cars and buses. They have roughed up
and robbed taxi drivers and stolen their vehicles. Most victims
were ethnic Indians.
</P>
<P>
   On May 19, the day the hostages were seized, a rampaging mob
tore through Suva, the capital, and looted businesses. Gangs have
attacked Indian homes and businesses in Suva and outlying villages
in the days since. Until martial law was imposed, police acted
slowly or not at all to stop the violence.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen men were arrested last week after rampaging through an
Indian farming settlement on Suva's outskirts, beating and robbing
people in their houses and stealing cattle and chickens, police
said. In the Indian-dominated village of Viria, bandits ransacked
and set fire to homes during several nights last week.
</P>
<P>
   ''They came onto our property in masks and started throwing
stones and smashed the windows before they entered,'' Jagat Prasad
told The Fiji Times newspaper. ''They took a stereo, video deck and
money from the house before setting the rooms on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the worst moment of our lives,'' said another
resident, 79-year-old Bhagirati, who uses only one name. ''I am
very frightened.''
</P>
<P>
   The nation's military took control Monday, declaring martial law
and opening negotiations with Speight's supporters. The military
rulers have accepted Speight's major demands: scrapping the 1997
constitution blamed by indigenous Fijians for giving too much power
to ethnic Indians, deposing President Ratu Sir Kamisise Mara and
offering Speight and his gang amnesty.
</P>
<P>
   In downtown Suva, shops remain closed Thursday. Business leaders
say many will stay shut until the crisis is resolved, and some will
probably never recover.
</P>
<P>
   ''About 80 percent of business will not get back to normal
because many businessmen don't have the funds to start up again,''
said Himmat Lodhia, a spokesman for downtown retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Fijians of Indian ancestry make up 44 percent of Fiji's
population of 813,000, but they control much of the commerce.
Damage to Indian businesses means damage to Fiji's economy, which
is centered around sugar, timber production and tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Fiji's four sugar mills have been idled since the crisis
started, just as the harvest was due to begin. Shipments to
Malaysia, Korea and Portugal have been rescheduled, with no
prospect that the orders will be filled.
</P>
<P>
   ''No farmer feels like harvesting while his leader is held
hostage by a gunman,'' National Farmers Union spokesman Marika
Silimaibau said of Chaudhry.
</P>
<P>
   Indians may be scared, but they are also furious. One
businessman who asked that his name not be published said the
Indian community is used to being discriminated against.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a lot of anger, but I don't think they (Indians) will
do anything about it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
