<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rival Flags Waved on Jerusalem Day  </HEADLINE>
By DINA KRAFT
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Jerusalem Day, Israel's annual commemoration of
its unification of the city, was marked Thursday with raised fists
and defiant waving of Israeli and Palestinian flags.
</P>
<P>
   As peace negotiators from both sides worked to resolve the
future status of the disputed city, the two peoples who share it
fought it out with words: ''Jerusalem is ours!'' shouted
ultra-nationalist Jews. ''No, it's ours!'' Palestinians shouted
back.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians seek traditionally Arab east Jerusalem as a
future capital. Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has maintained
that Jerusalem will remain united under the sovereignty of the
Jewish state, as it has since the 1967 Middle East war when Israel
captured the eastern sector of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Confrontations between Israelis and Palestinians became heated
Thursday when militant right-wing Jews from the outlawed Kach
movement protested in front of the Orient House, Palestinian
headquarters in east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Itamar Ben-Gvir, a Kach activist, yelled, ''Arabs get out -- it's
not your country.'' A shouting match and then scuffles broke out
between seven ultra-nationalist Jews and about 30 Palestinians
until they were separated by police. Ben-Gvir was taken into
custody, to the cheers of the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, about 40 militant Jews from the Temple Mount
Faithful group marched passed the Orient House, blowing ram's horns
and waving Israeli flags. As they went by, a Palestinian stood on a
nearby stone wall waving a large Palestinian flag while others
behind him chanted ''God is Great.''
</P>
<P>
   The status of Jerusalem is the most emotional issue to be
resolved in a final Israeli-Palestinian peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Some Barak associates have said the dispute over Jerusalem is so
complex that it might have to be left unresolved for many more
years, even if agreement is reached on all other issues, such as
Palestinian refugees and final borders.
</P>
<P>
   Although the city is no longer physically separated, a wide
ethnic and economic divide remains between its Jewish and Arab
populations, which rarely mix outside of the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Also ringing in Jerusalem Day were hundreds of teen-agers from
Israeli nationalist youth movements, who clogged the alleys of the
Old City, dancing and chanting nationalist slogans while
Palestinian residents watched.
</P>
<P>
   ''They think that if they come in and shout it will scare the
Arabs but you see, the Palestinian flag keeps waving,'' said Hassam
Rajbi, a 27-year-old Palestinian security guard. ''Jerusalem Day is
a sad day for us because they think they can keep the city
united.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ariel Sharon, head of the opposition Likud Party, called it
a day of celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jerusalem has been the capital of the Jewish people for the
last 3,000 years,'' said Sharon, after visiting the Western Wall,
Judaism's most revered site, which is in the part of the city
captured in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel more and more confident that no one can take this
Promised Land from us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
