<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NJ Supreme Court allows Continental pilot to sue over online postings </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- A Continental Airlines pilot who a federal
jury found was sexually harassed by pornography strewn about
cockpits can sue the airline on charges it failed to stop fellow
pilots from posting defamatory statements on a company computer
bulletin board, the state Supreme Court ruled Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-0 decision reinstates a lawsuit by Capt. Tammy S. Blakey,
and declares that harassment outside of the workplace is fair game
for litigation.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling allows Blakey's lawyer to take depositions, and then
requires a state trial judge in Essex County to determine whether
the remarks on the Crew Members Forum were severe enough to be
considered harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Before a trial can take place, the judge must also determine if
Continental was alerted to the questionable postings and if the
forum provided a benefit to Continental, the state's highest court
ruled.
</P>
<P>
   The court also said that Continental could avoid trial if it
demonstrated prompt efforts to correct any harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Continental issued a response that asserted ''it should not be
liable for the personal, private opinions of (Blakey's) co-workers,
completely unrelated to their employee duties made outside of her
workplace in a forum which Continental does not control.''
</P>
<P>
   The company said it believes the lawsuit will again be
dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Blakey lawyer Linda B. Kenney said Continental lawyers responded
to letters complaining about the remarks on the forum by asserting
the company had no duty or authority to act because the bulletin
board was not part of the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks appeared after Blakey filed her federal lawsuit
against Continental in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ''Certain pilots implied that she should commit suicide, that
she was money hungry, that she was a terrible pilot, that she
destroyed planes ... and none of that was true,'' Kenney said.
</P>
<P>
   Blakey, who was based at Continental's hub in Newark at the
time, was not allowed to add the forum matter to the federal
lawsuit, so she filed a lawsuit in state Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   Blakey, 40, of Arlington, Wash., is seeking unspecified monetary
damages.
</P>
<P>
   A federal jury here in October 1997 awarded her $875,000, of
which a half-million dollars was for emotional distress from a
hostile workplace. The remainder was for back pay.
</P>
<P>
   After considering an appeal by Houston-based Continental, U.S.
District Judge William G. Bassler reduced the distress award to
$250,000. He ruled the evidence did not support a $500,000 award,
which the judge said was perhaps the highest of its kind.
</P>
<P>
   Continental has appealed, so no money has yet been paid.
</P>
<P>
   Blakey took leave soon after filing her lawsuit and returned to
Continental after the verdict. She is now based in Seattle, where
she flies a wide-body jet, the Boeing 777, Kenney said.
</P>
<P>
   Her case exposed the tradition among airline pilots, nearly all
of whom are men -- of leaving lewd pictures in the cockpit, in
flight manuals, behind equipment panels and pasted in drawers.
</P>
<P>
   During the federal trial, Blakey testified she made repeated
complaints to her supervisors about ''rampant'' pornographic
pictures in cockpits, including several on which male pilots
scrawled her name, and one of a naked woman penetrated sexually
with a bloody saber.
</P>
<P>
   Continental maintained that Blakey's complaints only began when
her schedule changed in December 1991 due to seniority, and after
the company raised concerns about how many days she had missed.
</P>
<P>
   Blakey testified she was hired in 1984 and in January 1990 she
became the first woman at Continental Airlines -- and possibly the
nation -- to attain the rank of captain of an Airbus A300, a
wide-body jet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-01-00 1459 </TRAILER>
