<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Toxicity document revealed on fire-safe cigarettes  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER JORDAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Antismoking groups continued lobbying for
so-called fire-safe cigarette legislation by presenting new
evidence Thursday about the product's relative toxicity.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers, meantime, put forth a new bill that would extend by
about a year over a previously vetoed bill -- to mid-2003 -- the time
manufacturers have to get the new cigarettes on the market.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for a Tobacco Free New York on Thursday announced it
had a document ascribed to Philip Morris which concluded that
fire-safe cigarettes the tobacco company was working on would be no
more toxic than traditional cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would seem to indicate with these tests Philip Morris has
solved the problem which the governor raised in his veto message,''
said Russell Sciandra, of the Center for a Tobacco Free New York.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of increased toxicity was an objection Gov.
George Pataki raised last week in vetoing a fire-safe cigarette
bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''Results of smoke chemistry analysis, cytotoxity testing,
genotoxicity testing, and inhalation revealed only minor,
inconsistent changes,'' the document said. Philip Morris officials
later confirmed they presented the report at a scientific
conference in March.
</P>
<P>
   The antismoking groups acknowledged that the document was only
further evidence of what company officials already said -- that
initial tests that showed cigarettes with a different paper did not
present added health risks. It was used mainly to counter Pataki's
argument and to show Philip Morris would have no trouble meeting
any deadline the state sets for fire-safe cigarette sales.
</P>
<P>
   ''These test results ... give us great hope that such technology
can greatly reduce the incidence of cigarette-caused fires without
increasing the risk of cancer, lung and heart disease in smokers,''
said a letter signed by the American Cancer Society, the American
Lung Association, the League of Women Voters, New York Public
Interest Research Group and other organizations.
</P>
<P>
   A new bill from Assemblyman Alexander Grannis, a Manhattan
Democrat, also addresses toxicity. It would require tobacco makers
to certify that the changed cigarettes would be no more toxic than
those now available.
</P>
<P>
   The previous bill would have required fire-safe cigarettes to be
sold in New York in April 2002. The new bill pushes that back to
mid-2003.
</P>
<P>
   ''The governor's suggestions are ones we agree with,'' said Sen.
Frank Padavan, a Queens Republican, who said he will introduce the
same bill as Grannis. ''We will include them in the new bill and
pass it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki also cited potential illegal sales of traditional
cigarettes as a reason for his veto. Grannis' office and Padavan
said separate bills in both houses of the Legislature would deal
with bootlegging concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki is ''definitely interested'' in the new legislation, said
his spokeswoman Suzanne Morris. He is ''committed to having a bill
and passing it this session and he's hopeful that's going to
happen,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris officials reiterated their opinion that national,
and not state, legislators should address the topic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
