<HEADLINE> 'Harry Potter' Posts Casting Call  </HEADLINE>
By SUE LEEMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Warner Bros. is looking for Muggles to play Harry
Potter, the young English wizard, and his pals, ginger-haired Ron
and toothy, talented Hermione, in the first Potter film.
</P>
<P>
   Brits only -- ages 9 to 11 -- need apply.
</P>
<P>
   The casting call, on the movie's official Web site, invites
youngsters who ''look like Harry Potter, Ron Weasley or Hermione
Granger'' to send photographs and videotapes of themselves telling
a joke and reading a paragraph from one of the best-selling books
by British author J.K. Rowling.
</P>
<P>
   Filming of ''Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone,'' the first
Potter adventure, starts in Britain this summer, for release next
year. It will be directed by Chris Columbus (''Mrs. Doubtfire'' and
the first two ''Home Alone'' movies), with Steve Kloves (''The
Fabulous Baker Boys'') writing the screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros. Pictures already has tried conventional casting
methods but decided to look further afield.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Krizman, acting director of communications at the Screen
Actors Guild in Los Angeles, said the move does not mark the first
time a studio used the Internet to solicit actors. ''This is just
the electronic version of your typical casting call,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Potter books follow the exploits of an 11-year-old boy who
discovers he inherited magical powers from his parents, a pair of
wizards killed by a powerful enemy.
</P>
<P>
   In ''The Sorcerer's Stone,'' Harry leaves the world of the
Muggles -- ordinary, non-magic people -- and an aunt and uncle who
treat him like dirt, to study at Hogwarts, an English boarding
school for wizards. There he makes friends with Ron and Hermione.
</P>
<P>
   Harry is a daring scrap of a boy with dark hair and glasses --
and a distinctive, lightning-shaped scar on his forehead -- while
Ron is ''tall and thin and gangling'' with freckles, large hands
and feet, and a long nose. And the clever, spell-working Hermione?
Picture bushy brown hair, large front teeth and a bossy voice.
</P>
<P>
   At Hamley's, a huge toy store in central London, news of the
movie was received with enthusiasm. But many British kids proved
more diffident about putting themselves forward for the role.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not very good at acting,'' said Jonathan Britten, a
tousle-headed 9-year-old. ''I just like the adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten-year-old aspiring actor Alexander Darley, however, was
already a step ahead of many young Potter hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've just auditioned,'' he said. ''I sent a photo and have
already filmed a tape.''
</P>
<P>
   He's done his research, too.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going for the part of Ron Weasley, because I'm quite tall
and I've got freckles and ginger hair,'' he said. ''I think the
books are quite enchanting. They really get you involved in the
adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Rowling's first three books have passed the 30 million
mark worldwide, having been translated in 35 languages in more than
200 countries.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth Potter volume will be published simultaneously in
Britain and the United States on July 8.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.harrypotter.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-01-00 1507 </TRAILER>
