<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tycoon Denounces Putin Control Plan  </HEADLINE>
By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Almost alone in public opposition to President
Vladimir Putin, Russian tycoon Boris Berezovsky on Thursday
denounced a Kremlin plan to tighten control over the nation's
regions as a move away from democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ''What Putin is trying to do will lead to dictatorship,''
Berezovsky told a news conference. ''It's a revival of the
Soviet-style system of government.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin, who was elected president in March, has made
strengthening federal control over Russia's independent-minded
provinces a top priority. He says the plan is necessary to fix the
ailing economy and keep Russia from breaking up.
</P>
<P>
   The State Duma, or lower house of parliament, gave preliminary
approval Wednesday to three bills Putin proposed to rein in
regional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky was the only legislator to speak out strongly against
the plan, and on the eve of the vote he published an open letter
outlining his objections. The letter was widely discussed in the
Russian media.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky, who had close ties with former President Boris
Yeltsin's inner circle, said Thursday he had ''normal'' relations
with the new president and denied that his protest stemmed from a
personal rift with Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky, whose business interests range from oil to car sales
to media, was a controversial figure during the Yeltsin years.
Critics claim he wielded excessive influence from behind the
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   He said the goal of his one-man campaign against Putin's plan
was to encourage criticism from the public and the governors. Most
governors have welcomed the plan even though it erodes their power
and only a few have dared to criticize it publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are afraid to do that, and it's very bad,'' Berezovsky
said. ''I want to show them that it's necessary -- and not at all
dangerous -- to put forward their arguments against it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Putin's plan was a mistake caused by lack of experience,
not a display of an authoritarian streak.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's proposal calls for changing the composition of the upper
house of parliament, the Federation Council. The chamber is made up
of regional governors and heads of regional legislatures, but the
new plan calls for full-time, appointed legislators, which would
reduce the governors' say in federal politics.
</P>
<P>
   It also contains provisions for the president to dismiss elected
governors and dissolve local legislatures whose policies are
determined by courts to violate federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Putin says one-fifth of local laws contradict the Russian
Constitution, and many rich provinces have balked at sharing
revenues with the central government.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky claimed many Duma members were reluctant to publicly
criticize the plan for fear of alienating the Kremlin and expressed
hope that opposition would soon become strong enough to
significantly amend it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-01-00 1510 </TRAILER>
