<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Claims Rebel Reversals  </HEADLINE>
By DILIP GANGULY
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- Using newly acquired weapons including
Israeli warplanes, Sri Lanka's military halted the Tamil rebels one
mile from Jaffna, the government said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   It said the government forces were gaining the upper hand and
had killed three guerrillas in a clash near Sarasalai, a village in
the northern Jaffna Peninsula, where fighting was raging.
</P>
<P>
   Sri Lanka's reversals began April 22 when nearly 10,000 troops
gave up the Elephant Pass linking the mainland with the northern
Jaffna Peninsula, which the rebels seek as part of a Tamil
homeland.
</P>
<P>
   The debacle at the pass opened the way for the Tamil separatists
to reach the outskirts of Jaffna in the battle to recapture their
former stronghold of 1990-95.
</P>
<P>
   ''During the Elephant Pass setback we did not posses the high
degree of fire power that the (Tamil) Tigers had acquired,''
Defense Minister Anuruddha Ratwatte said on state-run television.
</P>
<P>
   But the soldiers rallied when Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga ''contacted several leaders of friendly and sympathetic
countries in getting down the latest and best weapons,'' Ratwatte
said.
</P>
<P>
   He did not elaborate on the new acquisitions. But army officers
say the troops defending Jaffna now have multiple barrel rocket
launchers which helped halt the rebel advance on the city.
</P>
<P>
   Small groups of Tamil Tiger rebels came as close as one mile
from the city center, but they were driven back, the military said.
</P>
<P>
   The military also said the air force has doubled bombing raids
after acquiring new aircraft from Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The government had imposed censorship on war reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Ratwatte, the defense minister, said he literally emerged into a
battle when he visited Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I arrived in Jaffna on May 18 unannounced, I had to jump
out of the helicopter in the dead of night because the Tigers were
shelling the Palali air base with their long range guns,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The government said that the rebels had also shelled
Kankesanturai port. The port and air base are the only supply lines
for 40,000 troops battling to prevent a rebel takeover of Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of the Palali air base would leave government soldiers
trapped in the peninsula with no land route available to leave.
Escape by sea would be unsafe with the rebels attacking the navy
ships.
</P>
<P>
   Sri Lanka's Tamil minority says it faces discrimination from the
Sinhalese majority, which controls the government and the military.
The government denies any bias.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels are trying to establish an independent homeland in
the north and east for the country's 3.2 million Tamils. The
17-year civil war has killed more than 62,000 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-01-00 1525 </TRAILER>
