<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mount Etna Spits Lava and Ash  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CATANIA, Sicily (AP) -- Mount Etna's southern crater erupted
Thursday morning after five hours of tremors, spitting out a
fountain of fiery lava and sending up a mile-high column of ash and
smoke.
</P>
<P>
   The spectacular display could be seen from nearby coastal towns.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was no danger caused by the explosion, only the fallout
of ash on the villages lying southeast of Etna,'' said Salvatore
Inguaggiato of the Sistema Poseidon, a volcano monitoring
organization in Sicily.
</P>
<P>
   The column of ash billowed more than a mile above the ground and
the stream of lava stretched for 600 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Etna's last major eruption was in 1992, but minor eruptions
occur every few months.
</P>
</TEXT>
