<HEADLINE> U.S. Jets Bomb Iraq Military Sites  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- U.S. jets bombed military sites in
northern Iraq on Thursday for a fourth consecutive day, returning
fire by Iraqi gunners, the U.S. military said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. warplanes patrolling the no-fly zone were fired upon by
anti-aircraft artillery from two sites near the towns of Bashiqah
and Tall'Afar, 250 miles north of Baghdad, the U.S. European
Command said.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft safely returned to Incirlik air base in southern
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   In Iraq, the official Iraqi News Agency quoted an unidentified
military spokesman as saying the planes bombed ''civil and service
installations.'' It said the planes dropped flares on crops in what
it called an attempt to ''cause damage to our national economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The report did not cite any casualties.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has been enforcing northern and southern
no-fly zones in Iraq since the end of the Persian Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq considers the zones violations of its territorial
sovereignty and has been challenging the patrols since December
1998.
</P>
