<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> For first time, St. Joseph's Hawk a woman  </HEADLINE>
AP Photos PADL103-104
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Sarah Brennan believes she's more than
prepared for the new role she's assuming at St. Joseph's
University. In fact, you could say her confidence is unflappable.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Brennan, a three-season manager for the men's
basketball team, this week became the first woman to be named the
school's mascot. She's the 25th person named to suit up in the
university's well-known Hawk costume.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the fact that I am a woman is a pretty big
signature,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Brennan said she's also hoping people don't just concentrate
on her gender.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope when people see me at games, people don't know whether
I'm a guy or a girl,'' said Brennan, a marketing major from Point
Pleasant, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ''But they will, I know. It's something I wanted to do when I
came here, and I know all that's involved and all the
responsibilities of carrying on this great tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Brennan's predecessors were known for some high-profile
incidents, including when the Hawk was attacked by the Rhode Island
mascot and a fan in 1998 and for a 1988 fight at the Palestra with
the La Salle Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   ''She understands people will come after her, throw stuff,''
ex-mascot Chuck Sack said. ''She has the ability to focus on the
task at hand, and we're confident that won't be an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Team officials say she will fill the Hawk's shoes admirably.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Hawk is a symbol, and we couldn't have a better symbol
than Sarah,'' said Phil Martelli, the Hawks' head coach. ''We have
a lot of great people on this campus, but she's a special cut, she
really is. As the head of the program, I'm honored to have Sarah as
our symbol.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Gallagher, son of the late John T. Gallagher, who endowed
the full scholarship awarded to each Hawk annually, helped select
Brennan and said his father would have approved. Women have applied
in the past, but Brennan was the best choice this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We knew someday we'd have a girl,'' he said. ''I mean, the
school is 54 percent women now. The person inside the costume
doesn't change the tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Don DiJulia, St. Joseph's athletic director, said Brennan fit
the part perfectly -- in every way. As is tradition, the Hawk
constantly flaps its wings during every game.
</P>
<P>
   ''Size, conditioning, flaps, the whole thing, it works,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
