<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-British Spy Seeks Book Review  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Former British spy David Shayler was complying
with the law when he handed his new book over to government censors
Thursday, but did he really need the cancan dancer or the six guys
in dark suits and sunglasses playing soccer?
</P>
<P>
   While the entourage performed on the steps of the Home Office,
Shayler's agent, Chris Joseph, delivered two copies of the former
MI5 man's novel to make sure no state secrets were compromised.
</P>
<P>
   The government obtained an injunction in 1997 to bar Shayler
from disclosing any information he obtained while working for the
agency.
</P>
<P>
   Shayler, 33 worked for MI5, the internal security agency, from
1994 until 1997. He came to public attention in 1997 when he
claimed that the agency kept files on a number of politicians
including the current home secretary, Jack Straw, and the Northern
Ireland secretary, Peter Mandelson.
</P>
<P>
   He has also said Britain was involved in a plot to assassinate
the Libyan leader, Moammar Gadhafi.
</P>
<P>
   Shayler was arrested in France in 1998 on a British warrant, but
a French appeals court rejected an extradition bid. He could face
charges of breaking the Official Secrets Act, but says he is
determined to return to Britain later this year to clear his name.
</P>
<P>
   Shayler maintains that his book, ''The Organisation,'' is a work
of fiction. It is being billed as ''a gritty thriller about spies,
sex and football.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph said the government is persecuting Shayler by insisting
his book is first read by censors.
</P>
<P>
   ''For fiction to be subject to vetting at all obviously
contravenes freedom of expression and human rights,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The government also recently filed a civil lawsuit against
Shayler, accusing him of violating his contract and copyright laws
by releasing secret documents to British newspapers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
