<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jenoff admits role in slaying of rabbi's wife  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) -- A private investigator who says he was hired
by Rabbi Fred Neulander to kill his wife admitted his role in the
attack Thursday, agreeing to testify against his co-defendants.
</P>
<P>
   In pleading guilty to aggravated manslaughter, Leonard Jenoff
said he would help prosecutors in their bid to send Neulander and
another man to prison for the Nov. 1, 1994 slaying of Carol
Neulander.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff, who originally was charged with murder and conspiracy to
commit murder, could face less than two years in prison, depending
on how cooperative he is in the prosecutions of Neulander and Paul
Michael Daniels, 27, of Pennsauken, Jenoff's alleged accomplice.
</P>
<P>
   His sentencing was delayed until after the cases against Daniels
and Neulander are resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff, 54, admitted hitting Mrs. Neulander in the back of the
head with a lead pipe in her Cherry Hill home. He provided no other
details -- about the attack or his alleged $30,000 fee -- during his
appearance before Superior Court Judge Linda Rosenzweig.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rabbi, Mr. Neulander, had paid me to arrange for his
wife's murder,'' Jenoff said.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander, 58, who founded Congregation M'Kor Shalom synagogue
with his wife in 1974, allegedly wanted his wife of 29 years dead
so he could continue having an affair with Philadelphia radio
personality Elaine Soncini.
</P>
<P>
   He believed a divorce would jeopardize his position as senior
rabbi at the synagogue. He resigned three months after the killing,
however, after reports surfaced about two extramarital affairs he'd
allegedly had with members of his congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander, who wasn't charged in the killing until 1998, says he
had nothing to do with it. He was not present in court Thursday
when Jenoff entered his plea, but his lawyers were.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Jenoff a liar, Neulander attorney Jeffrey Zucker
insisted that the killing was for reasons that had nothing to do
with Neulander.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he killed her, it was for his own motives and had nothing
to do with Fred Neulander,'' Zucker said in an interview outside
the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff, a native of Atlantic City who named teaching history as
his career ambition in his high school yearbook, worked as a
private investigator for various lawyers in southern New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   He confessed to the killing in April, telling a newspaper
reporter about his role and saying that he could no longer live
with the burden of the secret.
</P>
<P>
   Standing before the judge Thursday, shackled at the waist and
wearing orange Camden County jail-issue clothes, he answered
questions posed to him by Rosenzweig and First Assistant Camden
County Prosecutor James P. Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   The Neulanders' son, Matthew, sat in the gallery with about 10
other relatives. They declined comment afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff faces 10 to 30 years in prison for the killing. If he
gets the minimum, he could be freed on parole in one year, 11
months and one day, Rosenzweig said.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch said the state was reserving judgment on a sentence
recommendation until after the other cases are heard. Daniels'
lawyer says his client, too, is likely to plead guilty in the
killing.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff lawyer Francis Hartman acknowledged that Jenoff's
credibility will be a central issue in the trial of Neulander.
</P>
<P>
   But he disputed Zucker's comments about Jenoff, saying it was
pretrial posturing.
</P>
<P>
   ''My client is so damaging to his that he has to attack him.
This is the traditional bravado of a defense lawyer trying to
shield his client from the inevitable consequences of his
actions,'' Hartman said outside court.
</P>
<P>
   No date has been set for Neulander's trial. A conference to
discuss the trial schedule is set for Sept. 5. Lynch said no
decision has been made on whether to seek the death penalty against
Neulander.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-01-00 1601 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
