<DOCNO> APW20000601.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Car accident kills two state troopers  </HEADLINE>
AP Photo pursuing
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST HURLEY, N.Y. (AP) -- Two state troopers, looking for
aggressive drivers on a winding, two-lane road, died Wednesday
night when they tried to make a U-turn and were hit broadside by a
tractor trailer.
</P>
<P>
   Trustcott ''Michael'' Kelly, 49, and Kenneth A. Poormon, 23,
were killed in the 7:40 p.m. crash on Route 28 near Kingston, state
police said.
</P>
<P>
   The truck's driver, 53-year-old Robert Kothe Jr. of West Hurley,
suffered cuts to his head and was released from a local hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Kelly was driving the patrol car east on Route 28
when he pulled to the southern shoulder and began a U-turn to
pursue another vehicle. Kothe, also headed east, hit the cruiser in
the driver's side door and pushed it down a steep embankment off
the north side of the road.
</P>
<P>
   Both troopers were pronounced dead at the scene. Major Alan G.
Martin, commander of Troop F, said it appears both men were wearing
seat belts.
</P>
<P>
   The speed limit on that stretch of Route 28 is 55 mph. Martin
said Kothe has cooperated fully with investigators, providing blood
and urine samples and allowing an examination by a drug recognition
expert.
</P>
<P>
   ''At this point, we have no reason to suspect there was any
alcohol or drugs involved,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said the tractor trailer was in ''reasonably good shape''
and had no overt evidence of an unsafe condition that could have
led to the accident. A reconstruction expert will determine the
truck's speed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very, very dark day for the state police,'' Martin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly spent his entire 22-year career in the Kingston barracks
and his most recent assignment was to the Community Stabilization
Team, concentrating primarily on aggressive driving in the Route 28
area. An avid runner and cyclist, he organized the police torch run
for The Special Olympics. He leaves a wife and two children, ages
17 and 10.
</P>
<P>
   Poormon graduated from the New York State Police Academy in
November, trained in Auburn and was transferred to Kingston in
March. He is survived by his parents.
</P>
<P>
   The road, long a safety concern for local police, was closed for
several hours after the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ''They will be in my thoughts and prayers, as well as those of
all New Yorkers,'' Gov. George E. Pataki said in a statement.
''Their loss is deeply felt.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm ... stunned, stunned,'' Kingston City Police Chief Gerald
Keller said. ''It's one of the most horrible things to happen to
the police community around here in a long, long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the state police was founded in 1917, 108 officers have
been killed in the line of duty, 60 in motor vehicle accidents,
according to the New York State Police website. Of the 60 killed,
many were on motorcycles and some in their personal vehicles on
their way to or from work.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday in Brooklyn, a police officer and the driver of a
newspaper delivery truck were killed in a violent pre-dawn
collision as the police officer and his partner sped to answer a
report of a man with a gun.
</P>
<P>
   West Hurley is 48 miles south of Albany.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-01-00 1625 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000601.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Post office issues letter of apology to DRS commissioner  </HEADLINE>
By JUDITH FORMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The Department of Revenue Services
commissioner said he is proud of the U.S. Postal Service for owning
up to the slow certified mail service that left state income tax
payments unprocessed for two weeks last month.
</P>
<P>
   ''They did the talk,'' Gene Gavin said Thursday. ''I want them
to do the walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Gavin received a letter of apology dated May 26 from Jon M.
Steele, the post office's vice president for Northeast Area
Operations. The apology came in response to the May 11 letter Gavin
sent to Postmaster General William Henderson asking that the
certified mail process be improved nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ''This failure caused you embarrassment and loss of use of
funds,'' Steele wrote. ''I can personally assure you that will
never happen again. It should not have happened this one time. It
was wrong, and we have taken corrective action.''
</P>
<P>
   The tax returns sent by certified mail included a $10 million
check.
</P>
<P>
   Those words -- along with the post office's pledge that come next
tax season more workers will be employed to process the certified
mail -- have satisfied Gavin. And DRS and post office officials are
set to meet together three more times before the start of the next
tax season, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ''They stepped up,'' Gavin said. ''They recognized there were
some problems in their handling of certified mail. I couldn't get a
better letter.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hartford post office plans to employ six people on three
shifts -- for a total of 18 workers -- to handle the certified mail
next spring, said Christine Dugas, a spokeswoman with the U.S.
Postal Service. This year, two employees working on two shifts --
for a total of four workers -- handled the mail.
</P>
<P>
   ''Both sides are very committed to solving the problem,'' Dugas
said, adding that the post office also will continue to communicate
daily with the DRS.
</P>
<P>
   The DRS has battled with the post office since 1987 for faster
certified mail processing, Gavin said.
</P>
<P>
   The state received more tax payments this year, likely because
of capital gains. Typically, large checks, like the one for $10
million, are received by certified mail.
</P>
<P>
   This year's tax deadline was April 18, but according to the
president of the Hartford postal workers' union, mail was piling up
weeks before that date. The mail was there April 12, although the
postal service didn't start processing it until two weeks later,
said Stephen R. Peters, president of Hartford Local 147 of the
American Postal Workers Union, AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   The DRS received 46,270 pieces of certified mail from May 2-6,
with checks estimated at about $120 million. The extra money was
not discovered until after the Legislature had approved a budget
and agreed on how to spend the projected surplus.
</P>
<P>
   State Comptroller Nancy Wyman has projected a $413.4 million
budget surplus by the end of the Fiscal Year 2000 -- due in part to
the mail delay. Wyman also attributed the surplus to Connecticut's
stronger-than-expected economic growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
