<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't Tries To Curb Drug Costs  </HEADLINE>
By ALICE ANN LOVE
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government is taking action to try to
lower taxpayers' costs for drugs covered by Medicaid and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala sent letters
to Capitol Hill on Thursday telling lawmakers that Medicare claims
processors will be encouraged to lower reimbursement rates.
</P>
<P>
   The lower rates would be based on new drug price estimates
resulting from ongoing federal investigations of the pharmaceutical
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are now moving administratively to take advantage of the
newly available more accurate data on average wholesale prices
developed for Medicaid as a result of Department of Justice
investigations,'' wrote Shalala to House Commerce Committee
Chairman Thomas Bliley, R-Va.
</P>
<P>
   Bliley had written to Shalala and to several pharmaceutical
companies recently expressing concern about high drug prices paid
by government health care programs.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Pete Stark, D-Calif., another concerned lawmaker, said
''The timing of this policy announcement is particularly important
in view of the current debate about adding a (broader) prescription
drug benefit to Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicare, the nation's health insurance program for the elderly
and disabled, currently covers very few drugs -- generally, only
those that must be administered by a doctor, such as chemotherapy
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid is a state-federal partnership program providing health
care for low-income Americans and covers a much wider array of
prescriptions that can be purchased at pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
   Both programs have long based reimbursement rates for drugs on
industry guidebooks that list so-called average wholesale prices.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators say that those prices are often much
higher than what doctors and pharmacies actually pay, however.
</P>
<P>
   The HHS Inspector General has estimated that Medicare pays from
11 to 900 percent more for drugs than what it costs doctors to buy
them. Similar price discrepancies have been found between Medicaid
reimbursements and what drug stores pay.
</P>
<P>
   The result: health care providers pocket the difference at a
cost of hundreds of millions of dollars to Medicare and Medicaid
each year.
</P>
<P>
   Under government pressure, a California company called First
Data Bank, which provides a drug price guide known as the ''Blue
Book'' to Medicaid, agreed to lower its list prices for 50 drugs in
May.
</P>
<P>
   The lower prices reflect insight federal investigators have
gleaned from drug wholesalers' catalogs and other marketing
materials.
</P>
<P>
   Shalala said in her letter that HHS will encourage Medicare
claims processors to use the new, lower list prices, as well. But
current regulations do not require the use of the Blue Book over
other industry guides.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are attempting to meet with the company that publishes the
''Red Book'' which is the source of average wholesale price data
that most (Medicare) carriers have used to date,'' Shalala said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, federal and state prosecutors are continuing to
pursue possible legal action against drug companies, alleging that
they purposely inflate prices reported to the industry guidebooks.
</P>
<P>
   Drug companies have denied wrongdoing, saying the government has
long known that guidebook prices are only rough estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has asked Congress to cut Medicare
reimbursements for drugs to 83 percent of guidebook prices. In
1997, lawmakers agreed to legislation cutting the reimbursements to
95 percent from 100 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-01-00 1650 </TRAILER>
