<HEADLINE> GOP primary contenders set for final debate in race for U.S. Senate </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST ORANGE, N.J. (AP) -- The four Republicans running for the
U.S. Senate nomination have one last chance in a debate Thursday to
build their credibility and to diminish that of their opponents
with five days left before the June 6 primary.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Bob Franks, R-Berkeley Heights, and state Sen. William
Gormley, R-Atlantic, stand as the perceived front-runners by virtue
of their moderate views, their county endorsements, in which Franks
has an edge, and their money, in which Gormley has an edge.
</P>
<P>
   Most agree the contest is close. The only polls of the GOP race
have shown it to be virtually too close to call, especially with
the likelihood of a low voter turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Essex County Executive Jim Treffinger, who along with the
leaders has raised more than $1 million, is cutting into Franks'
base. To lay claim to the conservative wing of the party,
Treffinger has been waging a one-man war of words with the fourth
candidate, Ramapo College professor Murray Sabrin, a former
Libertarian who stands alone in opposition to abortion and to all
gun control measures.
</P>
<P>
   A lively topic among them is likely to be the other side of the
aisle, where Democratic hopeful Jon Corzine has shattered national
spending records with a flurry of TV commercials and opponent Jim
Florio has been raising alarms that Corzine is a threat to
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The debate is scheduled to be held at the Jewish Community
Center. It is will tentatively begin between 7:30 p.m. and 8 p.m.
depending on the arrival of all the candidates. It will be held
before a live audience that will be able to submit questions, but
it is the only debate of the five in the GOP primary contest that
will not be broadcast.
</P>
</TEXT>
