<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Little Progress In Mideast Talks  </HEADLINE>
By KARIN LAUB
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISBON, Portugal (AP) -- Israel and the Palestinians have little
to show for six months of peace treaty talks, and time is running
out for President Clinton to produce a deal that has become
increasingly elusive.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of negotiating, Israelis and Palestinians have been
engaging in name-calling and accusing each other of foot-dragging
and intransigence.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak spent much of his meeting with
Clinton on Thursday in Lisbon complaining that Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat was not making a serious effort to reach an
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat responded, saying it was Israel that was stalling the
talks, not the Palestinians. ''They are the side that is wasting
time and not moving toward peace,'' Arafat said Thursday in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat is upset that Israel has not released Palestinian
security prisoners, handed over three West Bank villages near
Jerusalem and withdrawn from additional West Bank land ahead of a
final accord, Barak was told, according to a senior Israeli
official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton listened to Barak, as he had earlier to Arafat on the
phone on Wednesday, but didn't take sides or present his own
bridging proposals, seen by both sides as a prerequisite for
breaking the deadlock.
</P>
<P>
   The president was upbeat, saying an accord was within sight. But
Clinton apparently will decide on whether to fully engage as a
negotiator only after his Mideast envoy, Dennis Ross, and Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright visit the region next week. With
presidential elections in November, the president doesn't have much
time left to help broker a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Left to their own devices, Israeli and Palestinian negotiators
have been unable to overcome deep suspicions about each other's
true intentions. They have made no measurable progress since peace
treaty talks began in November.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat insists that Israel's outstanding debts, including a
withdrawal from an unspecified chunk of land in the West Bank, must
be settled before talks can move on to reaching a blueprint for a
final treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Barak says getting bogged down now on interim issues, such as a
partial pullback, is a waste of time better spent tackling key
issues, such as drawing final borders. A Barak aide argued that in
any event, the Palestinians would get more land as a result of a
treaty framework than in yet another interim troop withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   While both leaders say they are committed to reaching an
agreement, they may also be deeply afraid of it. The concessions
required to strike an accord would be hugely unpopular among large
segments of both peoples.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat could expect an outcry across the Muslim world if he
waters down Palestinian demands of control of east Jerusalem, home
to major Islamic shrines. Barak, in turn, would face heavy
criticism at home if he grants the Palestinians a foothold in the
disputed city.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrating those constraints, Barak made a quick trip to
Portugal and back on Thursday -- 11 hours in the air, four on the
ground -- so he could be home by nightfall to attend Jerusalem Day
festivities, marking the capture of the eastern sector from Jordan
in the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
   He apparently feared that his absence could have served as
fodder for hard-liners who claim he will relinquish part of
Jerusalem in a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Frequent references to domestic constraints also serve as a
negotiating tactic, with both leaders rejecting concessions with
claims that their constituents wouldn't stand for them.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat told Clinton this week that the Palestinians could not
settle for anything less than getting all of the West Bank, Gaza
Strip and east Jerusalem -- the areas Israel captured in the 1967
Mideast war -- since Syria was being offered a return of virtually
all the land it lost to Israel at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, in turn, cited Israelis' emotional attachment to
Jerusalem as a reason for rejecting compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ''Only one who does not understand the depth of the feeling of
the Jewish people for Jerusalem ... can even consider the
possibility of an Israeli concession in part of Jerusalem,'' Barak
said in his Jerusalem Day speech.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Karin Laub has been reporting from the Mideast
for The Associated Press since 1987.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
