<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State, local officials praise fire response  </HEADLINE>
By SUSANNE YOUMANS
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- An investigation indicates the two
inmates injured in a fire at the Northern Correctional Institution
set the items inside their cell ablaze.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Heather Ziemba could not say what two men used to start
the fire Wednesday night or how they got the materials. Smoking is
not allowed in Connecticut prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Sostre, 25, is awaiting trial for the Jan. 23, 1999 fatal
shooting of East Hartford police Officer Brian Aselton. He was
treated at Johnson Memorial Hospital for smoke inhalation. Pedro
Poupart, 18, a New Haven man serving 17 months for assault on a
police or fire officer, was being treated for minor burns at the
MacDougall Correctional Institution in Suffield.
</P>
<P>
   Magazines, papers, boxes, mattresses and bedding were set ablaze
in the fire, which guards spotted during routine rounds about 7:45
p.m. in a unit housing about 50 inmates, including residents of
Connecticut's death row.
</P>
<P>
   Six guards used extinguishers to largely doused the flames. When
30 firefighters arrived about 10 minutes later, the fire was
smoldering and the inmates had been moved to another area of the
prison, Somers fire Chief Bill Meier said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The cell was fully involved, but the fire did not spread, Meier
said.
</P>
<P>
   Both prison and municipal officials said planned emergency
procedures were followed and worked well.
</P>
<P>
   ''It went like clockwork,'' said Somers First Selectman Gordon
Mello, who was leading a town meeting on funding for a new million
firehouse when his emergency pager went off. ''The first thought
that ran through my mind was 'Gee, I hope this is a test.' Then I
heard the sirens.''
</P>
<P>
   Ziemba said that at no time was public safety threatened or the
security of the prison compromised. The evacuated prisoners were
held in other secure areas of the prison for about four hours, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The firefighters never felt threatened at all,'' Meier said.
</P>
<P>
   A third inmate, Julio Gomez, 29, was treated at Johnson Memorial
after he became unruly during the evacuation and was subdued with
pepper spray, Ziemba said. The Meriden man is serving three years
for violation of probation; his record includes burglary, larceny
and drug charges.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was being evacuated for his safety and he was
noncompliant,'' Ziemba said. ''In order to get him under control
and protect him, he was restrained with pepper spray.''
</P>
<P>
   The fire marked the first time the town's firefighters were
called to the prison since 1997, when the Department of Correction
disbanded its fire department. The prison houses more than 430 of
Connecticut's worst offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Meier said his department is not usually called to minor fires
at the prison.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just the fact that we were responding led us to believe it was
a bigger fire,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the first selectman said the public was never at risk and he
remained at the town meeting, where officials gave final approval
to a $2.2 million firehouse already under construction
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt very comfortable continuing my duties,'' Mello said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
