<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft official speaks at Technology 2000 conference  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRUMBULL, Conn. (AP) -- Companies must embrace information
technology and the Internet in order to attract and retain
customers, a Microsoft executive told a group of business
executives Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Werner, regional marketing manager of Microsoft's
eBusiness Solutions Group, said many companies are having a
difficult time keeping up with technology and their competition.
</P>
<P>
   But he said doing business on the Internet is critical for
companies who hope to attract and retain customers in today's
Web-driven world.
</P>
<P>
   ''The objective is creating a faster-moving organization that's
really efficient,'' Werner said, speaking to a group of about 270
business leaders at the Connecticut Business &AMP; Industry
Association's ''Technology 2000'' conference.
</P>
<P>
   He said many companies still face the task of getting the needed
support from upper management.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be shocking to you the number of CFOs and CEOs that
we do business with that don't even own a PC,'' he said. ''That's
really kind of sad because that's reflected in their businesses a
lot of time, so you need to make sure that you're bringing your
management teams along as you may be developing your IT restructure
yourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   As more and more companies use the Web to do business, customers
have new buying expectations, including delivery of information any
time, any place and on any device, Werner said.
</P>
<P>
   Werner joked about the Justice Department's highly publicized
drive to break up Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   After state Senate Majority Leader George Jepsen spoke to the
crowd about Connecticut's difficulty in attracting enough
information technology workers, Werner said Microsoft has several
things in common with Connecticut, including an ''image problem''
and ''a problem in getting the legislature or the government to
understand their position.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Again, I think we share that common concern with the state,''
Werner joked.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the judge in the Microsoft case granted a Justice
Department request for more time to explore possible areas of
agreement on secondary issues.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft filed a legal brief Thursday that attacked the
government's proposal to break the Redmond, Wash., corporation into
two companies. There was no indication the government would
compromise on the basic proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The judge ruled April 3 that Microsoft had engaged illegally in
anticompetitive marketing practices. As a penalty, the Justice
Department and 17 states said Microsoft should be split into two
parts -- one that would develop and market the various Windows
operating systems, and the other that would take possession of
Microsoft Office and the company's various Internet properties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-01-00 1751 </TRAILER>
