<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudden arrest keeps ex-lover from court  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- A woman who had an affair -- and a
daughter -- with Albert Pirro was prevented from confronting him at
federal court Thursday when she was arrested upon entering the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro, husband of the Westchester district attorney, said he had
nothing to do with the arrest. He said he wouldn't have cared if
the woman, Jessica Marciano, had shown up as planned at the federal
courthouse in White Plains, where Pirro is on trial for alleged tax
evasion.
</P>
<P>
   ''Miss Marciano and that extremely unfortunate episode in my
life happened 17 years ago,'' he said after Thursday's court
session. ''It is a personal matter between my wife and myself.''
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Jeanine Pirro, who attended the trial as
usual, would not comment on Marciano's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Pirro complained that by linking the woman's paternity
case against him to the tax evasion trial, federal prosecutors were
aiding ''all the geeks out there trying to look into our personal
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Government lawyers brought up the paternity case, which ended
when Pirro had his DNA tested and set up a trust fund for the girl,
because Pirro allegedly claimed business deductions for $70,000 in
related lawyers' and investigators' fees. In all, he and his
brother Anthony are accused of claiming more than $1 million in
personal spending as business deductions.
</P>
<P>
   Marciano was arrested Wednesday at Newark International Airport
after she flew in from Great Britain with Pirro's 17-year-old
daughter. She told The Journal News that she had planned to attend
the trial at federal court in White Plains on Thursday and to
challenge allegations by Pirros' lawyers that she tried to extort
money from Pirro after their affair.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Pitz, a Customs spokeswoman, said Marciano was taken
into custody on a warrant from Brevard County, Fla., that was
discovered when her name was routinely run through a computer. The
Brevard County sheriff's office said Marciano had failed to pay
back her victims after a grand-theft conviction, thereby violating
parole. An extradition hearing is scheduled in Newark on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Marciano's fiancee, David Hutchison, alleged that Pirro was
behind the arrest, but Pirro called that ''absolute nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There was an outstanding warrant, and it was just a question
of time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wanted to make sure that his daughter was taken care
of and he understood she was in Hutchison's care.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rest of it is just theater,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In court on Thursday, the deputy chief investigator in Jeanine
Pirro's office, Patrick Spatafore, testified that he runs a private
investigation company on the side. He said he was hired by Albert
Pirro to check for wiretaps on phone lines at the Harrison and
Manhattan homes of Marvin Singer, a friend of Pirro.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had the work done by two contractors -- one of them
another district attorney's investigator -- and submitted a bill for
$1,077.50 to Baumeister Enterprises, one of Pirro's companies, as
Pirro directed. That company then sent him a check for the same
amount.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, prosecutors showed the jury an invoice from
Baumeister Enterprises to Singer's clothing company, Depeche Mode,
for an ''audio countermeasure survey'' for $2,693.75. Court papers
indicate they will claim that Pirro had the amount inflated,
possibly so Singer could claim a larger deduction.
</P>
<P>
   After Spatafore's testimony, defense lawyer Gustave Newman told
Judge Barrington Parker that it was ''so prejudicial, I
respectfully move for a mistrial.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Denied,'' the judge said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
