<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retired judge takes over as public safety commissioner  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- A recently retired Superior Court judge
took over as the state's public safety commissioner Thursday,
replacing world-renowned forensics expert Henry Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur L. Spada, 68, was sworn in by Gov. John G. Rowland in
front of more than 100 state officials and well wishers at the
state Capitol. He retired from the bench last month to take the
job.
</P>
<P>
   Lee announced his retirement in April after a two-year stint as
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Among Spada's top priorities for the new job: improve public
safety on Connecticut's roads and highways, hire more state
troopers and make sure the state police force has updated equipment
and facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not going to be a plotted plant,'' Spada said. ''I'm not
going to sit there as a ceremonial figure head. I expect to do work
and earn my keep.''
</P>
<P>
   Spada will serve on an interim basis until confirmed by the
General Assembly. Legislative leaders have said they expect Spada
to be easily OK'd for the $129,000 job. Spada said he expects to
hold the post for at least as long as Rowland is in office.
</P>
<P>
   Spada, who is best known for conducting a grand jury
investigation into Hartford police corruption, will oversee a
department that has a $114 million budget and more than 1,400
employees, most of whom are state troopers.
</P>
<P>
   A Hartford native who credits his upbringing in the city's
predominantly Italian-American East Side for his success, Spada
earned a law degree from the University of Connecticut School of
Law in 1957. Gov. Ella Grasso appointed him to the Superior Court
in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to find somebody with stature, someone that would
have instant respect and credibility with our troopers as well as
the public, and Judge Spada met all of those recommendations,''
Rowland said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
