<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> As hurricane season arrives, resident recalls past horrors  </HEADLINE>
By MARIAN GAIL BROWN
Connecticut Post
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILFORD, Conn. (AP) -- From inside his mother's beachfront house,
Frank Bromley watched Long Island Sound's waters churn, rise and
slam ashore.
</P>
<P>
   The breeze that felt delightful a few minutes earlier was now
howling so hard that he could feel the skin on his face and his
clothing flap -- all this while indoors.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the once-solid Silver Beach home in Milford began to
sway. The wood pilings shimmied. And the sky turned dark gray with
a pukey green undertone.
</P>
<P>
   ''The water and the wind got right out under the house and
lifted it off its foundation like it was nothing. Poof,'' Bromley
recalls. ''We were sitting at the kitchen table, me and my mother.
I can never forget that day. It was my 17th birthday: Sept. 21,
1938.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the day the house moved under Bromley's feet, and an
unnamed hurricane pummeled New England, killing 600 people, causing
$306 million in damages ($4.1 billion in 1996 dollars) and leveling
thousands of buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sept. 21, 1938. It (the house) lifted off and went right out
to sea and we never found it,'' Bromley said.
</P>
<P>
   He and his mother escaped. But for months after the devastating
hurricane, bits and pieces of the big gray wood-frame house washed
ashore. Molding. Door knobs. Flooring.
</P>
<P>
   All that remains of Bromley's boyhood summer house are two
concrete steps that led to the front door. Where the house once
stood is a barren lot oddly sandwiched between two oversized
saltboxes that are now year-round homes.
</P>
<P>
   Bromley's mother, Elizabeth Winetta West, who owned about a
dozen houses along Silver Beach in Milford, was devastated by the
damage.
</P>
<P>
   ''It broke her heart,'' Bromley said. ''She didn't want to have
any more of the beach after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Folks along the shore are hoping that they don't have to worry
about a similar storm this year. The hurricane season officially
kicks off Thursday and extends through November. And the forecast
from the country's pre-eminent hurricane expert, William Gray,
professor of atmospheric science at Colorado State University,
calls for 11 named storms, seven hurricanes, three of them
considered ''intense events.''
</P>
<P>
   The predicted total is above the long-term average, but somewhat
lower than the number of storms that struck in four of the past
five years.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Gray and his colleagues believe there is a
higher-than-average chance of a major hurricane hitting land on the
East Coast and Florida peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane belt in the United States stretches from
Brownsville, Texas, to Eastport, Me., a span of 3,500 miles
encompassing some of the most developed waterfront properties and
densely populated urban areas in the country.
</P>
<P>
   As weather watchers, amateur armchair meteorologists and
hurricane experts ponder what Mother Nature has in store, the
National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration plans to track
developing hurricanes and their storm paths on its Web site. And
several television stations in Connecticut and New York intend to
use the Internet similarly.
</P>
<P>
   ''Typically, it is next to impossible to forecast (hurricanes)
for New England. We are never in a direct path that we can say for
sure,'' said Gary Lessor, chief meteorologist with the Weather
Center at Western Connecticut State University in Danbury. ''As
much as I would like to forecast them, I won't go out on a limb
about hurricanes. They are a last-second event more than
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   To strike New England head on, Lessor said, a hurricane has to
have winds moving west to southwest. Complicating the question of
how robust this year's crop of hurricanes will be is the influence
of La Nina.
</P>
<P>
   La Nina is a condition of cooler-than-usual water in the Pacific
Ocean. Typically, during strong La Nina years, the Atlantic coast
has a better-than-average chance of hurricanes making landfall.
During El Nino years, when Pacific waters are warmer than usual,
the odds of having hurricanes in the Atlantic drop.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now, the general feeling as we move into summer is that
La Nina will begin to fade and we will move into a neutral area,
neither La Nina nor El Nino,'' said Brian Jarvinen, a hurricane
specialist with the National Hurricane Center in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Great Hurricane of 1938, Connecticut also
took a pounding from Hurricane Diane on Aug. 19, 1955. Diane, a
category 1 storm that caused $831.7 million in damages, adjusts to
$4.8 billion in 1996 dollars, making it the sixth costliest
hurricane of all time, according to the National Hurricane Center.
</P>
<P>
   As for the hurricane that Bromley and thousands of others
experienced in 1938, ''if you had that storm go through New England
today, you would probably have at least $10 billion or more in
damages,'' Jarvinen said.
</P>
<P>
   ''And that doesn't even fully adjust for new infrastructure and
new development. It would rank among the all-time worst
hurricanes,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-01-00 1800 </TRAILER>
