<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Advocates challenge NYC's enforcement of Kendra's Law  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- New York City is seeking court orders to
force mentally ill people to take medication far more often than
other communities in the state are under Kendra's Law, an advocacy
group for the mentally ill said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Figures obtained from the state by the New York Association of
Psychiatric Rehabilitation Services show that of 74 individuals
facing court orders to take medication under Kendra's Law, 55 were
sought by New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative under Kendra's law is to offer the mentally ill
packages of voluntary enhanced services not including
court-mandated medicine-taking. Of the 317 people in that category,
only 31 are in New York City, the advocacy group said.
</P>
<P>
   ''What is really outrageous is that the city of New York has
proven non-responsive,'' the executive director of the Association
of Psychiatric Rehabilitation Services, Harvey Rosenthal, said.
''The city of New York is not out there offering all kinds of
voluntary services packages.''
</P>
<P>
   However, a spokeswoman for the New York City Department of
Mental Health said she did not know how to explain the differing
proportions in how the city is enforcing Kendra's Law vs. counties
in the rest of the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have worked hard to put into place a process that is
thorough, fair and objective,'' Anne Sommers said. ''We're bringing
into care people who were caught before in the revolving door. We
are helping people who had been lost before.''
</P>
<P>
   The figures are for between Nov. 8, when Kendra's Law went into
effect, and April 24, 2000, Rosenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   The law is named in honor of Kendra Webdale, who died after
being shoved in front of a subway train by a disturbed man who had
not been taking his medication.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal, whose group opposed the court-ordered medicating of
individuals, said the good that appears to be coming out of
Kendra's Law is that county health officials are being forced to
identify the people in their communities who need psychiatric
services the most.
</P>
<P>
   If the voluntary services packages are indeed voluntary and not
being accepted because a court order would follow, Rosenthal said
that is how the mental health system should have been working --
government recognizing the people who needed help and coming up
with ways to deliver it.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 962 investigations of individuals were launched under
Kendra's Law between Nov. 8-April 24. The state reports that 571
were dismissed because no action was needed or are still pending.
</P>
<P>
   Other counties outside New York City in which court orders were
secured for the medication of people were Suffolk (six);
Chautauqua, Orange, Nassau and Rockland (two each) and Cattaraugus,
Erie, Saratoga, Sullivan and Tompkins (one each).
</P>
<P>
   In starkest contrast to the administration of Kendra's Law by
New York City (55 court orders, 31 service arrangements) was Erie
County (one court order, 77 service arrangements), according to the
state figures.
</P>
<P>
   The first court challenge to Kendra's Law has been filed in
state Supreme Court in Brooklyn by the Long Island branch of Mental
Hygiene Legal Services. It charges New York City with failing to
demonstrate in two applications for court-ordered medication that
the people in question were too ill to make a reasoned decision.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal said his group will join the claim in a
friend-of-the-court brief, as will the Bazelon Center for Mental
Health Law in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   New York City officials had no immediate comment on the suit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-01-00 1806 </TRAILER>
