<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Ends Up 182; Dow Up 130  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rallied Thursday as investors took heart
in the latest signs that rising interest rates are successfully
keeping inflation at bay. Buyers dipped into the technology sector,
snapping up shares of market leaders that have been battered in the
past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   A full slate of benign economic reports provided the spark for
the gains amid hopes that growth will cool to a more sustainable,
less inflationary pace. But with the government's jobless report on
deck for Friday morning, analysts were recommending that investors
remain cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ''We now have some indication that the economy is slowing,''
said Gary Campbell, chief investment officer at The Commerce Funds
in St. Louis. ''But it's a little too soon to pop the cork on the
champagne bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index rose 181.59 to close at 3,582.50 and
the Dow Jones industrial average gained 129.87 to close at
10,652.20.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 rose 28.21 to 1,448.81.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rose after several economic reports suggested that the
pace of the nation's economic growth has slowed a bit. On Thursday
morning, many of the nation's retailers reported lackluster sales
for May, indicating that six interest-rate increases by the Federal
Reserve are beginning to quell consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the National Association of Purchasing Management issued
a report that growth in the industrial economy slowed during May.
The report also said inflationary pressures for industrial supplies
appeared to have peaked in March.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the Commerce Department said spending on
construction projects fell 0.6 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
   The reports of moderating growth could persuade the Fed to raise
interest rates by a slim quarter-percentage point -- or perhaps to
hold them steady -- at its next meeting on June 27-28, said Michael
Moran, chief economist at Daiwa Securities America.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of an end to the Fed's long run of rate increases
helped financial stocks Thursday. Merrill Lynch rose $5.125 to $104
and PNC Financial rose $3.375 to $53.563.
</P>
<P>
   But the technology sector made the steepest gains, continuing a
tentative recovery from a long, steep decline in March and April
that knocked the Nasdaq more than 37 percent below its March 10
record. At the close Thursday, it was still off 29 percent from the
record 5,048.62.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those stocks reached an oversold level and deserved to bounce
back,'' Campbell said. ''There's no question that there's a strong
fundamental story here, although many of these stocks remain very
expensive relative to earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisco rose $4 to $60.938 and PMC-Sierra rose $16.75 to $170.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard soared $14.375 to $134.50 following upbeat
projections made at the company's semiannual meeting this week.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft rose $2 to $64.563. The company has asked for extra
time to formulate a breakup plan should a federal judge order the
company to divest its Windows operating systems business.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise development Thursday, the judge granted a Justice
Department request for more time to explore possible areas of
agreement on secondary issues. But the government would continue
its drive to break up the company.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. analyst Rick Sherlund said the stock may be
able to recover some ''lost ground'' after the judge rules and the
lengthy appeal process gets underway.
</P>
<P>
   ''This 'quiet time' in which there is not much new news on the
lawsuit could enable sentiment to improve a bit,'' Sherlund told
clients. Sherlund, among Wall Street's most influential Microsoft
analysts, has triggered several shifts in the stock's performance
in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Some traders spent the session looking ahead to the Labor
Department's May employment report, due out before the start of
trading Friday. Any signs of slower growth -- whether in a higher
unemployment rate or lower wage pressures -- should enable the
market to extend its efforts to rally.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has viewed the plummeting jobless rate as a sign that
companies would have to sharply raise wages and benefits to retain
workers. That could eventually force them to raise prices, setting
a stage for renewed inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Parry, president of the San Francisco Federal Reserve
Bank, said Thursday in Salt Lake City that central bankers were
viewing the reports with caution.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think one ought to be very careful in basing a forecast on a
handful of indicators,'' said Parry, who has a vote this year on
setting interest rates. ''Indicators do get revised.''
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 2-to-1 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where composite volume totaled 1.15
billion shares, compared with 1.14 billion on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 16.29 to
492.47.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. market drew strength from overseas markets, which were
almost uniformly higher. Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 2.2
percent. Germany's Xetra DAX index rose 2.3 percent, Britain's
FT-SE 100 gained 1.8 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 2.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
