<HEADLINE> Senator: Ambassador Nominees Charged  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. Rod Grams said Thursday that six nominees
for ambassadorial posts have been charged with security violations
during their careers in the foreign service.
</P>
<P>
   Grams, R-Minn, is a member of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee, which must pass judgment on the nominees as part of
their confirmation process. He did not name the six but said they
collectively had committed 62 violations and that one appointee was
responsible for 22.
</P>
<P>
   Grams outlined his concerns in a letter to Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   He said rewarding diplomats charged with security violations
appears to run counter to the standard Albright set a month ago
when she spoke to a meeting of State Department employees
</P>
<P>
   Albright told the gathering, ''I don't care how skilled you are
as a diplomat, how brilliant you may be at meetings, or how
creative you are as an administrator; if you are not professional
about security, you are a failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Grams said in his letter that it would help the committee as the
nominations are processed if Albright would reconcile her statement
with the fact that the president has chosen ''to reward individuals
whom you describe as 'failures' with high honors and the
responsibility of representing the United States and her interests
in foreign countries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
