<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Executive admits funneling donations to Torricelli campaign  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- A Bergen County-based executive of a South
Korean conglomerate admitted Thursday that he illegally funneled
$20,000 in donations to U.S. Sen. Robert Torricelli's 1996
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Cha-Kuek ''Charles'' Koo admitted he recruited eight ''straw''
donors at the behest of another businessman, David Chang, so their
enterprises might prosper if Torricelli was elected. Chang gave him
cash to reimburse the donors, Koo said.
</P>
<P>
   Koo is the fifth person to admit wrongdoing regarding the New
Jersey Democrat's fund-raising and has agreed to cooperate with the
Justice Department's Campaign Financing Task Force. The task force
has charged a total of 25 people regarding abuses in the 1996
elections.
</P>
<P>
   He could testify against Chang, who is accused of directing
$23,000 in illegal donations -- separate from the $20,000 -- to the
Torricelli campaign. Chang and his former aide, Audrey Yu, are to
go on trial here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Koo, 54, of Alpine, a South Korean citizen, is president of LG
Group's executive office for the Americas in Englewood Cliffs. The
LG Group is one of South Korea's largest conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli is not accused of any wrongdoing. He has maintained
he was unaware of the improper donations, which have since been
donated to charity.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli lawyer Abbe David Lowell released a statement
asserting that the ''Justice Department has confirmed that neither
the senator nor anyone in the campaign are the focus of any
investigation and not one of the people who have admitted making
these improper contributions has even hinted that anyone in the
campaign knew what they were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The head of the campaign task force, Robert J. Conrad, declined
to comment on whether Torricelli was aware of straw donations.
Conrad attended Koo's plea.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli has described Chang as a friend. As for Koo, ''They
met many years ago, but they haven't had any contact for quite some
time,'' Torricelli spokesman Richard McGrath said.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli's fund-raising ability led to his appointment as
chairman of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee. While a
congressman from Bergen County, he raised $9.2 million to defeat
Rep. Richard A. Zimmer in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Koo and his lawyer did not speak to reporters after Koo pleaded
guilty to a single misdemeanor charge of making campaign
contributions in the name of another person.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his plea bargain, Koo agreed to waive the three-year
statute of limitations on the offense in return for no further
prosecution regarding the $20,000 or Koo's efforts to obstruct the
investigation into the ''conduit'' contributions, according to
court papers.
</P>
<P>
   Such donations are structured to evade the limit on federal
campaigns -- $1,000 a candidate from a single donor for each
election -- often by illegally reimbursing the person who supposedly
made the contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Koo faces up to six months in prison, and has a chance of
getting probation, when sentenced Sept. 7 by U.S. District Judge
Alfred M. Wolin.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning in court by Wolin, Koo acknowledged that in
late 1995 Chang's companies owed LG Group more than $50 million
used by Chang to finance the shipment of goods to North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea had failed to pay Chang's companies in full, so
Chang was unable to repay LG Group, Koo said.
</P>
<P>
   Chang operated several international trading companies based in
Englewood Cliffs, including Bright &AMP; Bright, Nikko Enterprises Inc.
and Panacom Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Wolin asked if Koo agreed to make illegal contributions with
Chang ''in the hope that if Senator Torricelli were elected he
would help David Chang's companies, and therefore LG Group, recover
money he lost in trading with North Korea?''
</P>
<P>
   Koo responded yes.
</P>
<P>
   During a meeting at an Englewood Cliffs diner in December 1995,
Chang asked Koo to help raise funds for Torricelli's campaign, Koo
said.
</P>
<P>
   After Koo said he could not contribute because he was not a U.S.
citizen, Chang asked him to solicit employees at LG Group and
others who were citizens, Koo said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Chang sought the maximum from the primary and general
elections -- $4,000 from a married couple, $2,000 from an individual
-- and said he would reimburse checks solicited by Koo.
</P>
<P>
   Koo obtained checks from eight people, including seven
subordinates at LG Group, and brought them to a Torricelli
fund-raiser in mid-December 1995 at the Fort Lee Hilton that Chang
attended, Koo said.
</P>
<P>
   Chang, of Cresskill, later gave Koo $20,000 in cash, of which
Koo used $18,000 to reimburse seven of the donors, Koo said. Koo
kept the remainder as compensation for forgiving an unrelated
$2,000 debt from the eighth donor, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While reimbursing the conduit donors, Koo warned them to be
quiet about the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have pleaded guilty in connection with
Torricelli fund-raising is Berek Paul Don, a former Bergen County
Republican leader. Despite his GOP affiliation, he admitted
illegally donating $11,000 from a Chang company through other
employees in his law office, and said that Chang asked him to get
the money into the Torricelli campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Chang is accused of using the $11,000 to reimburse the straw
donors, and of reimbursing $10,000 in other donations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
