<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State seeks more time to clean air, eliminate auto inspection waits </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   EWING TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) -- Long lines at New Jersey auto
emissions testing stations continue to dog state officials.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, state authorities Thursday asked the federal
Environmental Protection Agency to give them another month to
shorten motorists' waiting time before completely changing over to
the enhanced testing system.
</P>
<P>
   EPA spokeswoman Mary Mears said Thursday the agency was likely
to agree to push the state's deadline back from the end of June to
the end of July.
</P>
<P>
   State Transportation Commissioner James Weinstein said the state
will do all it can to diminish long lines at select testing
stations to allow the new system to be installed at all sites.
</P>
<P>
   The state will continue to use the old system at seven stations
through the end of July, Weinstein said. To ease waits at those
stations once the enhanced system is finally installed there, the
state will take appointments and extend hours, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, motorists who pass the old test will receive a
one-year sticker. Those who pass the enhanced test offered at other
stations will receive a two-year sticker, he said.
</P>
<P>
   That change is a result of an agreement entered into by the
state and the New Jersey Gasoline Retailers Association. Thursday
was the state's deadline to implement the enhanced system statewide
under a lawsuit brought by the gas stations, who complain they are
unable to compete with state inspection stations that offer the old
test.
</P>
<P>
   If the state had abided by the agreement with the gas retailers
and implemented the enhanced system statewide Thursday, only 11 of
the state's 32 stations would have complied with contracted waiting
times under the deal with Parsons Infrastructure and Technology
Group, the company building and installing the new system, he said.
</P>
<P>
   If waiting times are still excessive after Aug. 1, the state may
consider changing the inspection period for motorists from one
month to one or two weeks, Weinstein said. Theoretically, that
would prevent most motorists from crowding inspection stations at
the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Taking appointments ''is a wise and smart way to deal with an
issue that would result in outrageous wait times if we did not make
this move,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The state needs the extra time from the EPA to hire and train
additional workers to set up the appointment schedule at the
beleaguered stations, which are located in the state's southern and
northwestern sections, Weinstein explained.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein said remaining delays are not nearly as bad as those
that greeted motorists last December, when Parsons inaugurated the
enhanced auto emissions system statewide. Parsons now can inspect
an average of about 12 cars per hour statewide, compared to only
about six per hour in December, he said.
</P>
<P>
   State officials were forced to partially shelve the new system
last winter after it was snowed under with frozen or malfunctioning
computer equipment. Under its state contract, Parsons has been
fined more than $1 million for excessive waiting times since then,
Weinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the appointment schedules and other improvements, the
state still projects some sporadic long waits after Aug. 1, but at
least it should be in compliance with EPA's clean air standards,
the commissioner said.
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic critics of the Whitman Administration said
Thursday that Weinstein's plan does not go far enough to alleviate
waits for motorists or lost business for private garages who offer
the enhanced test.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Whitman people keep writing checks to pay Parsons, but
taxpayers get nothing but double talk and endless delays,'' said
Sen. Garry J. Furnari, D-Essex.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
