<HEADLINE> Deacon who heard murder confession was also a state trooper  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Two days after a fatal shotgun shooting
outside a Newark fast food restaurant, David Cary sought spiritual
advice.
</P>
<P>
   Cary wanted to turn himself in, and went to his Baptist pastor
for help.
</P>
<P>
   For help, the pastor looked to a deacon in the congregation.
</P>
<P>
   The three men prayed, talked and then the deacon read Cary his
rights.
</P>
<P>
   The deacon's day job: State Police trooper.
</P>
<P>
   After his arrest, Cary wouldn't talk to Newark police and later
argued before a trial court judge that his confession should be
kept from a jury.
</P>
<P>
   But after some initial hesitation, trooper John Perry relayed
details of Cary's confession.
</P>
<P>
   However, the judge agreed with the defense and ordered the
confession suppressed.
</P>
<P>
   A state appeals court Thursday disagreed and said when Cary
confessed he told his tale to a police officer, not a cleric.
</P>
<P>
   ''Given the fact that Cary knew Perry was a state trooper and
that Perry warned Cary of his right to remain silent and searched
Cary, it is difficult to comprehend how Cary could have 'reasonably
expected' that his communication with Perry would remain
confidential,'' Judge Steven L. Lefelt wrote in the unanimous
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court ordered the trial court to continue with its
proceedings and allow Perry to give his version of Cary's
statements. Cary is charged with murder for firing gunshots into
the restaurant on Feb. 5, 1999, and striking Andre Dean. Dean later
died from the injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Several times in the court's 15-page decision, the judges
wrangled with the meaning of cleric, as defined in state law and in
Baptist orders.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's 1947 state constitution recognizes the
''cleric-penitent privilege'', but that only applies in
''confessions to clergymen and ministers,'' the court said.
</P>
<P>
   According to court papers, Cary went to the Second Baptist
Church in Bellville on Feb. 7, 1999, to speak to Pastor Lucious
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Cary waited through the Sunday service and then met with
Williams. But before meeting with Cary, Williams talked to Perry,
telling the officer that the suspect came ''to turn himself in,
because he got in trouble with the law,'' the decision reads.
</P>
<P>
   Williams later testified that Perry's role as an ordained deacon
made him a church official with duties and responsibilities similar
to that of a pastor.
</P>
<P>
   But the court said it was clear Perry was not acting as a deacon
when he put Cary up against a wall, searched him and read him a
Miranda warning before calling local police.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-01-00 1849 </TRAILER>
