<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investment Fraud Charges Levied  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A 28-state sweep by the Securities and
Exchange Commission and state securities regulators has led to over
a dozen enforcement actions involving the fraudulent sale of
promissory notes.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC said Thursday that the enforcement action, meant to
combat this practice, resulted in charges against hundreds of
individuals and businesses, who allegedly defrauded more than 3,000
investors out of hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The sweep took place over the past several weeks and culminated
in Thursday's announcement, said North American Securities
Administrators Association spokesman Myles Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   Promissory notes typically involve loans to companies made by
investors in exchange for a fixed amount of periodic income.
However, ''legitimate corporate promissory notes are not usually
sold to the general public,'' said Susan Wyderko, director of the
SEC Office of Investor Education and Assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ''If someone calls you up or knocks on your door trying to sell
you a promissory note, chances are you're dealing with a scam,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The fraudulent notes, the SEC said, targeted elderly investors,
falsely claimed the money invested was guaranteed by insurance
companies or collateral located offshore, and promised unusually
high returns.
</P>
<P>
   ''Investors must never forget the first rule of finance: the
greater the reward, the greater the risk,'' said NASAA President
Brad Skolnick. ''In today's market, there's no such thing as a
'guaranteed' 10 percent or 15 percent return.''
</P>
<P>
   In one case in Illinois, four persons and their companies are
accused of raising $114 million from hundreds of investors by
selling promissory notes in a $314 million Ponzi scheme. Other
schemes raised from $4 million to $63 million.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC advises potential investors to see if the investment is
registered with the SEC or their state. The SEC also reminded that
insurance agents cannot sell securities without a securities
license, and investors should make sure the seller dealing with
them is properly licensed.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC and the states undertook the sweep because fraudulent
notes have become a growing problem for regulators, Edwards said.
He said the investigations will continue.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.nasaa.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.sec.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
