<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Killer's life spared: Judge rejects death penalty request  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TOMS RIVER, N.J. (AP) -- A judge Thursday agreed to spare the
life of an Ocean County man who stabbed a thrift shop owner to
death during a robbery, citing the man's troubled childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Derek LeCompte, 20, faces 30 years to life in prison for the
1999 slaying of Linda Thomas, owner of The Garage Depot.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously, absolutely nothing could justify what he did. But
it is explained because of his disruptive home life. That is where
we develop love and a moral sense of responsibility,'' said
Superior Court Judge Edward J. Turnbach.
</P>
<P>
   LeCompte, who witnessed alcoholism and domestic violence while
growing up in his mother's home, was turned out by his mother and
then his father and lived in a broken-down car for a period before
he dropped out of Toms River North High School during his senior
year, according to testimony this week.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted stabbing Thomas 42 times during a May 4, 1999,
robbery that netted about $375 and some used stereo equipment. The
killing was captured on a surveillance camera videotape, but the
tape has not been made public.
</P>
<P>
   Executive Assistant Ocean County Prosecutor John J. Mercun had
urged Turnbach to sentence LeCompte to death.
</P>
<P>
   But Turnbach would not, saying the mitigating factors -- as
presented by LeCompte's lawyers -- outweighed the aggravating
factors.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Thomas, 37, the victim's husband, was satisfied with
Turnbach's finding nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   ''It helps the spirit of Linda rest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At his July 7 sentencing, LeCompte faces 30 years to life in
prison. As calculated by the state Department of Corrections, a
life term is 75 years.
</P>
<P>
   LeCompte would have to serve 85 percent of that, or 63 years and
nine months, before becoming eligible for parole. Mercun said
Thursday he would seek the maximum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
