<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Female prisoners claim male guards allowed to strip-search them  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FLEMINGTON, N.J. (AP) -- Some inmates at the state's prison for
women claim they are routinely subject to strip searches by male
guards, even though state policy requires guards of the same sex to
conduct such searches except in emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   Six current and former inmates have sued the state Department of
Corrections and officials at the Edna Mahan Correctional Facility
for Women, seeking unspecified compensatory and punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit also seeks a court order barring male officers from
conducting or viewing strip searches, as well as from frisking
clothed women without cause.
</P>
<P>
   Corrections Department spokesman Christopher Carden said the
agency would not comment on pending litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Mahan, which has areas of maximum, medium and minimum security,
has about 1,150 inmates, while less than 30 other female prisoners
are at New Jersey State Prison in Trenton, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 265 guards at Mahan, 110 are female, Carden said. The
prison is in Union Township, Hunterdon County.
</P>
<P>
   The women's prison for years has ''maintained an official policy
and custom of having male corrections officers conduct
non-emergent, suspicionless clothed body searches of female
inmates,'' according to the lawsuit, filed last month in state
Superior Court here.
</P>
<P>
   The inmates were subject to ''overly invasive and harmful''
pat-downs, and were strip-searched after showers, during room
searches and before urine tests, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   The state administrative code requires that strip searches and
body cavity searches ''be conducted in a professional and dignified
manner, with maximum courtesy and respect for the inmate's
person.''
</P>
<P>
   ''No member of the opposite sex shall be present during strip
searches and body cavity searches except medical staff,'' the code
says. An officer of the opposite sex can conduct a strip search
''under emergent conditions as ordered by the superintendent,'' it
says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
