<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attorney: Ex-Wolverine Testifies  </HEADLINE>
By JIM SUHR
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Former Michigan standout and current NBA player
Robert Traylor has testified before a federal grand jury probing a
former Michigan booster's alleged links to illegal gambling, the
player's attorney said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Fishman said Traylor appeared before the grand jurors in
the case of Ed Martin, a retired auto worker who has been a key
figure in a long investigation of possible NCAA rule violations
involving the Wolverines basketball program.
</P>
<P>
   Fishman said that as an attorney he was not allowed to hear
Traylor's testimony, given grand jury rules. He declined to
paraphrase what Traylor said during his appearance Wednesday or the
questions posed, saying only ''it has to do with the investigation
of Ed Martin.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I wouldn't be able to discuss what happened,'' Fishman said.
</P>
<P>
   Traylor plays for the Milwaukee Bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Bullock, another former Wolverine represented by Fishman,
has been subpoenaed to appear before the grand jury and will
testify perhaps within a month, Fishman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He just hasn't had a chance to set up a time yet,'' the
attorney said of Bullock, who was cut by the NBA's Orlando Magic
during training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Fishman said Traylor and Bullock have cooperated fully when
interviewed months ago by federal agents investigating Martin, and
that Traylor's testimony Wednesday apparently didn't stray.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have answered all the questions they've been asked.
They've told the truth,'' Fishman said. ''They didn't commit any
crime, didn't do anything by any stretch that's criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith Corbett, the assistant federal attorney handling the
Martin case, said Thursday that law bars him from discussing grand
jury proceedings, including who has been subpoenaed or who has
testified.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not in the position to make any comment,'' said Corbett,
chief of the organized crime and racketeering unit of the U.S.
Attorney's Office in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, 66, was banned from contact with the Michigan program in
1997 amid allegations he gave cash and gifts to players. Federal
authorities have said they have found no evidence that Martin's
alleged gambling operation included betting on Wolverines games.
</P>
<P>
   Martin was alleged to have run an illegal gambling operation
from 1988 through 1998. Published reports said Martin and his son
ran a numbers operation at Ford Motor Co.'s Rouge complex.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a plea deal reached in March between Martin, son
Carlton and federal prosecutors was scrapped, meaning Martin could
face an indictment in a gambling and income-tax case.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plea deal, Martin had agreed to detail his involvement
with the team in exchange for a reduced sentence of no more than 15
months in jail on one count each of gambling and tax evasion that
carried possible five-year sentences on each count.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's attorney, Neil Fink, said Thursday he would not discuss
the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Other former Wolverines -- the Sacramento Kings' Chris Webber,
the Indiana Pacers' Jalen Rose and the Los Angeles Clippers'
Maurice Taylor -- reportedly have been interviewed by investigators
in the past year. It is unclear whether they have been ordered to
appear before the grand jury.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-01-00 1927 </TRAILER>
