<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DiMaggio Estate: Stop Using Name  </HEADLINE>
By RACHEL LA CORTE
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Joe DiMaggio's estate is demanding a San Francisco
playground be stripped of the legendary ballplayer's name, saying
the park is not fit for the honor.
</P>
<P>
   The estate asked a federal court in Miami to order the city and
county to remove DiMaggio's name and destroy any playground
letterhead, promotional material or signs using his name.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint, filed Wednesday on behalf of DiMaggio, LLC., also
asks for unspecified damages.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees Hall of Famer and his brother Dom, an
All-Star outfielder for the Boston Red Sox, played in the park as
children. But the estate contends it is now rundown.
</P>
<P>
   ''The plaintiff doesn't believe that it's a fitting park or
place that should carry the DiMaggio name,'' said Miami attorney
Jeffrey Herman.
</P>
<P>
   Morris Engelberg, a trustee and attorney for DiMaggio's estate,
said naming North Beach Playground after DiMaggio ''is both morally
and legally wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I promised Joe, not only during the years I was with him but
also on his deathbed, to protect his name at whatever sacrifice to
myself,'' Engelberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Joe DiMaggio died last year at his home in Hollywood, Fla., at
age 84.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint includes charges of false endorsement and federal
trademark dilution.
</P>
<P>
   ''The defendant should not be given carte blanche to name the
city junk yard, the city waste dump, in this case the North Beach
Playground, or any other such facility after Joe DiMaggio, without
consent,'' it reads.
</P>
<P>
   Gavin Newsom, a member of the San Francisco Board of
Supervisors, said the complaint's description of the playground was
insulting.
</P>
<P>
   ''That he would relate it in any way to a city dump or a waste
yard is an outrage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Newsom said that a $3.5 million renovation is to begin on the
park this month.
</P>
<P>
   The playground was named Joe DiMaggio North Beach Playground in
February 1980, however the name was not official until this past
May 5, when San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown approved it.
</P>
<P>
   Newsom said name change ''fell through the cracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Engelberg has said he's just trying to protect the value of the
DiMaggio name. Allowing use of the name without permission dilutes
that value, causing financial problems for the estate, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Newsom noted that Engelberg has signed a $2 million book deal
about his relationship with DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unfortunately, we're dealing with someone who can potentially
gain from this controversy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dom DiMaggio has said that he has no problem with the park using
DiMaggio's name.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's where we played as kids. It's only a block from where
we lived,'' he said recently.
</P>
<P>
   However, the complaint notes that Dom DiMaggio does not speak
for the estate and ''was not even included in the will.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Dominic DiMaggio owns real estate in the North Beach
Playground area which would benefit from the use of the Joe
DiMaggio name in the neighborhood,'' the complaint reads.
</P>
<P>
   The 2.5-acre park has tennis courts, a swimming pool, playground
equipment and a bocci court.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco adopted a resolution in March 1999 to memorialize
DiMaggio. In a letter to Engelberg last June, Newsom suggested 10
sites, including the North Beach Playground, the San
Francisco/Oakland Bay Bridge and the San Francisco Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Engelberg wrote back saying DiMaggio's first choices would have
been the bridge and the airport.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Newsom in February, Engelberg again said he did
not approve of naming the playground in honor of DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   The city attorney's office in San Francisco has said Engelberg's
concern can extend only to the commercial use of the name and
doesn't extend to the city naming a public site after someone. And
the mayor agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will prevail in any legal challenges coming from Mr.
Engelberg,'' said Ron Vinson, Brown's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing before U.S. District Judge Joan Lenard has not been
set.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-01-00 1928 </TRAILER>
