<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Committee approves school construction bill; final passage uncertain </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Costs would be capped and building plans
subject to legislative review under a new version of the school
construction bill released by a key Assembly committee Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the bill, which limits total spending by poor districts to
$6 billion and suburban districts to $2.5 billion, faces an
uncertain future before the full Assembly Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly Appropriations Committee Thursday released the bill
by a party line tally, 7-4. More significantly, members did so
without recommendation, sending a signal to the full Assembly that
they held their noses when they voted.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, who control the lower house, said they were
disturbed by the measure's massive pricetag, despite the inclusion
of a spending cap.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, Democrats protested the spending limits and the
prospect of legislative oversight, saying such controls may doom
the bill to the constitutional scrapheap.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican spokesman said later it is unclear whether the bill
will pass with the minimum 41 votes Monday. If it doesn't, it's
unclear how the Legislature will meet the state Supreme Court's
spring deadline to provide full state funding to replace or repair
crumbling, overcrowded school buildings in the state's poor
districts.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess for some Republicans, they still have qualms. If
that's the party position, there could be problems,'' said Assembly
GOP spokesman Chuck Leitgeb, who also laid blame for the bill's
questionable prospects at the feet of opposing Assembly Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly version differs from a bill already passed by the
Senate in the following ways:
</P>
<P>
   -- Spending cap. Although both bills assume total spending will
come in around $15 billion, including interest, only the Assembly
has put in a cap. Assembly sponsors used state Department of
Education estimates to place a $6 billion spending ceiling on the
30 so-called special needs districts, and a $2.5 billion cap on all
other schools.
</P>
<P>
   -- Legislative oversight. The Senate bill is silent on this
issue. In the Assembly, lawmakers want to have final say over any
projects in districts in which the state is paying the full share.
</P>
<P>
   -- Community development. The Assembly version does not contain
this Senate proposal to enable six pilot cities to dovetail
economic development projects around newly built or renovated
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's debate featured criticism of the bill from several
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   David Sciarra, director of the Education Law Center who sued the
state on behalf of the poor school children, said the amendments
may run afoul of recent Supreme Court rulings.
</P>
<P>
   ''The last thing we need is to go back to court,'' he said. ''We
don't want more litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Legislative oversight ''would become redundant at least and
unconstitutional at worst,'' said Assemblyman Joseph Charles,
D-Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   Education Commissioner David Hespe also expressed doubts about
the constitutionality of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''The caps ... are without rhyme or reason,'' said Trenton Mayor
Douglas Palmer, whose school district is considered special need.
''Also, going back for legislative approval is retarding the
process.''
</P>
<P>
   But Assemblyman Joseph Malone, R-Burlington, defended the
amendments as necessary to keep costs in line. He also justified
forcing high state aid districts to surrender local control of
building projects to the state, a mandate not forced on districts
that receive less state aid.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman Leonard Lance, R-Hunterdon, took the opposite
tack. While he voted for the bill, he said he is philosophically
opposed to the state taking on such a huge debt without voter
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Both Senate and Assembly versions contain 100 percent state
funding for the special needs districts as mandated by the court.
But that guarantee is now in doubt with the possibility that
lawmakers could veto state-aided projects in poor districts.
</P>
<P>
   Both bills allow some school districts that previously borrowed
money to pay for construction projects not yet commenced to be
eligible for state aid. The more affluent schools will be eligible
for state grants of at least 40 percent, the minimum aid level in
both bills.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-01-00 1942 </TRAILER>
