<DOCNO> APW20000601.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Lost Colony' Production To Open  </HEADLINE>
By ESTES THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANTEO, N.C. (AP) -- The 63-year-old production of ''The Lost
Colony'' will be spiced up with an extra kiss and more romance in
hopes of drawing a younger audience to the drama about the English
settlement that vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance has been declining at the outdoor theater on Roanoke
Sound, in sight of the towering Jockey's Ridge sand dune and the
condos at Nags Head. Last summer, attendance was 74,000, down from
98,000 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The production, which opens Friday and runs through Aug. 25, is
considered the country's longest-running outdoor drama with a
professional company of actors. Launched in 1937, the play closed
only during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Salgado, a former dancer and singer in the production and
now its chief executive, wants to attract 100,000 people this year.
She decided to emphasize the characters' romance after observing
the popularity of two hit movies that did much the same thing --
''Shakespeare in Love'' and ''Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I've got this group on the beach, and if we're not
entertaining we won't get them,'' Salgado said. ''We're trying to
market to the twentysomethings, to walk that fine balance between
educating and entertaining.''
</P>
<P>
   Billboards and flyers feature lead characters John Borden and
Eleanor Dare in a near embrace as they gaze into one another's
eyes. Borden and Dare are star-crossed lovers -- she's an aristocrat
and he's a farmer.
</P>
<P>
   The drama goes back to 1587, when English colonists landed in
North America and the first English child, Virginia Dare, was born
in the new world. The colony disappeared, leaving as the only clue
the word ''Croatoan'' carved on a tree.
</P>
<P>
   ''It deals more with passion and emotion than skin and sexual
sensation,'' said director Drew Scott Harris. ''What we lack in
exposed skin, it makes up in exposed hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   In the play, Dare arrives in the New World pregnant, although it
is unclear whether her husband, who gets killed, is the baby's
father. Dare once was portrayed as weak and dependent, but this
year is seen as a gutsy woman.
</P>
<P>
   Playwright Paul Green's work is ''a very literate script,''
Harris said. ''A lot of the emotional stuff is not sitting there on
top of the words. You have to dig into the words.''
</P>
<P>
   Old-timers have told Harris the original play was ''wild with
emotion.'' But over the years, the play turned into a drier
historical drama focusing on the mystery of the colony's
disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   One difference this year will be the extra kiss between Dare and
Borden. The smooch occurs in the first act to whet romantic
appetites before the original second-act kiss. Harris also gives
Native American characters cleaner diction, instead of portraying
them as illiterate savages as former productions have.
</P>
<P>
   Another character adjustment involves the Indian chief Wanchese.
In the past, he was portrayed as a villain, but this year his
character will have more feeling as well as a family.
</P>
<P>
   The production is prey to the Outer Banks' sometimes oppressive
summer heat and humidity. The audience sits outside and actors
change in uncooled dressing rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Only the costume designer and stitchers have an air-conditioned
work space, where the costumes also are kept, including the
60-pound skirt worn by the queen and Chief Manteo's cape, covered
with more than 3,000 pheasant feathers.
</P>
<P>
   The humidity and salt air also mean a dozen or more loads of
laundry are done daily and actors cannot wear microphones, but must
use ground mikes.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Lost Colony site: www.thelostcolony.org
</P>
<P>
   National Park Service, Fort Raleigh:
www.nps.gov/fora/raleigh.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
