<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP primary contenders in final debate in race for U.S. Senate  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST ORANGE, N.J. (AP) -- The four Republicans running for the
U.S. Senate nomination took their last chance before the June 6
primary to build their credibility and to diminish that of their
opponents at a debate here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Bob Franks, R-Berkeley Heights, state Sen. William
Gormley, R-Atlantic, Essex County Executive Jim Treffinger and
Ramapo College professor Murray Sabrin faced off before their first
live audience at the Jewish Community Center. It was the only one
of their five debates not to be broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Franks and Gormley stand as the perceived front-runners by
virtue of their moderate views, their county endorsements, in which
Franks has an edge, and their money, in which Gormley has an edge.
To lay claim to the conservative wing of the party, Treffinger has
been waging a one-man war of words with the fourth candidate,
Ramapo College professor Murray Sabrin, a former Libertarian who
stands alone in opposition to abortion and to all gun control
measures.
</P>
<P>
   Most agree the contest is close. The only polls of the GOP race,
which are now weeks old, have shown it to be too close to call,
especially with the likelihood of a low voter turnout Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A lively topic among them is likely to be the other side of the
aisle, where Democratic hopeful Jon Corzine has shattered national
spending records with a flurry of TV commercials and opponent Jim
Florio has been raising alarms that Corzine is a threat to
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
