<HEADLINE> Judge Lowers Bail for Phillips  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) -- A judge reduced bail Thursday to
$130,000 for Lawrence Phillips, the former NFL running back accused
of beating his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Hills Superior Court Judge Linda Lefkowitz agreed to a
defense request to cut Phillips' bail from $630,000, which another
judge set Wednesday at the recommendation of prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips, 25, is charged with three felony and three misdemeanor
counts for the alleged beating at his Beverly Hills home Saturday.
He remains in custody.
</P>
<P>
   The former Nebraska star's girlfriend was treated at the scene
for her injuries, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips is charged with felony counts of corporal injury to a
cohabitant, making a terrorist threat and conspiring to dissuade a
witness. The misdemeanor counts involve having a concealed firearm
in a vehicle, carrying a loaded firearm and vandalism with damage
under $400.
</P>
<P>
   A first-round draft choice of the St. Louis Rams in 1996,
Phillips was later released for insubordination. He was
subsequently released by the Miami Dolphins after a misdemeanor
battery conviction in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   He revived his career with stellar play in NFL Europe last year
and was signed by the San Francisco 49ers, only to be cut for
missing practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
