<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Plans Retreat  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- With U.N. peacekeeping operations under
fire, Secretary-General Kofi Annan and Security Council members
planned a weekend retreat Friday in an effort to figure out what
has gone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The informal meeting -- the second one in as many years -- comes
at a crucial time for the organization, which is still reeling from
the seizure of 500 U.N. peacekeepers in Sierra Leone but is also
gearing up for the deployment of a 5,500-strong mission to the
Congo and a doubling of its force in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're right in the middle of important missions and more
coming up,'' John Ruggie, Annan's special adviser, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary-general ''wanted to take this opportunity, before
we deploy in Congo and Lebanon, to see what lessons ... we learned
from the recent cases that we should be applying.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruggie said the retreat at the Rockefeller estate in Pocantico
Hills, New York, would give the council a chance to discuss the
details of peacekeeping policy that fail to get addressed in daily
deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leone is certain to feature prominently in the weekend
discussions of the 15 council ambassadors, as it represents the
most serious threat to international peacekeeping since the U.N.
debacle in the 1994 Rwanda genocide.
</P>
<P>
   Rebels of the Revolutionary United Front, who signed a peace
agreement with the government last year, took the U.N. peacekeepers
hostage last month and held them for more than three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has said the rebels were able to take
advantage of the young U.N. mission sent to oversee the peace
agreement because the troops volunteered by member governments --
many from poor African countries -- arrived without proper training
or equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said Thursday that during the weekend retreat, he would
raise the issue of better equipping and preparing U.N.
peacekeepers, particularly with a dangerous mission coming up in
the Congo.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe they will need to go in with heavier equipment -- not
necessarily to do battle, but sometimes you need to show force in
order not to use it,'' Annan said in Atlanta during an hourlong
forum on CNN. ''You have to have a credible presence so that they
don't even dare to challenge you.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan has been increasingly critical of the Western response to
the peacekeeping challenges facing the United Nations, saying the
organization cannot be expected to keep the peace in Security
Council-mandated missions if council members such as the United
States aren't willing to finance them.
</P>
<P>
   He has also recently said the United Nations needs to review how
it decides to deploy peacekeeping missions and under what
conditions it sends troops into the field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-01-00 2027 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
