<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AM-NY--Inmates Defended, 1st Ld-Writethru,0319  </HEADLINE>
Jury acquits 3 inmates in 3 weeks
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMIRA, N.Y. (AP) -- A state prison could have intervened in the
case of a 21-year-old inmate who claimed the plastic shank he
possessed was for self-defense against a former cellmate who tried
to molest him, a jury ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's acquittal of the promoting prison contraband charge
against Kareem Young, an inmate at Elmira Correctional Facility,
keeps Young from having an additional seven years added to his
current five-year sentence for burglary.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third time in three weeks that a Chemung County jury
has acquitted an inmate at the maximum security prison on a charge
that would have extended his sentence. And Chemung County Public
Defender Richard W. Rich Jr. says the acquittals reflect the
injustices that sometimes occur within prison walls.
</P>
<P>
   Young was charged with possessing a plastic shank during a fight
with an inmate in a shack in the prison's recreation field.
</P>
<P>
   Rich said Johnson had a history of problems with the inmate,
Patrick Johnson, while they were sharing a cell at the prison, and
that Johnson allegedly tried to molest Young in their cell.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had subsequently been moved by correction officers into
a different cell, Rich said, and Young had told staff before the
fight that he feared for his life because Johnson had threatened
him, Rich said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Young did everything he could to report the thing before it
happened,'' Rich said.
</P>
<P>
   Rich successfully defended two other inmates in unrelated cases
during the last three weeks. On May 25, a jury found 31-year-old
Michael Henriquez innocent of assaulting another inmate. He was
facing life imprisonment if he was convicted, Rich said.
</P>
<P>
   On May 16, Rich argued that a correction officer had planted a
weapon on Elmira Correctional Facility inmate Dean Andrea, 27,
because the officer had a grudge against Andrea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-01-00 2029 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000601.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Packers To Release Chmura  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- The Green Bay Packers will release tight end
Mark Chmura on Monday, the Milwaukee Journal Sentinel reported on
its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Citing an anonymous source ''closely connected to the matter,''
the newspaper said Thursday the Packers plan to cut ties with the
former All-Pro who was accused of sexually assaulting a 17-year-old
girl at a post-prom party on April 9.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Chmura, 31, and Robert Gessert, 43, were
ordered to stand trial in Waukesha County on third-degree sexual
assault charges.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay general manager Ron Wolf was out of his office
Thursday afternoon and was not immediately available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Chmura's agent, Eric Metz, could not confirm the report.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've read a million reports that say he's going to get cut,''
Metz said Thursday. ''But I haven't heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Metz said Chmura, who declared his innocence earlier this week,
plans to speak publicly Saturday about his future in football and
in court.
</P>
<P>
   Chmura's release has been widely expected since shortly after
the incident.
</P>
<P>
   By releasing Chmura after June 1, the Packers will gain $900,000
in salary cap room that could be used to sign free agents. Chmura
signed a five-year, $15 million contract -- which included a $3
million signing bonus -- during the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   Chmura, who became one of the game's elite tight ends during the
Packers' run to consecutive Super Bowl appearances, missed all but
two games last season with a neck injury that caused partial
paralysis in his arms and threatened to end his career.
</P>
<P>
   Metz said he hasn't considered whether Chmura will have a future
in football beyond the Packers. Metz publicly urged his client to
retire last season because of his injury.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Packers' decision could be based more on their
concerns about his health than his guilt or innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't assume anything in this business ... but I also
assume that he's innocent too, and that he'll be acquitted on all
charges,'' Metz said.
</P>
<P>
   ''And what happens when he's acquitted of all this? Are they
releasing him because of (the incident)? Are they releasing him
because of the injury? That's going to be the speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   Chmura was planning to play in the upcoming season before his
arrest. Prosecutors say Chmura had sex with the 17-year-old girl --
who was once a baby sitter for Chmura's two children -- in a
bathroom at Gessert's home without her consent. An 18-year-old
woman said Gessert fondled her while they were in a hot tub.
</P>
<P>
   Chmura, who faces a 10-year prison sentence and a $10,000 fine,
is due back in court on June 23 to enter a plea. No trial date has
been set.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers began planning for Chmura's departure less than a
week after his arrest. They selected tight end Bubba Franks with
its first-round draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   Chmura did not participate in the team's two minicamps since his
arrest and wasn't expected at the team's fourth and final minicamp,
which begins Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In seven seasons with the Packers, Chmura became one of Brett
Favre's favorite targets, catching 188 passes for 2,253 yards and
17 touchdowns. Favre said Chmura's absence last season was a strong
factor in the Packers' slump to an 8-8 record that cost coach Ray
Rhodes his job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-01-00 2031 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000601.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
