<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaragua, US Said To Fix Military  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) -- After 21 years, the United States and
Nicaragua have normalized their military relations, Nicaragua's
ambassador to Washington said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government accredited former Sandinista officer Brig.
Gen. Manuel Salvatierra as military attache to the Nicaraguan
Embassy in Washington on Wednesday, Nicaraguan Ambassador Francisco
Aguirre Sacasa said Thursday by telephone. The U.S. State
Department was unavailable for immediate comment.
</P>
<P>
   Nicaragua and the United States had a tense relationship during
the 10-year leftist Sandinista regime, which had close ties to Cuba
and the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-Nicaraguan relationship improved dramatically after the
Sandinistas were deposed in 1990 in an election and were replaced
by a pro-U.S. government. Relations became much closer after
Hurricane Mitch in 1998, when the U.S. government sent 1,700 troops
to Nicaragua to help build roads and build health clinics.
</P>
<P>
   ''This has a tremendous symbolic impact, because it's the
finalization of the last traces of the Cold War between the main
world powers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A Sandinista fighter in the 1970s, Salvatierra became a top
military official in the 1980s, when his forces were fighting the
U.S.-backed ''Contra'' rebels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
