<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Targets Chechnya's Mountains  </HEADLINE>
By LYOMA TURPALOV
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUDERMES, Russia (AP) -- Russian forces pounded Chechnya's
mountains with warplanes and artillery Thursday, trying to drive
hundreds of rebels out of their strongholds, the military said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials in Chechnya also claimed that Aslan Maskhadov,
the elected president of Chechnya, had been wounded in the most
recent fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov was wounded overnight outside the village of Malye
Shuani in the Nozhai-Yurt region, where Russian forces have
directed much of their bombing and shelling, said a spokesman in
Gudermes, Chechnya's second-largest city, which is under Russian
control.
</P>
<P>
   The report could not be confirmed independently. Russia's chief
military spokesman on Chechnya, deputy chief of the general staff
Gen. Valery Manilov, said the report was ''on the level of rumors
that require confirmation.''
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov commanded the Chechen forces that drove Russian troops
out of the separatist republic in the 1994-96 war. But since
becoming president he has been unable to exert control over Chechen
warlords and Russian officials have said he has only several
hundred fighters under his command.
</P>
<P>
   Manilov estimated Thursday that about 2,500 rebels ''capable of
vigorous actions'' remain in Chechnya. The rebels have been
concentrated in the mountains since the bulk of the fighters fled
the capital Grozny in early February, but have continued to mount
sporadic attacks in Grozny and elsewhere in Russian-held territory.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 600 fighters had been surrounded in the rugged region
around Nozhai-Yurt in southeastern Chechnya. Russian ground troops
were refraining from close-quarters fighting with the militants,
trying instead to pinpoint rebel positions for air and artillery
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has relied on that tactic throughout the nine-month
campaign to subdue the rebellious republic.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops launched a major operation Monday to clear the
region and the neighboring district of Vedeno of rebels. The area
has been a stronghold of resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Russian losses have reached 2,331 killed and 6,798 wounded since
fighting in the North Caucasus region of Russia began in August,
Manilov told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Manilov said Russian troops in May killed 393 rebels and
destroyed about 100 rebel vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The military has often exaggerated the damage it has done to
militant formations and their equipment, and the claim could not be
verified.
</P>
<P>
   Although the rebels have not mounted large-scale operations
recently, they have stepped up ambushes that have inflicted serious
casualties on the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the second-ranking Russian civilian official in
Chechnya, Sergei Zveryev, was killed when remote-controlled bombs
blew up his car on the outskirts of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb attack underscored the rebels' ability to hit back in
areas long under nominal Russian control. Russian officials say
some rebels have melted into the civilian population.
</P>
<P>
   Russia also blames Chechen rebels for the explosion that killed
three soldiers in the southern Russian city of Volgograd on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops, whom the rebels pushed out of Chechnya in
1994-96, re-entered in September after Chechnya-based militants
seized villages in Dagestan and after about 300 people died in
apartment bombings the government blames on Chechens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-01-00 2118 </TRAILER>
