<DOCNO> APW20000601.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP primary contenders have final debate in race for U.S. Senate  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST ORANGE, N.J. (AP) -- The four Republicans running for the
U.S. Senate had one final chance to blitz each other before the
June 6 primary here Thursday, but a restrictive debate format
watered it down.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Bob Franks, R-Berkeley Heights, state Sen. William
Gormley, R-Atlantic, Essex County Executive Jim Treffinger and
Ramapo College professor Murray Sabrin now head their own ways to
hit the street and perhaps the airwaves to impress undecided
Republicans and to make sure the people in their corners show up
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Franks and Gormley stand as the perceived front-runners by
virtue of their moderate views, their county endorsements, in which
Franks has an edge, and their money, in which Gormley has an edge.
Treffinger has joined the leaders by raising more than $1 million
while Sabrin, the former Libertarian, stands alone in the pack by
opposing abortion and all gun control laws.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to lay claim to the party's conservatives,
Treffinger has been waging a one-man war of words with Sabrin.
However, little of it surfaced Thursday before about 200 people at
the Jewish Community Center here. It was the last of five debates
and the only one not broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Most agree the GOP primary contest is close. The only polls
taken showed it to be virtually too close to call, especially with
the likelihood of a low voter turnout.
</P>
<P>
   The format kept the candidates from hacking at one another and
also gave them no chance to provide contrasting answers on the same
issues. Many of the questions veered toward foreign policy matters
that have had a minor role in this campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Some questions, however, did lead candidates into tricky ground.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about campaign finance and his donations from casino
industries, which are prohibited for state office candidates,
Gormley ducked the specific question and said he had always worked
for the best interests of the constituents of his Atlantic
County-based district. ''That's the main criteria,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Franks, who has criticized Gormley for casino donations, had no
opportunity to continue that attack Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Treffinger, who has supported the use of school vouchers in
struggling urban districts, took it a step further Thursday by
claiming such vouchers would actually save taxpayers money because
parochial school tuition in Jersey City, for instance, costs less
than the per-pupil costs of the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Franks said the Kosovo operation required the approval of
Congress and lacked a defined mission and ''exit strategy.'' Sabrin
took it further, denouncing the entire air war. ''We actually
killed more people with our own bombs than the Serbians killed in
Kosovo,'' he charged.
</P>
<P>
   The debate had a light moment when one panelist referred to
''Professor Gormley.'' Gormley drew laughs when he started
clowning, signaling a ''time out'' and pantomiming a wall between
himself and the actual professor, Sabrin.
</P>
<P>
   Sabrin opposes gun control laws. ''NRA,'' Gormley said, pointing
to Sabrin, then pointed to himself, adding, ''No NRA.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-01-00 2147 </TRAILER>
