<DOCNO> APW20000601.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crash Survivors Mark Anniversary  </HEADLINE>
By MELISSA NELSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- One year after the crash of American
Airlines Flight 1420, survivors marked the anniversary Thursday
with a memorial service and their first look at the charred
wreckage of the jetliner.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was amazing to me after seeing the plane that so many of us
were able to survive, that we were able to make it out,'' said
survivor Jeff Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold, of Anchorage, Alaska, spent two hours in the hangar
housing the wreckage looking for seat 8D, in which he remained
unconscious for 40 minutes after the crash.
</P>
<P>
   The MD-82, carrying 145 people, careened off the runway after
landing in Little Rock in a late night thunderstorm. Eleven people
were killed, including the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Another survivor, Mohammad Abdel of San Jose, Calif., said
seeing the plane brought back the smell of the jet fuel that
drenched him during the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know if there's any good answer to why I wanted to see
it, except for there's some kind of attachment to the plane,'' said
Abdel, who suffered minor injuries in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Rowe said viewing the wreckage brought people closer
together.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was very emotional. There were a lot of tears, a lot of
hugs and people were amazed that we were able to get out,'' she
said after looking for how she escaped the burning wreckage from
Row 14.
</P>
<P>
   During a morning memorial service, survivors dropped 11 white
wreaths into the Arkansas River, two miles from the airport. They
also released 11 doves and a bugler played taps.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are all friends of the heart, not just numbers on a
passenger manifest or names in the latest news report,'' survivor
Charles Fuller told more than 200 survivors and family members at
the gathering. Fuller's 14-year-old daughter, Rachel, died from
burns suffered in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Some survivors said their anger toward the airline over the
decision to land in the violent thunderstorm was part of the reason
they attended the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not going to be quiet about the need to see changes in
airline policy and procedures,'' said Kristy Sheridan of Koppell,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines Vice Chairman Robert Baker represented the
airline but did not speak at the memorial.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a sad day for our American family. We are out here to
offer support. We hope our being here is a demonstration of respect
for all those families and what they have been through,'' he said
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board has not determined a
cause of the accident. Investigators are considering weather, pilot
error, mechanical failure or a combination of factors.
</P>
<P>
   While the survivors and their families gathered for the tearful
reunion, lawyers representing some of them in lawsuits against
American were in a federal courtroom blocks away. U.S. District
Judge Henry Woods said 34 passengers have settled lawsuits against
the airline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
