<HEADLINE> Clinton Considers Retreat Location  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID A. LIEB
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- President Clinton is considering
establishing a rustic retreat in his childhood hometown of Hot
Springs that would be connected with his planned presidential
library and policy center.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations have begun with relatives who own the estate of
Clinton's late uncle, Raymond Clinton, the library's fundraiser,
Skip Rutherford, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we're considering is a retreat location associated with
the programming of the policy center,'' Rutherford said. ''But
we're in the very early stages of negotiations on this particular
site.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the library, which is to be built on land purchased by
the city of Little Rock, the land for the retreat would be bought
with private funds, Rutherford said.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-acre site includes a five-bedroom home with a screened
porch, lots of trees and a boat dock on Lake Hamilton, Rutherford
said. The property is about 50 miles southwest of Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Hot Springs already is the site of the William Jefferson Clinton
Cultural Campus, which is being developed at the former high school
Clinton attended. The school moved more than 30 years ago and the
building has been vacant for years.
</P>
<P>
   ''When one looks at a retreat location, Hot Springs is a natural
and this property is a natural,'' Rutherford said. ''What makes the
site attractive is you walk in the middle of the site and you could
be anywhere rural in the world. You don't know there is a world out
there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
