<HEADLINE> Ecuador Grants Amnesty In Coup  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Congress has granted amnesty to
participants in January's military-backed Indian uprising that
toppled President Jamil Mahuad.
</P>
<P>
   But the move, approved late Wednesday by 90 of the 123
congressmen, only covers criminal prosecution in civilian courts.
</P>
<P>
   The military is still pursuing its own charges against 113 of
its members, most of them colonels, who joined hundreds of Indians
on Jan. 21 in a takeover of the Congress building and proclaimed a
short-lived junta.
</P>
<P>
   The insurrection led to Mahuad's ouster. He was replaced by his
vice president, Gustavo Noboa, who on April 12 asked congress to
grant the amnesty.
</P>
<P>
   Noboa told reporters Thursday that the ''amnesty is important,
but we must continue the dialogue with all social groups in the
country so that all understand that peace brings progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the fate of the officers still facing possible court
martials, Noboa said, ''That is in the hands of the military
courts. I respect each jurisdiction, just as I would like them to
respect me.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Noboa accepted the resignation of three members of
the military high command, which made no attempt to put down the
uprising.
</P>
<P>
   Military tribunals are trying 17 officers for their part in
Mahuad's unconstitutional overthrow.
</P>
</TEXT>
