<HEADLINE> Japan Cabinet To Dissolve Parliament  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The Cabinet of Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori on
Friday agreed to dissolve the lower house of Parliament, paving the
way for national elections on June 25.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was taken at a morning Cabinet meeting and was to
be finalized with the formal dissolution of the powerful body in
the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Support for Mori has plummeted since his remark last month that
Japan is a ''divine nation'' and recent polls suggest that his
administration is the least popular to face an election since the
end of the war.
</P>
<P>
   Mori has also been dogged by scandals since he assumed
leadership after his predecessor, Keizo Obuchi, fell into a coma in
April. Obuchi died May 14.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had initially expected a sizable sympathy vote for the
ruling coalition centered on Mori's Liberal Democratic Party after
Obuchi's death, but many now question whether the LDP will benefit.
June 25 would have been Obuchi's 63rd birthday.
</P>
</TEXT>
