<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru Election Protests Continue  </HEADLINE>
By RICK VECCHIO
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Defeated candidate Alejandro Toledo said
Thursday that he will continue pushing to disqualify President
Alberto Fujimori's re-election victory.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our goal is a new election in which Fujimori does not
participate,'' said Toledo, who boycotted Sunday's presidential
runoff. ''He's broken all the laws and the constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo, 54, said nationwide protests would continue, including d
march on Saturday in downtown Lima, followed by an all-night vigil
in front of the Organization of American States' local
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no need for a second election. This one was an
expression of the popular will,'' said Francisco Tudela, Fujimori's
vice-presidential running mate.
</P>
<P>
   The OAS permanent council decided Wednesday in Washington to
recommend that the controversy over the fairness of Peru's
presidential runoff be addressed in a meeting of OAS foreign
ministers scheduled to begin Sunday in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   But after intense debate, the council ruled against the United
States' suggestion that the issue be taken up in the context of a
1991 resolution designed to deal with threats to democracy. The
resolution gives the ministers broad authority to take punitive
action in such cases.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo called the OAS council's decision ''a great victory''
because Peru's representative at the meeting failed in her attempt
''to discredit the OAS election observer mission'' and ''close the
case on Peru.''
</P>
<P>
   OAS election monitors left Peru two days before the vote in
protest after Fujimori's government refused to delay the runoff to
ensure the reliability of ballot-counting software.
</P>
<P>
   Other international and local monitors did the same, pronouncing
the election and the campaign that led up to it unfairly biased in
favor of Fujimori.
</P>
<P>
   With Toledo boycotting the election, Fujimori, 61, won by a wide
margin. Final results announced Thursday gave Fujimori 51.2 percent
of the vote, compared to 17.7 percent for Toledo, who had asked his
supporter to spoil their ballots by marking them with the words
''no to fraud.''
</P>
</TEXT>
