<DOCNO> APW20000601.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UCLA's Sua Wins Discus Title  </HEADLINE>
By BERT ROSENTHAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- Even while training through the NCAA Outdoor
Track and Field Championships, UCLA's Seilala Sua was good enough
to win the women's discus Thursday and make meet history.
</P>
<P>
   Sua's triumph made her the first woman to win the same field
event four times. Wisconsin's Suzy Favor is the only other woman to
win the same event four times, the 1,500 meters from 1987-1990,
with her final victory also coming at Duke's Wallace Wade stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Sua, who will defend her shot put title Friday, also tied Favor
for the most overall outdoor NCAA titles by a woman. Favor also won
the 800 in 1990. Indoors and outdoors, Sua has six NCAA titles,
including this year's indoor shot put crown. Favor finished her
career with nine.
</P>
<P>
   Sua, the sixth-ranked discus thrower in the world last year and
the sixth-place finisher at the World Championships, was not
concentrating heavily on the NCAA meet because she is working
toward next month's Olympic trials and the Sydney Games in
September.
</P>
<P>
   Her coach, Art Venegas, thought the strategy might backfire.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't, although Sua, the two-time U.S. champion, was not at
her sharpest. After winning her previous three NCAA titles with
throws over 200 feet, she didn't pass that distance until her final
attempt, throwing 200-9.
</P>
<P>
   ''She hasn't reached her top gear yet,'' Venegas said. ''When
she does, it will be scary.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought by now she would be throwing 220 feet, but it's been
tough on her. She's not been as dominant as usual, because she
wasn't peaking for April, May or June like in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Venegas also had another reason for Sua's relatively mediocre
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the reasons she struggled so much was because of the
weight of doing something that isn't commonly done,'' he said.
''She's basically outgrown this level of competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Sua put it a little differently.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was very nervous on my first throw,'' she said, ''because
it's harder coming in as the favorite. I don't think it was
pressure to win. It was pressure to get a good throw.''
</P>
<P>
   In other finals, Brad Hauser led a 1-2-4 Stanford finish in the
men's 10,000, outkicking teammate Jason Balkman to win in 30
minutes, 38.57 seconds, the slowest winning time since 1956;
Christi Smith became the first NCAA champion from Akron, taking the
heptathlon with 5,797 points; Texas' Erin Aldrich won the women's
high jump at 6-2}; and LSU's Russ Buller took the men's pole vault
at 18-4{.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Joachim Olsen of Idaho won the men's shot put at 66-5};
Houston's Jenny Adams took the women's long jump at 21-5{; and
SMU's Libor Charfreitag won the men's hammer throw at 253-4,
breaking the 25-year-old stadium record and a distance that
qualified him for the Olympics for Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
   In the pedestrian 10,000, Stanford almost had its third
consecutive 1-2-3 finish, but Hauser's twin brother, Brent,
collapsed just before crossing the finish line and was overtaken by
Drake's Jason Lehmkuhle.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening round of the women's 100 hurdles, Ohio State's
Donica Merriman equaled the stadium record of 12.84 and matched the
fifth-fastest time in the world this year in winning her heat.
</P>
<P>
   Adams was another hurdles heat winner in 12.87, tying the
seventh-fastest time in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas' 1,600 relay team of Melvin Lister, Sam Glover, Ryan
Stanley and Kevin Baker ran the fastest time by a collegiate team
this year and the fifth-fastest in the world, winning its heat in a
school-record 3:02.02.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Razorbacks' chances of winning a ninth consecutive
title were damaged when shot putter Marcus Clavelle, projected
among the top three, and 10,000 runner Adam Dailey, one of the
favorites who was bumped onto the inside of the track while running
fourth, both failed to score.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' women also ran a sizzling 1,600 relay heat, winning with
the world's fourth-fastest time, 3:29.74, with a team of Angel
Patterson, Nakiya Johnson, Moushaumi Robinson and Tanya Jarrett.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina's Terrence Trammell, the world leader in the
men's 110 hurdles, easily won his opening heat in 13.61. Trammell,
also one of the favorites in the 100, ran 10.19 in his heat and
reached the semifinals despite competing with a sore left
hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   LSU's Derrick Brew, the second-fastest 400 runner in the world
this year, failed to advance to the final, running 45.79 in the
heats. World No. 1 Michael Blackwood of Oklahoma won his heat in
45.17.
</P>
<P>
   There also were surprises in the women's 800 heats, as Tracy
Robertson of Arkansas and Liz Diaz of Texas, considered among the
top contenders, did not advance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
