<DOCNO> APW20000601.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Musical giant Tito Puente dead at 77  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY McSHANE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Musical giant Tito Puente, the Grammy-winning
''El Rey'' of big-band mambo whose pioneering sound paved the way
for Latin musicians from Carlos Santana to Marc Anthony, has died
in Manhattan. He was 77.
</P>
<P>
   The flamboyant percussionist and bandleader, who had undergone
recent treatment for a heart ailment, died Wednesday at the New
York University Medical Center, said his agent, Eddie Rodriguez. At
his family's request, no other details were given.
</P>
<P>
   Decades before the current ''Latin explosion'' of Anthony, Ricky
Martin and Jennifer Lopez, Puente -- a contemporary of the late Desi
Arnaz -- was driving audiences to the dance floor with his animated
style and influential music. He created his own jazz by blending
Latin rhythm with the big band stylings of Tommy Dorsey or Count
Basie.
</P>
<P>
   Puente's star ascended across six decades. He earned five
Grammys as he recorded more than 100 albums in a career than began
at age 13. His most recent Grammy, best tropical Latin performance
for ''Mambo Birdland,'' came in February.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thank God for giving me the opportunity to know and care for
one of the most amazing men ever to walk the earth,'' said Anthony,
who first performed in Madison Square Garden at Puente's
invitation. He returned the favor in February, inviting Puente onto
his HBO special.
</P>
<P>
   Puente crossed over before anyone coined the expression,
collaborating with traditional jazz artists such as Dizzy Gillespie
and Lionel Hampton. He wrote the song ''Oye Como Va'' years before
it became an enormous rock hit for Santana.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Santana offered his condolences to the family and
said he was thankful to have been able to tell Puente himself how
much his work meant.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel very honored and grateful to have been touched by Tito
Puente's spirit and his monumental talent,'' Santana said in a
statement he issued from Duisburg, Germany. ''He helped open doors
for me as well as many other musicians.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, traveling in Berlin, said Puente was ''more
than a musician -- he was a trailblazer.'' He said Puente's
''countless recordings are classics in the genre he helped
define.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore also paid tribute to the late bandleader.
</P>
<P>
   Puente performed with various symphonies, and brought his band
to the White House for Presidents Carter, Reagan and Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But he also transcended music to enter pop culture. Bill
Murray's character in ''Stripes'' hailed Puente's musical genius,
as did television's Lisa Simpson. Puente performed the theme song
for ''The Cosby Show,'' and even played himself in the 1992 movie
''Mambo Kings.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Tito's life was like one of his solos -- he got all he could
out of it,'' said Bill Cosby, a friend and a fan, in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, he received a National Medal of Arts from Clinton -- one
of dozens of honors bestowed on Puente for both his musical prowess
and his ceaseless goodwill.
</P>
<P>
   The inestimable influence of the Harlem-born national treasure
was reflected in tributes offered by a variety of musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tito was for me more than family,'' said Cuban-born singer
Celia Cruz, a long-time friend and collaborator. ''Our world is in
mourning because one of the souls of Latin music has died.''
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Estefan, in a statement with husband Emilio, praised
Puente as ''a pioneer in the music industry ... an inspiration for
artists and music lovers alike.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tito said to us recently that his music was not only the story
of who he was, but also the pride and the passion of a people
rejoicing in who they are,'' the Estefans said. ''There are no
better words with which to say goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Anthony Puente Jr. was born April 20, 1923, in Harlem
Hospital, the oldest child of a a factory foreman and his wife.
Initially, Puente was a Fred Astaire-styled dancer; a serious ankle
injury in a bicycle accident refocused his attention on music.
</P>
<P>
   Puente quickly took to percussion, beating rhythms on boxes or
the windowsill and playing his first semi-pro gig at age 13 in a
local club.
</P>
<P>
   The high school dropout was soon playing the timbale with the
Machito Orchestra, a group that had successfully merged the Big
Band sound with a Latin beat.
</P>
<P>
   Puente developed a flamboyant style and convinced the band
leader to move the timbales -- a pair of single-headed drums mounted
on stands and played with sticks -- from the back of the band to the
front.
</P>
<P>
   From his new spot, Puente became the center of attention:
wide-eyed, animated and constantly moving. He reveled in his work
as the consummate showman.
</P>
<P>
   After a three-year stint in the Navy during World War II, Puente
took courses at the famed Juilliard School of Music. He then
arranged and worked with other bands until finally debuting his
own, the Tito Puente Orchestra, in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   When the '50s mambo craze swept the states, Puente's fame soared
and he became a regular headliner at the New York Palladium. He
moved to Hollywood in the '60s, working with the biggest Latino
stars: Cruz, Ray Barretto, Mongo Santamaria.
</P>
<P>
   Over the decades, the hard-working Puente became an
international star, taking his band around the world. In 1992, his
100th album -- ''The Mambo King 100th LP'' -- was nominated for a
Grammy.
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 three-CD career retrospective, ''50 Years of Swing,''
included a cut from his 1946 debut ''El Rey del Mambo'' (''The King
of the Mambo'').
</P>
<P>
   ''The excitement of the rhythms and the beat make people
happy,'' he said in a 1997 Associated Press interview. ''We try to
get our feelings to the people, so they enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Puente was released May 2 from a San Juan, Puerto Rico, hospital
after two days of treatment for an irregular heartbeat. He canceled
all his events in May, including three concerts planned with the
Symphonic Orchestra of Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Puente is survived by his wife, Margie, two sons and a daughter,
said his agent. Memorial services were planned for Sunday and
Monday in Manhattan, with a funeral Tuesday morning in Nanuet.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
