<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAndrew Faulds:
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Andrew Faulds, who displayed an actor's flair as a
member of the House of Commons for three decades, died Wednesday.
He was 77.
</P>
<P>
   His devotion to issues such as the Palestinian cause and his
attack in 1973 on ''Zionists in the Labor Party'' ruled out his
advancement in the Labor Party hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   After Rhodesia proclaimed its independence in 1965, Faulds
demanded that white leader Ian Smith be executed. He was also among
the few Labor members of Parliament who spoke out against the
military campaign to retake the Falkland Islands from Argentina in
1982.
</P>
<P>
   Faulds was elected to Parliament in 1966 and retired in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Before taking up politics, Faulds had roles in about three dozen
films and played Jet Morgan in the radio adventure series,
''Journey into Space.''
R. Loudon Kelly:
</P>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Longtime newsman R. Loudon Kelly, a 23-year
veteran of The Associated Press, died May 26. He was 94.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly worked for the Denver Rocky Mountain News during the
1930s, where he was a film critic, crime beat reporter and sports
reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Later he worked for the AP in Denver as news editor, and in Salt
Lake City, where he was the bureau chief.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly also is survived by a son and four grandchildren.
Themba Khoza:
</P>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- Themba Khoza, a leader of the
Zulu-based Inkatha Freedom Party who allegedly organized deadly
attacks on ANC rivals in the 1990s, died Sunday of AIDS. He was 41.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his death, Khoza -- a member of parliament -- was
awaiting trial on 19 charges, including attempted murder, inciting
violence and gunrunning. The charges stem from attacks on African
National Congress supporters during bloody factional fighting in
the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people died in the undeclared war between the IFP
and the ANC, which led the struggle against white rule, in the
run-up to South Africa's first all-race elections in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The attempted murder charges against Khoza stemmed from an
attack on two African National Congress members in 1990 at Ermelo,
east of Johannesburg. He also was implicated in alleged gunrunning
on two occasions.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1994 elections, Khoza served in a national committee
that worked toward ending hostilities. He was elected to national
parliament in the 1994 elections and was re-elected in the June
1999 election.
Mary Langston:
</P>
<P>
   MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- Mary Langston, who for years cooked Elvis
Presley's peanut butter and banana sandwiches, died Tuesday of
complications from a stroke. She was 78.
</P>
<P>
   Langston cooked for the King of Rock 'n' Roll for 14 years and
continued working for his family for 12 years after he died in
1977.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, under her maiden name, Jenkins, Langston wrote a book
about her experiences with Presley called ''Memories Beyond
Graceland Gates.''
</P>
<P>
   In it, she said Presley returned from a concert tour in 1972 and
told her about a fried peanut butter and banana sandwich he had
eaten while on the road. Langston said it took her three tries to
get the sandwich to Presley's satisfaction, and then she cooked
them for him the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Presley died at age 42 of heart disease worsened by drug abuse.
Jack Lloyd:
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Jack Lloyd, a writer and columnist for The
Philadelphia Inquirer for more than 30 years, died Sunday of a
heart attack. He was 66.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote about pop culture, entertainment, jazz and the Atlantic
City performance scene.
</P>
<P>
   When Frank Sinatra released a comeback album in the 1970s, Lloyd
gave it such good reviews that Sinatra, who had a stormy
relationship with the press, asked to meet with him when he visited
the area.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, he is survived by two children and a
brother.
Petar Mladenov:
</P>
<P>
   SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) -- Petar Mladenov, who served under
Bulgaria's longtime communist strongman Todor Zhivkov and then
helped oust him before becoming president, died Wednesday following
a long illness. He was 64.
</P>
<P>
   Mladenov served 18 years as foreign minister under Zhivkov. In
1977 he became a member of the policy-making Politburo.
</P>
<P>
   The end of hard-line communist rule in Bulgaria came in a
Communist Party coup in which reform-minded comrades ousted
Zhivkov.
</P>
<P>
   Mladenov and former Prime Minister Andrei Lukanov helped shape
the reformist group, under the influence of then Soviet-leader
Mikhail Gorbachev's ''perestroika.''
</P>
<P>
   Mladenov became president in November 1989, overseeing the
party's formal break with Stalinism. He resigned in July 1990,
bowing to pressure by the anti-communist opposition after he
allegedly suggested that tanks be used to stop anti-government
demonstrators.
Tito Puente:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Tito Puente, the exuberant percussionist and
bandleader who rose to stardom during the mambo craze of the 1950s
and paved the way for Latin musicians from Carlos Santana to Marc
Anthony, died Wednesday. He was 77.
</P>
<P>
   Decades before the current ''Latin explosion,'' Puente -- a
contemporary of Desi Arnaz -- was driving audiences to the dance
floor with his wide-eyed, energetic style and influential sound. He
created his own jazz by blending Latin rhythm with the Big Band
stylings of Tommy Dorsey and Count Basie.
</P>
<P>
   In a six-decade career that began at age 13, the New York City
native recorded more than 100 albums and won five Grammys. His most
recent Grammy, best tropical Latin performance for ''Mambo
Birdland,'' came in February.
</P>
<P>
   Puente crossed over before anyone coined the expression,
collaborating with jazz artists such as Dizzy Gillespie and Lionel
Hampton. He wrote the song ''Oye Como Va'' years before it became
an enormous rock hit for Carlos Santana.
</P>
<P>
   Puente performed with various symphonies and brought his band to
the White House for Presidents Carter, Reagan and Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, his 100th album -- ''The Mambo King 100th LP'' -- was
nominated for a Grammy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Puente received a National Medal of Arts from President
Clinton.
Jonas Rosenfield:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Jonas Rosenfield, former president of the
American Film Marketing Association, died Wednesday. He was 84.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfield helped independent film producers compete with major
studios by developing the American Film Market, a cheaper
alternative to the Cannes Film Festival held in Santa Monica,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue from the sale of English-language films abroad climbed
steadily under Rosenfield, reaching $1.8 billion in the last fiscal
year before his retirement in 1998.
Johnnie Taylor:
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Soul legend Johnnie Taylor, whose 1976 ''Disco
Lady'' was a hit on the dance floor and on the pop charts, died
Wednesday of an apparent heart attack. He was 62.
</P>
<P>
   The Crawfordsville, Ark., native was nicknamed the ''Philosopher
of Soul'' by Memphis' Stax Records.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was a protege of Sam Cooke and took over the Soul
Stirrers after Cooke left gospel for rhythm and blues in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, Taylor scored his first number one on the R&AMP;B charts
with ''Who's Making Love,'' his first million-seller, followed by a
steady run of other hits. When Stax went bankrupt in 1975, Taylor
signed to Columbia Records and had his biggest commercial success
with ''Disco Lady.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
