<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Whales Die After Beaching  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Nearly 80 whales died after beaching
themselves on Mexico's southeastern coast, officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A group of 98 whales worked their way onto the shores of a
nature reserve in the Yucatan peninsula on Wednesday, said Ramiro
Rubio, the director of the reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities launched a rescue effort and were able to bring 22
to deeper waters but 76 died, said Rubio.
</P>
<P>
   Officials were taking samples from the animals and the water to
determine what might have led to the beachings.
</P>
<P>
   This particular species, known as false killer whales, is prone
to beaching itself, Rubio said, who heads the Ria Lagartos
Biosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Officials buried the corpses to prevent any damage their
decomposition might cause to the ecosystem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
