<DOCNO> APW20000601.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> LSU Female Athletes Gain Victory  </HEADLINE>
By BRETT MARTEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- In a victory for female athletes seeking
damages from LSU, a panel of federal appeals court judges refused
to reverse their position that the school intentionally denied
female students equal access to athletics.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel of the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
initially ruled on the matter in January, then reconsidered the
case in light of new arguments by LSU. But on Thursday, the judges
ruled that those arguments lacked merit to overturn any part of the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling reopens the possibility for lead plaintiff attorney
Nancy Rafuse of Atlanta to include thousands of present and former
LSU female student-athletes in a class-action lawsuit against
Louisiana's largest public university.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the case does not become a class action, the five
initial plaintiffs still may seek damages, Rafuse said.
</P>
<P>
   The case dates to 1994, when three female soccer players said
the school's refusal to offer them varsity status and the funding
that goes with it violated Title IX of the 1972 Education Amendment
Act.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, U.S. District Judge Rebecca Doherty ruled that LSU was
not in violation.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the lawsuit was expanded to include two softball players
and, while it was pending, LSU added varsity women's soccer and
softball. This time, a judge ordered LSU to submit a plan for Title
IX compliance but ruled the school had not intentionally
discriminated against the female athletes. The judge also denied
class-action status for the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   But in January, the federal appeals panel reversed that ruling,
saying the discrimination was intentional and that the district
court judge must hold further proceedings on whether the lawsuit
can proceed as a class-action.
</P>
<P>
   In asking the appeals court to reconsider the issue, LSU sought
to prove not only that its actions were not intentional, but also
that the state university was immune from paying damages under
state sovereignty clauses in the U.S. Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the appeals court said LSU dropped its immunity
when it accepted federal education funding.
</P>
<P>
   ''As best I can tell it's the same end result going back to
district court to decide some more issues,'' Rafuse said. ''I'm
happy to see the court did not need to look at immunity issue.''
</P>
<P>
   LSU athletic department spokesman Herb Vincent said the
university will not comment until its lawyer has an opportunity to
study the opinion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
