<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, June 1, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Court Denies Asylum In Elian Case
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- A federal appeals court sided with the government today and
denied an asylum hearing for Elian Gonzalez -- a ruling that could send the
6-year-old shipwreck survivor back to Cuba with his father within weeks. The
unanimous ruling from a three-judge panel of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals blocked Elian from leaving the country immediately and gave his Miami
relatives two weeks to appeal -- either to the full appeals court or the Supreme
Court. Family lawyer Kendall Coffey said he hadn't decided on a course of
action.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Warned On Missile Defense
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Displaying a new sense of boldness in dealing with Germany's
staunchest postwar ally, Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder warned President Clinton
on Thursday not to start another arms race with a proposed new national missile
defense system. Washington's proposal to build the system -- a scaled-down
version of the shield against incoming ballistic missiles once championed by
President Reagan in the 1980s -- represents for many Germans the most serious
split in thinking with the United States since the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Little Progress In Mideast Talks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LISBON, Portugal (AP) -- Israel and the Palestinians have little to show for
six months of peace treaty talks, and time is running out for President Clinton
to produce a deal that has become increasingly elusive. Instead of negotiating,
Israelis and Palestinians have been engaging in name-calling and accusing each
other of foot-dragging and intransigence. Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
spent much of his meeting with Clinton on Thursday in Lisbon complaining that
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat was not making a serious effort to reach an
agreement.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush, In First, Grants Reprieve
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) -- With less than a half-hour before a convicted
killer's scheduled execution tonight, George W. Bush approved his first reprieve
in a Texas death penalty case. Bush issued a 30-day reprieve for Ricky McGinn
who was set to die for killing his 12-year-old stepdaughter seven years ago.
Bush has allowed 131 lethal injections over his 5{ years as governor of the
nation's busiest execution state.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gov't Names 12 To Drug Kingpin List
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House today put 12 suspected international drug
kingpins on a new U.S. government blacklist aimed at financially isolating
traffickers and their associates. The list contained no surprises. Most, if not
all, of the suspects named were already under indictment. The list consisted of
six Mexicans, a Burmese warlord, a Chinese national operating in Southeast Asia,
two from St. Kitts-Nevis and two from Nigeria. The White House submitted the
list to Congress late today, meeting a June 1 deadline set in a law enacted last
year.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Trial Lawyers Give to Campaigns
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With two major bills to limit lawsuits heading for the
Senate floor, trial lawyers in April contributed $508,000 to Democratic Senate
campaigns. The Houston law firm of Williams Bailey donated $250,000 of the total
raised from trial lawyers in unregulated soft money during April by the
Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee. The committee took in $300,000 at a
fund-raiser in Savannah, Ga., during an Association of Trial Lawyers of America
conference. Senate Republicans also are collecting money from special interests
awaiting action on legislation. The railroad industry in April contributed
$185,000 to the National Republican Senatorial Committee.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Actor Swayze OK After Crash Landing
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PRESCOTT VALLEY, Ariz. (AP) -- A small plane piloted by actor Patrick Swayze
crashed today while he was trying to make an emergency landing on a dirt road in
central Arizona. Swayze was not injured. Swayze was flying a 1978 twin-engine
Cessna 414A from Van Nuys, Calif., to Las Vegas, N.M., when he was forced to
attempt an emergency landing, said John Clabes, a spokesman for the Federal
Aviation Administration. Swayze's spokeswoman Annett Wolf in Los Angeles
confirmed Swayze had made an emergency landing and that he was not seriously
hurt.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei Stock Average gained 139.29 points to 16,833.59 in
the first 30 minutes of trading. In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average
rose 129.87 points to 10,652.20 at Thursday's close. The Nasdaq composite index
gained 181.59 points to finish at 3,582.50.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Royals Defeat Red Sox 13-11
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Dave McCarty capped a wild game with his fourth hit, a two-run
triple in the eighth inning, as the Kansas City Royals had their best offensive
game of the season in a 13-11 win over the Boston Red Sox tonight. The Royals,
who trailed 8-2 after five innings, rallied with nine runs in a crazy sixth
inning that saw the teams combine for 12 runs, 12 hits and four walks as 22
batters faced 78 pitches.
</P>
