<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 23:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peacekeepers Enter S. Leone Battle  </HEADLINE>
By CLARENCE ROY-MACAULAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- U.N. peacekeepers will not be
dragged into an offensive war in Sierra Leone despite signs the
country's rebels are massing ahead of a pullout of British troops,
a U.N. official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Many Sierra Leoneans, terrified of a possible rebel attack on
the capital, Freetown, have pleaded for a strong military response
by the international community. So far, the U.N. peacekeeping
mission, known as UNAMSIL, has used force infrequently, and only
when attacked.
</P>
<P>
   ''UNAMSIL is not going to be involved in the fighting,'' U.N.
spokesman David Wimhurst said, but added ''We have no intention of
pulling out if the rebels should advance toward the city. We will
defend the civilian population if they are in danger.''
</P>
<P>
   Wimhurst said the beleaguered peacekeeping force was pinning its
hopes on a regional diplomatic initiative to negotiate a
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   The world body is still recovering from an incident last month
when the rebels took about 500 U.N. personnel hostage, holding them
several weeks before freeing them.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolutionary United Front rebels killed tens of thousands
of civilians and intentionally maimed many more during eight years
of civil war.
</P>
<P>
   In early May, the RUF abandoned a peace accord signed last July,
seizing the U.N. captives and advancing to within 25 miles of
Freetown. Pro-government forces, with the help of British military
advisers and equipment, have since been pushing the rebels back
from the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The government campaign was set back Wednesday when its forces
were driven from Lunsar, some 60 miles east of Freetown, just days
after they captured the strategic town from the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said Lunsar was in the
hands of the RUF following heavy fighting with the Sierra Leone
army.
</P>
<P>
   The pullout from Lunsar came after a heavy, eight-hour gunbattle
there, U.N. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, U.N. troops shot dead a suspected fuel thief after he
and two others opened fire on the peacekeepers in Freetown's port
overnight, Eckhard said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-01-00 2304 </TRAILER>
