<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forced Repatriations Worry U.S.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP)-- The United States has expressed concern to
Chinese officials about the forced repatriation of North Korean
refugees, the State Department said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Philip Reeker said the administration supports the
U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees in his opposition to such
repatriations. The UNHCR contends the repatriations are a violation
of international law because the North Koreans face persecution on
their return.
</P>
<P>
   ''We take human rights extremely seriously, and expect all
members of the international community to abide by the guiding
principles of the U.N. Charter as well as the 1951 convention on
refugees and the Universal Declaration of Human Rights,'' Reeker
said.
</P>
<P>
   Reeker said estimates of the number of North Koreans who have
fled to China range up to the hundreds of thousands.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are deeply concerned about the desperate situation many
North Koreans face,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
