<HEADLINE> Thunderstorms Wreak Havoc in Wis.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRON RIDGE, Wis. (AP) -- Thunderstorms packing heavy rain and
strong winds pounded Minnesota and Wisconsin on Thursday, sending
rivers out of their banks and destroying homes in this southeast
Wisconsin community. At least one tornado was reported.
</P>
<P>
   Straight-line winds that struck about 6 p.m. knocked down four
homes and damaged several others in Iron Ridge, Dodge County
Sheriff's Lt. Glenn Welles said.
</P>
<P>
   A tornado touched down in southwest Wisconsin, damaging several
homes in Cataract, and 100 mph winds overturned cars and trucks on
Interstates 90 and 94 near Camp Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   In Gays Mills, near the Iowa border, two dozen families were
evacuated from their homes when the Kickapoo River spilled its
banks.
</P>
<P>
   ''All the streets are blocked off by emergency vehicles, and
crews are getting ready to fill sandbags,'' said Bob Monk of the
Salvation Army of La Crosse, which set up a shelter for the
displaced families. ''It's an eery feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Flooding along the Pecatonica River shut down a highway bridge
into Darlington, cutting off access to the southwest Wisconsin city
from the south.
</P>
<P>
   ''You just can't get across the river until it goes down,'' said
Deputy Jim Jacobson with the Lafayette County Sheriff's Department
said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service reported the Pecatonica River at
15.57 feet in Darlington early Thursday, about 4{ feet above flood
stage. The river was expected to crest at 17 feet early Friday, a
level that could cause major flooding.
</P>
<P>
   In parts of Minnesota, up to 5 inches of rain flooded
communities and caused creeks to spill from their banks.
</P>
<P>
   The heaviest rain fell late Wednesday and early Thursday near
the Iowa border, with the town of Harmony receiving 5.71 inchesin a
24-hour period, said Pete Boulay, an assistant state climatologist.
</P>
<P>
   In Spring Valley, about 100 miles southeast of Minneapolis,
residents of 25 homes were evacuated as the usually slow-moving
Spring Valley Creek turned into a torrent more than 200 feet wide
in some places.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was just like a wall of water that came through,'' said Jim
Cooper, Spring Valley emergency management coordinator. ''It
happened so fast that we were not able to get in and sandbag.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Weather Service, http://www.crh.noaa.gov/grb/
</P>
</TEXT>
