<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Reimbursement Plan Under Fire  </HEADLINE>
By JAMES JEFFERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- A lawyer for Wal-Mart argued Thursday
that Arkansas' plan to pay big chain pharmacies less than small
drug stores for filling Medicaid prescriptions was a blatant move
to curry political favor with the independents.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's largest retailer is suing its home state to void
implementation of a two-tiered method for reimbursing pharmacies
for providing medicine to Arkansas' poor, elderly and disabled.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge G. Thomas Eisele heard the one-day
trial Thursday and said he would rule next week. Wal-Mart Stores
Inc. is not seeking damages.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Human Services, which oversees Medicaid,
implemented its policy April 28 as part of a plan to save $4.5
million from spiraling drug costs. Officials said they also hoped
to minimize losses for small drug stores that provide extras such
as prescription delivery and service to nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart contends the policy is unjustified and discriminatory.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart lawyer Bill Coston said that a May 1999 memo suggested
the DHS based its plan on politics, not prudence. In the memo, Ray
Hanley, DHS director of Medical Services, suggests to Director Kurt
Knickrehm that a plan that protected independent drug stores might
work politically.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not a scheme to rip off the big boys,'' Knickrehm said
during a break in the trial. ''What it protects is the access that
we need to have for Medicaid clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart, a $100 billion retail giant, estimates its Medicaid
prescription losses at $1 million annually if the new policy
stands.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a matter of principle, we don't support what they're
doing,'' Wal-Mart spokeswoman Jessica Moser said.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome could have implications for some poor communities in
the state. Walgreens, which has located some of its 13 Arkansas
stores in lower-income neighborhoods with high Medicaid traffic,
has also filed a lawsuit against the state and threatened to pull
out of the Medicaid program rather than accept a lower
reimbursement.
</P>
</TEXT>
